Ateuchus is a diverse genus, with over 90 species, distributed from the USA to Argentina, and the Antilles. There are several taxonomic and nomenclatural problems, and many species to describe.

The genus Ontherus was revised by Génier (1996). Its consists approximately of 60 species that are distributed throughout continental tropical and subtropical Latin America. However, the greater diversity of the group occurs in southeastern Brazil and the Andes (Génier 1996). The species that compose the genus are divided into three subgenera: Caelontherus, Planontherus and Ontherus.

According to Edmonds and Zidek (2010), the Neotropical genus Coprophanaeus Olsoufieff (1924) is currently represented by 38 species, distributed among three subgenera (Megaphanaeus Olsoufieff, Metallophanaeus Olsoufieff, and Coprophanaeus s. str.) and eight species groups. According to Edmonds and Zidek (2010), Coprophanaeus corythus (Harold), formerly regarded as a subspecies of C. telamon (Erichson), assumes species status.

Published data: This species has two subspecies:  Hyporhamphus roberti hildebrandi and Hyporhamphus roberti roberti.
Jamaica Caribbean Workshop:Early records of Hyporhamphus roberti from continental United States refer to either H. meeki or H. unifasciatus.

Two other common and very similar species of western Atlantic Strongylura occur alongside Strongylura marina in the Western Central Atlantic: Strongylura notata and Strongylura timucu. Until the late 1960s, S. timucu was largely considered to be synonymous with S. marina (Berry and Rivas 1962). Collette (1968) notes that S. notata differs from S. marina and S. timucu in having fewer anal rays and fewer predorsal scales, and internal examination also reveals fewer vertebrae and other distinguishing skeletal features. Internal examination also reveals that both gonads are developed in S. tumucu while only the right gonad is developed in S. marina. Typically, S. timucu is also somewhat darker in coloration than S. marina (Hoese and Moore 1977). Strongylura notata differs externally from S. marina, possessing 13-15 dorsal rays and 13-16 anal rays (Hoese and Moore 1977).
The type locality for this species is Mexico. No subspecies are formally recognized for the taxon.

Some taxonomic sources have elevated the subgenus Heraclides to species level (e.g. Hancock 1983, Warren et al. 2016); however, molecular studies on Papilio phylogeny (e.g. Aubert et al. 1999, Caterino and Sperling 1999) showed that there was little support for this. Additional ongoing work has come to the same conclusion that there is no evidence for splitting Papilio into several subgenera (F. Sperling and F. Condamine pers. comm. March 2020).

The American Snout (Libytheana carinenta) has several subspecies: L. c. carinenta, L. c.mexicana, L. c. streckeri, L. c. larvata, and L. c. bachmanii (the Mexican Snout); the latter was formerly recognised as a separate species, Libytheana bachmanii (Warren et al. 2016).
This species is split into several subspecies across its range (Scott 1986).

Records of eastern Atlantic Myliobatis aquila from southern Brazil probably refer to this species, if both species are indeed distinct (if not, the name M. aquila has priority). There are two sister species in the southern part of its range under the present name M. goodei, with a description of the second species pending (Ruocco et al. 2012).

This species can be visually distinguished from two morphologically similar regional congeners, the Dusky Smoothhound (Mustelus canis) and the Gulf of Mexico Smoothhound (M. sinusmexicanus) by several characters including fin shape and ampullary pore patterns (Giresi et al. 2013).
The Bignose Shark is morphologically distinct but genetically similar to the Sandbar Shark (Carcharhinus plumbeus) (Naylor et al. 2012, Duffy and Struthers 2017).
Last et al. (2016a) revised the genus Rhinobatos, transferring glaucostigma, horkelii, lentiginosus, leucorhynchus, percellens, planiceps, prahli, and productus to the new genus Pseudobatos.

Parachromis loisellei was recently synonymized with P. friedrichsthalii in Catalog of Fishes (Fricke et al. 2019). However, taxonomic uncertainty may result in future changes to the current species concept.

The validity of Sicydium multipunctatum has been previously questioned (Chabarria and Pezold 2013, Gonzalez-Murcia and Alvarez 2018). Inclusion of S. multipunctatum as a synonym under S. salvini would likely warrant reassessment.

Archosargus probatocephalus is subdivided into three subspecies by some authors: A. probatocephalus probatocephalus for the northern form from Nova Scotia to Cedar Key on the west coast of Florida; A. probatocephalus oviceps Ginsburg (which is associated with muddy bottoms) in the Gulf of Mexico from St. Harks, Florida to the Campeche Bank; and A. probatocephalus aries from Belize to Bahia de Sepetiba, Brazil (Carpenter 2002).

The Chesapeake Bay Sheepshead population is suggested to constitute a separate population, as large differences in vital rates are often indicative of this. The differences observed in growth could arise due to a variety of factors, including differences in mortality rates, environmental conditions, food sources, or genetic variation (Ballenger et al. 2007).

Frequency distributions of each of five meristic counts are significantly different between the subspecies found in the northeastern Gulf of Mexico: A. probatocephalus probatocephalus and A. probatocephalus oviceps (P < 0.05). However, Bayesian structure analysis of microsatellite genotypes indicated that all Gulf of Mexico Sheepshead populations constitute a single stock.Variance partitioning of mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) haplotypes suggests significant but limited divergence between subspecies (genetic differentiation index FST = 0.036, P < 0.005). Molecular data from North American subspecies of  Sheepshead indicate very limited genetic subdivision between the subspecies despite considerable divergence of morphological characters. Genetic structure is defined primarily by the geographic distance between sampling locales from the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic. Overall, Sheepshead molecular genetic data indicate very limited genetic subdivision between the subspecies despite considerable divergence of morphological characters (Anderson et al. 2008).

Vigna luteola (Jacq.) Benth. is a genepool tertiary wild relative of both Bambara Groundnut [Vigna subterranea (L.) Verdc. var. subterranea (L.) Verdc.] and Cowpea [Vigna unguiculata (L.) Walp. var. unguiculata (L.) Walp.]. The species is also classified in Taxon Group 2 of Bambara Groundnut and Taxon Group 3 of Cowpea (Vincent et al. 2013), following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).

The species has also been recently placed in the typhlopid genera Typhlops and Typhlina see Wallach (2009) for a complete synonymy.

Following Wallach (2009), Typhlops khoratensis is considered a junior synonym of Indotyphlops braminus. Typhlops fletcheri has widely been treated as a junior synonym of Indotyphlops braminus, but examination of the holotype suggests that it is likely to represent a distinct species (A. Wynn pers. comm. to P. Uetz, in Uetz 2019). It is treated as valid (as I. fletcheri) without comment by Hedges et al. (2014), but as it has not been formally resurrected this account follows Pyron and Wallach (2014) in retaining it within I. braminus pending further taxonomic research.

Some authorities treat Schoenoplectus tabernaemontani as a subspecies of S. lacustris (e.g., Sell and Murrell 1996, Castroviejo et al. 2008) while others (such as TROPICOS) maintain it within Scirpus. In Euro-Med checklist this is treated as a synony of S. lacustris subsp. glaucus (Sm.) Bech (Euro+Med PlantBase). 

Schoenoplectus tabernaemontani hybridises with S. triqueter (L.) Palla and S. lacustris, however neither is sufficiently frequent to affect the Red List assessment for this species (Jermy et al. 2007, Lansdown and Rumsey 2020).

The nomenclature of the bonefish family Albulidae is currently in a state of revision. Some Brazilian specimens of Chilomycterus antillarum are intermediate in colour between the crisp, dark hexagonal pattern typical of the species and the dark background with vague lighter spots typical of C. spinosus spinosus. The significance of this is unknown, and further investigation is required (Leis 2006).

The nomenclature of the bonefish family Albulidae is currently in a state of revision. Until recently, bonefish were considered to be comprised of two species, the circumglobal Albula vulpes and the western Atlantic and eastern Pacific Albula nemoptera; however, new molecular genetic information indicates that there are at least eight morphologically indistinguishable, but genetically distinct species (Colborn et al. 2001). Wallace and Tringali (2010) have recently found nine distinct species.

Elops saurus was recently split into two largely allopatric species, E. saurus and E. smithi (McBride et al. 2010). In Florida waters, E. saurus and E. smithi may occur sympatrically at early life stages, though this does not appear to persist into the adult stage (McBride and Horodysky 2004).  E. saurus and E. smithi can be differentiated by myomere or vertebral counts;  the more northern E. saurus is characterized by a higher count while the more southern E. smithi exhibits a lower count (Smith 1989, McBride and Horodysky 2004, McBride et al. 2010). These phenotypic differences are corroborated by genetic data (McBride et al. 2010). The sequence divergence in mtDNA cytochrome b (d = 0.023-0.029) between E. smithi and E. saurus is similar to or greater than that measured between recognized species of Elops in different ocean basins (McBride et al. 2010). We recommend the vernacular name Malacho, which is already used for Elops in several countries bordering the Caribbean basin." (McBride et al. 2010; see 'etymology').
Some authors suggest this species should be classified in the genus Lutjanus.

Starksia atlantica is a species complex. The original species was divided into Starksia atlantica (Bahamas and Turks and Caicos), S. sangreyae (Belize) and S. springeri (Curacao) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

Starksia sangreyae was originally known as S. atlantica, now shown to be a species complex comprised of S. atlantica (Bahamas and Turks and Caicos), S. sangreyae (Belize) and S. springeri (Curacao) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

Starksia lepicoelia is a species complex. The original species was divided into S. lepicoelia (Bahamas and Turks and Caicos), S. weigti (Belize), S. williamsi (Saba Bank, Netherlands Antilles) and S. robertsoni (Panama) (Baldwin et al. 2011). Baldwin et al. (2011) did not sample populations in the Gulf of Mexico and the taxonomic status of that population needs to be confirmed with DNA barcode data (R. Robertson and B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2015).

Starksia weigti was previously known as S. lepicoelia, which is now known to be a species complex comprised of: S. lepicoelia (Bahamas and Turks and Caicos), S. weigti (Belize), S. williamsi (Saba Bank, Netherland Antilles), and S. robertsoni (Panama) (Baldwin et al. 2011). The taxonomic status of the Campeche Bank (Gulf of Mexico) population needs to be confirmed with DNA barcode data (R. Robertson and B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2015).
Starksia sluiteri is a species complex. The original species was divided into S. sluiteri (Curacao), S. greenfieldi (Tobago, Trinidad and Tobago) and S. langi (Belize) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

Previously, Starksia langi was known as S. sluiteri, which is now a species complex. The original species has been divided into S. sluiteri (Curacao), S. greenfieldi (Tobago, Trinidad and Tobago) and S. langi (Belize) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

Kaupichthys hyoproroides was previously known as a highly variable, circumglobal species. Recent studies show that the western Pacific distribution is K. japonicus and K. diodontus is known from islands of the central Pacific. The western Atlantic and western Indian Ocean distributions are currently in place for K. hyoproroides, however, these distributions may represent a cryptic species pair. Studies are underway to resolve this taxonomic issue. Until this is published, we accept current taxonomy of this species (K. Tighe pers comm. 2011).

The northern subspecies, Anolis lemurinus bourgeaei, has sometimes been treated as a full species. Anolis rhombifer was synonymized within A. lemurinus by Fitch and Seigel (1984).

This is considered to be a complex consisting of at least three species, with the available names Anolis nannodes Cope, 1864 (Chiapas to northern Nicaragua) and A. intermedius Peters, 1863 (Costa Rica) available for populations outside the Atlantic versant of Veracruz (G. Köhler pers. comm. 2012). The complicated status of these names and of others currently included within the synonymy of A. laeviventris remains to be fully resolved, and this assessment follows Uetz et al. (2019) in retaining a traditional concept of A. laeviventris pending a taxonomic revision.

Anolis damulus, described based on vague characters, is of uncertain provenance and identity (S. Poe pers. comm. 2011). The description does not indicate a type locality, but later workers have assumed a locality in Mexico. If this provenance is correct, it may be conspecific with the apparently similar Anolis rodriguezii or another common Mexican anole, but examination of the holotype is needed to clarify this (S. Poe pers. comm. 2011). A museum specimens referred to this species exists from Oaxaca, but it is presently unclear how this specimen relates to the holotype, and so whether the two represent the same species (L. Mahler pers. comm. 2019).

Anolis sericeus sensu lato has recently been split by Köhler and Vesely (2010) into three species based on hemipenial and dewlap characters. Poe et al. (2017) treated the enigmatic taxon Anolis williamsi, described from Brazil probably in error (Uetz et al. 2019), as a tentative junior synonym of A. sericeus. Conversely, M. Rodrigues (unpubl.) suspects A. williamsi is likely to be a junior synonym of A. fuscoauratus (L. Mahler pers. comm. 2019) Köhler (2012) synonymized A. cumingi within A. sericeus.

A historical record from Half Moon Cay in Belize attributed to the closely-related Anolis carolinensis probably represents this species (L. Mahler pers. comm. October 2011), and further surveys on this island have never recorded A. carolinensis here (Lee 2000). Further studies are needed into the populations on the islands of Belize which may warrant species status. This may also be true for the Mexican populations.

Armstead et al. (2017) removed Anolis parvauritus from southern Colombia and northern Ecuador from synonymy with A. biporcatus. These authors expressed "little doubt" that the resulting concept of A. biporcatus is a species complex which will need more extensive geographic sampling to resolve.
There is a single record of this species in Mexico that is based on a misidentified Clelia scytalina. It is not thought to occur in Mexico.

In Venezuela, the name "speciosus" is used for convenience, but the taxon known as Gymnophthalmus speciosus in South America is not the same taxon present in Central America, to which the name G. speciosus is properly applicable (Ugueto and Rivas-Fuenmayor 2010, Vanzolini and Carvalho 1991, Carvalho 1997). This assessment encompasses the species complex as presently understood, including populations from Colombia and Venezuela. Records from southern Apure state in Venezuela represent an undescribed taxon in the process of being described (G. Rivas pers. comm. 2016), and are excluded from this account.
This is part of a species complex. Taxonomic work is underway to resolve this complex.

Campbell (1998) considered Leptodeira septentrionalis polysticta (southern Mexico to Costa Rica) to be a distinct species, however considered that it may be conspecific with L. s. ornata of lower Central America and South America. Lee (2000) retained polysticta as a subspecies of  L. septentrionalis, and this scheme is followed here.
Leptophis santamartensis is considered a junior synonym of L. ahaetulla occidentalis (Albuquerque et al. 2012).
This species has often been placed in the genus Dryadophis, but Dixon and Tipton (2004) placed it in Mastigodryas on the basis of seniority.

A recent molecular phylogenetic analysis covering northern populations of Oxybelis aeneus (from North America to Panama) found three distinct clades in this area, all of which differed from a fourth clade from Trinidad and Tobago (Jadin et al. 2019). These authors refrain from taking taxonomic action pending the results of ongoing research incorporating both molecular and morphological data across the full distribution of this species complex (Jadin et al. in preparation), and suspect that additional cryptic species will be recognized as a result of this work.

This species and Oxyrhopus petola, both originally described by Linnaeus (1758), have long been recognized to be synonymous. Savage (2011) investigated the complex nomenclatural history of this taxon, and determined O. petolarius to be the correct name for this species.

Based on patterns of multilocus isozyme variation, Mendoza-Quijano et al. (1998) recognized Sceloporus variabilis marmoratus as a distinct species (Sceloporus marmoratus), and they proposed that the remaining S. variabilis populations be split into multiple species. In commenting on the proposed split, Crother et al. (2000) pointed out that the sample of marmoratus was from a single locality more than 500 km from the closest sample of S. v. variabilis and concluded that more extensive sampling from intermediate localities is needed to determine if marmoratus and variabilis are separate lineages.

Sceloporus variabilis marmoratus is retained here following Crother et al. (2000) and Bell et al. (2003) pending further investigation of its taxonomic status.

Hedges and McCranie (2012) examined the systematics of this species complex, assigning northern populations to the resurrected Sphenomorphus continentalis. These authors described two new species, S. leonardovaldezi and S. guanajae, based on records from the Bay Islands off the coast of Honduras. More recently, remaining "S. millepunctatus" populations from the Bay Islands have been examined and determined to represent two additional, distinct species, S. alphus (Islha de Guanaja) and S. poindexteri (Islha de Utila) (McCranie and Hedges 2013).

Xenodon rabdocephalus is believed to be a species complex. Populations from Central America and Colombia that "almost certainly" fall outside the true range of Xenodon rabdocephalus sensu stricto were tentatively assigned to the resurrected Xenodon angustirostris by Myers and McDowell (2014). These authors were however not able to examine the holotype of X. angustirostris, and as such the status of this taxon requires confirmation. Morphological differences between Central American populations identified by Myers and McDowell (2014) further suggest that multiple species may fall within their concept of X. angustirostris. These authors note however that the distribution they propose for this taxon is "zoogeographically plausible" and that any effort to delimit species within this group based on the identified differences would amount to guesswork. Myers and McDowell (2014) are more confident in resurrecting Xenodon suspectus from synonymy with X. rabdocerphalus, but this account follows the Reptile Database (Uetz et al. 2018) in retaining both taxa within the X. rabdocephalus complex until its taxonomy is more fully-resolved.

This species may be erroneously identified as a member of the genus Hoplunnis but may possibly be a leptocephalus of the genus Saurenchelys. (K. Tighe pers comm. 2011). Additionally, this species is possibly a senior synonym of Hoplunnis pacifica Lane & Stewart 1968 (MCZ type catalog, fide D. G. Smith).
The eastern and western Atlantic subpopulations may represent two separate species (D. Smith pers. comm. 2012).
Deichmann (1958) notes that Holothuria inornata was a synonym of Holothuria keferstenii, but there is no current review on the status of this species. A review is likely necessary.

Ostrea lurida (the Olympia Oyster) was previously synonymized under O. conchaphila; however, they are both now considered to be separate species with O. lurida in the northern portion and O. conchaphila from Mexico southward (Polson et al. 2009). It is still confused with O. lurida in the literature despite this taxonomic resolution.
This used to be many several species and then they were clumped.

Previously considered as part of Rana berlandieri Zaldívar-Riverón et al. (2004) subsequently validated this species based on molecular data. A phylogenetic study of Mesoamerican ranids is in progress (J. Townsend pers. comm. March 2019). This species was split from Lithobates berlandieri (Zaldívar-Riverón et al. 2004).

McCranie and Wilson (1996) regarded C. atitlanensis as a synonym of C. bivittatus. Characteristics of recently acquired specimens from extreme southwestern Honduras (J. R. McCranie) also suggest that the two taxa may be conspecific (L. Porras, pers. comm. 2013).

Records formerly assigned to this species from Guanaja are now understood to represent a distinct species, Phyllodactylus paralepis, based on molecular and morphological evidence (McCranie and Hedges 2013).
Meyer and Wilson (1971) synonymized Anolis heteropholidotus within A. sminthus, but Köhler (1996) later resurrected it from synonymy.

G. Köhler (pers. comm. 2012) suggests that records from the Pacific versant presently included within this species may represent a separate species, for which the name Anolis pulchripes is available, but taxonomic research is needed to confirm this. Poe (2016) notes that the characters used to distinguish this species from Anolis zeus, presently recognized as a distinct species, are not reliable.

There remains some confusion as to whether Anolis lionotus is a separate species from the very similar A. oxylophus, a situation complicated by the apparent loss of the Panamanian A. lionotus holotype (Wilson et al. 2010). Citing unpublished work, Köhler (2001) justified earlier works (Köhler 1999, 2000) that treated A. oxylophus as a synonym without comment. As no published work has yet formally synonymized these taxa, however, this account follows Savage (2002) and Wilson et al. (2010) in considering A. lionotus a separate species from A. oxylophus, with A. oxylophus ranging from Honduras to western Panama.
Was formerly treated as part of Anolis sericeus.

McCranie (2011) resurrected the name Dendrophidion clarkii for northern populations within the D. nuchale species complex. Cadle and Savage (2012), in a subsequent revision of this complex, confirmed the validity of D. clarkii but restricted this name to populations ranging from Costa Rica and Panama to Colombia and Ecuador; these authors assigned remaining Central American populations to a new species, D. rufiterminorum.
This species was previously considered to belong to Tantilla taeniata (McCranie 2011).

Following Peters and Orejas-Miranda (1970) Amastridium sapperi has been treated as a subspecies of A. veliferum, and this arrangement is still followed by some authorities (e.g. Uetz and Hallerman 2010). Recent work, however, generally treats it as a full species (e.g. Wilson and Townsend 2006, Wilson et al. 2010).

Coniophanes piceivittis taylori and Coniophanes piceivittis taeniata were elevated to species status by Flores-Villela and Smith (2009), who also described C. michoacanensis from populations previously assigned to piceivittis.

The year of description of this species is frequently given as '1869', but is given as '1870' here following Wallach et al. (2014), Uetz et al. 2021), based on the actual year of publication of the describing publication.

The identity of the three records attributed to this species from Colombia is uncertain, as two of these exhibit scale counts within the range of geographical variation known for Urotheca lateristiga (J.D. Lynch pers. comm.), and the third was a road-killed juvenile in a poor state of preservation.

The taxonomy of Epictia (formerly Leptotyphlops) in Central America is in need of resolution. Sunyer and Köhler (2010) provisionally recognize only the single species E. goudoti pending clarification of this situation. These authors tentatively synonymize E. nasalis and E. ater within this species, the latter without discussion. These authors consider E. nasalis a possible synonym on the basis that the single known individual differs from typical E. goudoti by a single scale character and no further specimens have been found in 70 years, indicating that it may be merely an aberrant individual rather than a genuine species. This arrangement has subsequently been accepted by Wallach (2016), who redescribed Epictia ater. This scheme is followed here for E. nasalis, however E. ater is tentatively treated as a valid species pending clarification of the basis for synonymizing it within E. goudoti.
Was previously listed on The IUCN Red List under the genus Typhlops but is now treated under Amerotyphlops (Hedges et al. 2014).
Was previously listed on The IUCN Red List under the genus Typhlops but is now treated under Amerotyphlops (Hedges et al. 2014).

Hynková et al. (2009) suggested that Boa imperator is likely to warrant recognition as a full species. This arrangement was further supported by Reynolds et al. (2014) and is followed here. Two subspecies are recognized: B. i. imperator and B. i. sabogae (Reynolds and Henderson, in press).

Quercus xalapensis can be confused with Quercus sartorii Liebm. and Quercus paxtalensis C.H.Mull. Numerous specimens collected in Central America have been erroneously identified as Q. xalapensis but in fact they may belong to Q. paxtalensis (González-Espinosa 2011).

The Dusky Shark is extremely similar genetically and morphologically to the Galapagos Shark (Carcharhinus galapagensis). These species share mitochondrial DNA haplotypes but are distinguishable based on single nuclear polymorphisms (SNPs) (Corrigan et al. 2017) and also occupy different habitats (insular vs. continental).

This species is comprised of two valid subspecies: Mustelus canis canis occurs on the continental shelf, whereas M. c. insularis occurs on insular shelves in the Caribbean (Heemstra 1997, Ebert et al. 2013).

The Galapagos Shark is extremely similar genetically and morphologically to the Dusky Shark (Carcharhinus obscurus). These species share mitochondrial DNA haplotypes but are distinguishable based on single nuclear polymorphisms (SNPs) (Corrigan et al. 2017) and also occupy different habitats (insular vs. continental).

These iguanas are sometimes referred to in the literature as Enyaliosaurus quinquecarinatus Gray, 1845. A specimen that was originally described by Gray (1842) as Ctenosaura quinquecarinata was later re-examined as a novel species from México and named Ctenosaura oaxacana (Kohler and Hasbún 2001).

This species is sometimes confused with Rhinoptera bonasus, which can only be distinguished by counting the series of toothplates. Rhinoptera bonasus usually have seven series of plates in both jaws, while R. brasiliensis teeth are typically arranged in series of nine (Last et al. 2016).

Caiman crocodilus has four subspecies currently recognized:  C. c. crocodilus, C. c. fuscus, C. c. chiapasius, and C. c. apaporiensis. Caiman yacare previously was considered to be a fifth subspecies (i.e., C. c. yacare). However, it is now generally accepted as a full species (King and Burke 1989), and is no longer treated as a subspecies (Escobedo-Galván et al. 2011).

Busack and Pandya (2001), using morphological analysis, stated that there were no differences between subspecies. However, Venegas-Anaya et al. (2008), using mitochondrial DNA analysis, recognized three out of these four subspecies (no samples from C. c. apaporiensis used in this study) and delimited geographically distributions within the C. crocodilus complex. DNA analyses also suggest a geographic divergence in two groups: the Mesoamerican group including C. c. fuscus and C. c. chiapasius and the South American group, which includes C. c. crocodilus and C. yacare (Amato and Gatesby 1994; Venegas-Anaya et al. 2008).

Recent morphological analysis of the Apaporis River caiman (C. c. apaporiensis), based on holotype and paratypes skulls from the Chicago Field Museum (USA), corroborates a significant morphological differentiation with the rest of the C. crocodilus subspecies (Escobedo-Galván et al. 2015a) as reported by Frederico Medem in 1952. However, DNA analysis conducted with additional paratypes from Colombian collections showed that several of those skulls identified as C. c. apaporiensis in the Instituto de Ciencias Naturales, National University of Colombia collection fall into the C. c. crocodilus clade (Bloor 2013). Nevertheless, a more in-depth study is being initiated in late 2018, to collect less fragmented DNA (from live individuals rather than ancient bones) and larger sample sizes (for both morphological and genetic analyses), which will hopefully provide new evidence on the validity of this subspecies.
The form occurring in the Cordillera Oriental of Colombia might be Rhaebo guttatus (J.V. Rueda pers. comm.).

Moved from Hyalinobatrachium to Cochranella by Cisneros-Heredia and McDiarmid (2006), then to Teratohyla by Guayasamin et al. (2009). Cochranella petersi has been recently synonymized under Cochranella pulverata (Guayasamin et al. 2008).

"Although Triprion spinosus has been considered a species with a wide distribution, from southeastern Mexico to western Panama (Duellman, 1970), the 16S fragment of our specimen from Honduras differs from those of Oaxaca in 2.9%. Better understanding of the sequence variation among these samples and those from the easternmost part of the distribution of T. spinosus is required, but a taxonomic revision of the different populations assigned to this species seems to be necessary" (Faivovich et al. 2018).

This species was previously within the genus Hyla but was moved to the resurrected genus Dendropsophus (Faivovich et al. 2005). It is probable that this is a complex of several species. Further systematic studies are needed to resolve the taxonomy of the complex.

This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005). Two new species were described from the species group to which Craugastor coffeus (C. laticeps group) belongs, it is possible, albeit unlikely based on distinguished external morphological characteristics, there is additional taxonomic change yet to be determined (McCranie 2018).

There is doubt about the validity of this species as it was described from a single specimen based on a variable trait (Honduras Red List Assessment Workshop March 2019).
This form might be a complex of more than one species.

This species was formerly allocated to the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith, 2005). Craugastor megacephalus (Cope, 1875), an intermediate-sized frog ranging from Honduras to central Panama, is the more common species to which the name biporcatus has usually been applied (Savage and Myers 2002).
This species was previously within the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith, 2005).

This species is sometimes confused with Rhinoptera brasiliensis, which can only be distinguished from R. bonasus by counting the series of toothplates. Rhinoptera bonasus usually have seven series of plates in both jaws, while R. brasiliensis teeth are typically arranged in series of nine (Last et al. 2016).
The scientific name for this species is often misspelled as Carcharhinus perezii. Carcharhinus springeri Sadowsky & Amorim 1977 is considered a synonym (Soto 2001).
Castro (2011) resurrected Carcharhinus cerdale, considering it distinct from C. porosus. Carcharhinus cerdale is restricted to the Eastern Pacific and C. porosus to the Western Atlantic.

Nurse sharks occurring in the eastern Pacific were formerly considered part of this species concept, however the Pacific Nurse Shark (Ginglymostoma unami) has now been formally described as a separate species (Del Moral-Flores et al. 2015).
Previously confused with the similar but smaller Etmopterus pusillus until described as a distinct species by Shirai and Tachikawa (1993).
This species is sometimes confused with Squalus clarkae and may be confused with recently described or undescribed species in the South Atlantic (C.F. Cotton unpubl. data 2020).

The species is here understood as encompassing all nominal subspecies described by Hubbs (1936, 1938) and other authors, and elevated to species status without a comprehensive analysis in some works (e.g. by Říčan et al. 2016). A recent morphological and genetic review found no support for more than one species (Barrientos-Villalobos et al. 2018). Several of the Hubbsian subspecies have been listed as vulnerable (e.g. by Jelks et al. 2008), but these assessments do not refer to Mayaheros urophthalmus proper.

Wüster et al. (2001) described a new species of Drymarchon from northwestern Venezuela, bringing the species total for the genus to four (five if couperi is recognized as a species). This taxonomic rearrangement treats D. corais and D. melanurus as distinct species. The species in the United States, Mexico, Central America, and South America west of the Andes and in Venezuela is D. melanurus. D. corais occurs in South America east of the Andes (Wüster et al. 2001).  Wüster et al. (2001) also recognized D. couperi and D. margaritae, previously considered subspecies, as full species but without examining specimens, based on previously published (but unspecified) morphological differences and application of the evolutionary species concept. Subsequent checklists (e.g. Crother et al. 2003, Collins and Taggart 2002) have adopted this taxonomy.
McCranie (2011) agreed with these taxonomic changes, but noted that these actions were taken on the basis of limited sampling and emphasized the need for further study to clarify the taxonomy of this group. The resulting concept of D. melanurus is likely to be a species complex; McCranie (2011) suggested that two species-level taxa may be included under the name D. melanurus in Honduras alone.
This species has often been placed in the genus Dryadophis, but Dixon and Tipton (2004) placed it in Mastigodryas on the basis of seniority.
Some authors consider the northern populations of the Yucatan peninsula as a separate species, Pliocercus andrewsi, but here it is considered a subspecies.

Jadin et al. (2013) investigated the systematics of Pseustes (for which they resurrected the senior synonym Phrynonax), within which they recognized the species P. poecilonotus, P. shropshirei, and P. polylepis (the latter resurrected from synonymy within P. poecilonotus). Natera-Munaw et al. (2015) resurrected the name Phrynonax lyoni encompassing both Venezuelan records of P. shropshirei and an eastern coastal subpopulation of P. polylepis, the latter without examining the specimens. The characters these authors use to distinguish P. lyoni are, however, confusing and examination of the eastern coastal specimens confirms their assignment to P. polylepis (G. Rivas pers. comm. 2016). On this basis, this account follows a traditional concept of P. shropshirei encompassing the Venezuelan populations, and P. lyoni is retained as a junior synonym of P. poecilonotus.
The subspecies victa of peninsular Florida is treated as a species by some authors.

Parkinson et al. (2000) concluded that Agkistrodon bilineatus howardgloydii and A. b. russeolus should not be elevated to species status based on shallow mitochondrial divergence and similar morphologies. Although noting that sample sizes in this study were low and covered only a small number of localities, Porras et al. (2013) reinterpreted this evidence and along with comparisons of colour patterns, proposed that A. b. howardgloydi and A. b. russeolus should be elevated to species status. These taxa were, however, retained within A. bilineatus by Wallach (2014).
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Potamocarcinini.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Hypolobocerini.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Hypolobocerini.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Hypolobocerini.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Hypolobocerini.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Hypolobocerini.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Potamocarcinini.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Hypolobocerini. This species was formerly assigned to Isabellagordonia.
Subfamily Trichodactylinae.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Potamocarcinini.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Hypolobocerini.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Potamocarcinini. This species was formerly assigned to the genus Potamocarcinus.
Subfamily Pseudothelphusinae; tribe Hypolobocerini, Subspecies zurstrasseni.
This species is easy to identify (F. Alvarez pers. comm. 2009).

Attention RLU: A new taxonomic concept is needed for Emblemariopsis signifer as it was revised by Victor 2020 (now considered Brazil endemic with records from elsewhere assigned to other Emblemariopsis spp.)

This species names has been previously misspelled as “signifera” but signifer is the appropriate spelling (Victor 2020).Species within the Emblemariopsis genus are poorly known and poorly represented in museum collections because of their small size, mostly transparent bodies, and preference for hole-dwelling habitats (Victor 2020). Descriptions of species within this genus are often based on adult male specimens, and due to significant sexual dimorphism, females and immature specimens are often mistaken as different species (Victor 2020).
Previously it was believed that Belize was abundant with Emblemariopsis signifera but according to DNA surveys and collections, E. signifera is not found in the Caribbeans (Victor 2020). Rather, specimens previously cited as E. signifera in Belize instead represent the initial phase of either E. dianae or of E. leptocirris (Victor 2020). 
Most Caribbean glass blennies were previously misidentified as this species (Victor 2020).
Populations of this species on offshore islands of Brazil may or may not represent separate genetic lineages, subspecies, or species as these populations require further research (Victor 2020).
In the tropical Eastern Pacific, Caranx crysos is replaced by Caranx caballus (Günther 1869)
The taxonomy and key characteristics of Brama spp. are in need of review (FAO ECA guide in prep RL Haedrich).
There are multiple undescribed species in this group which may have been confused with this species (Moore, Polanco, Russell, McEachran pers. comm. 2013).
Holacanthus ciliaris are closely related to blue angelfish Holacanthus bermudensis Goode, and colouration is the only reliable character to separate these species (Feeley et al. 2009).

There are two recognized subspecies for the species. Panulirus argus argus is found north of the equator and Panulirus argus westonii is found south of the equator in Brazil, however this is an invalid name (Sarver, Silberman and Walsh, 1998).

This species is frequently misidentified as juvenile or female of Coryphaena hippurus.

The specific name is sometimes misspelled as equisetis instead of equiselis (Gibbs and Collette 1959).
This species has often been confused with Halophila ovalis. Halophila decipiens is monoecious, has serrate leaf tips and hairs on both sides of its leaves.

Halodule wrightii is a well established species. However, the taxonomy of the other species of Halodule in the Atlantic is less certain (Larkum et al. 2006) and there are questions about its taxonomy in the Indo-Pacific as well (Green and Short 2003).
Ctenosaura praeocularis was recently described and may be previously referenced in the literature as Ctenosaura flavidorsalis and less often as Ctenosaura quinquecarinata.

Robertson and Allen (2006) treat the Eastern Pacific population as a separate species. However, the taxonomy of this group is in need of revision and the Eastern Pacific population may in fact belong to the circumglobal species Lobotes surinamensis.

Frequently misidentified as Albula vulpes, an Atlantic species. It has also been previously identified as A. neoguinaica (a synonym of the Indo-central Pacific species A. forsteri). However, genetic data indicate the eastern Pacific form is a separate species (Colborn et al. 2001), for which A. esuncula is the oldest name. There is recent genetic evidence that this species may in fact represent two species: Albula esuncula from south of Mazatlan, Mexico, and a yet to be named Albula species from Southern California to Mazatlan (Pfeiler et al. 2008).
This species may have some taxonomic confusion with Centropomus armatus.
This species is commonly confused with Acrostichum aureum. These species are often lumped together making it difficult to know the limits of the distribution.

This species is known from both the Eastern Tropical Pacific (western coast of the Americas) and the southwest Pacific. The population in the Eastern Tropical Pacific was formerly known as R. mangle (Ellison 1991, Duke 2006).
This species was previously considered as Eucinostomus argenteus.

Knudsen and Clements (2013) recently revised the family Kyphosidae. They determined that microcanthids, oplegnathids, kuhliids and terapontids are more closely related to Kyphosus than is Girella. Knudsen and Clements (2013) concluded that Girella, Scorpis, and Kyphosus should not be included within the same family and instead, be separated as individual families. Their study recognized 11 species in Kyphosidae, as well as one Neoscorpis, which is considered a distinct genus within Kyphosidae. Thus, there are 12 species total in the family Kyphosidae. 

Kyphosus lutescens and K. pacificus are now treated as synonyms of K. sectatrix. Both K. incisor and K. analogus are now considered synonyms of K. vaigiensis. K. pacificus/sandwicensis is a synonym of K. elegans. Before Knudsen and Clements (2013) it was thought that only two Kyphosids occurred in the Atlantic, but there are in fact four species, K. sectatrix, K. vaigiensis/incisor, K. bigibbus, and K. cinerascens.

The juvenile of Opistognathus punctatus was described as O. mexicanus by Allen and Robertson (1991). Opistognathus mexicanus is considered the junior synonym of O. punctatus (Bussing and Lavenberg 2003).
Also known as Japanoconger proriger (Robertson and Allen 2006). Ophisoma prorigerum is an objective synonym of Ariosoma prorigerum, and is listed as valid but the genus uncertain.
Newly discovered species in 2005.
Newly discovered species in 2005.
Previously this species has sometimes been referred to as Caranx hippos.

This species may represent two species given that no records known between them. Proposed names are Xenistius californiensis from southern California to the Gulf of California, and Xenistius peruanus from Lobos Islands Peru to central Peru (Roberston pers. comm.).
Lythrypnus pulchellus was separated from L. rhizophora based on island vs. coastal distribution by Bussing (1990). However, unpublished molecular data indicates that they may be the same species.
This nomenclature may represent a species complex including available names such as Cathorops liropus.
Springer (1958) recognized two subspecies: Malacoctenus zonifer zonifer from Mexico, and M. zonifer sudensis from Nicaragua to Ecuador.
Most recently, Sciades has been used as the genus for this species (Marceniuk and Menezes 2007).
This species was previously in the genus Enypias (Tornabene and Van Tassell 2014).
Lythrypnus pulchellus was separated from L. rhizophora based on island vs coastal distribution by Bussing (1990). However, unpublished molecular data indicates that they may be the same species.

This species has been considered a synonym of Abudefduf concolor, but a recent molecular study by Lessios et al. (1995) confirmed that it is a separate species. It is closely related to A. concolor and is easily confused in the field during visual surveys. The distributions of the two species overlap between El Salvador and Costa Rica, and a combination of morphological and genetic comparisons throughout the ranges of both species are needed to establish the full range of each.
This species is sometimes incorrectly spelled as Protemblemaria bicirris.
Dactyloscopus elongatus was previously considered a subspecies of this species but now is considered valid as a separate species (Hastings and Springer 2009).

This species has been considered a synonym of Abudefduf declivifrons, but a recent molecular study by Lessios et al. (1995) confirmed that it is a separate species. It is closely related to A. declivifrons and is easily confused in the field during visual surveys. The distributions of the two species overlap between El Salvador and Costa Rica, and a combination of morphological and genetic comparisons throughout the ranges of both species are needed to establish the full range of each.
Springer (1958) recognized two subspecies: Malacoctenus margaritae mexicanus from the Gulf of California, and M. margaritae margaritae from the remainder of its range.
Original orthography is scudderii.
Separate species for Scorpaena mystes and S. plumieri is more commonly accepted.
This species is also known as Notarius osculus by some authors, but Arius osculus is the nomen dubium (Betancur and Acero 2004). Other generic names used for this species are Ariopsis and Aspistor.
Sciades has also been used recently as the genus for this species.

According to Sandoval-Huerta et al. (2019), this species is part of a species complex, with some records from the Gulf of Panama to El Choco, Colombia now attributed to Elacatinus rubrifrons. Records from Costa Rica and Ecuador are suspected to represent a third undescribed species (Sandoval-Huerta et al. 2019).

Dawson (1975) recognized three subspecies: Dactyloscopus pectoralis pectoralis from the Gulf of California and outer coast of Baja California; D. pectoralis fallax from Sinaloa, Mexico to Ecuador, including Isla del Coco; and D. pectoralis insulatus from Islas Revillagigedos. All three are now considered valid as separate species (Hastings and Springer 2009).
This species is also known as Eucinostomus californiensis, but E. gracilis is apparently the senior synonym.
This genus has undergone taxonomic revision (Miller and Stefanni 2001).

Springer (1959) recognized the populations from Baja California/Gulf of California and the remainder of the range as a separate subspecies, Malacoctenus tetranemus multipunctatus and M. tetranemus tetranemus, respectively.
This species was previously referred to as Elacatinus janssi.
This species is also more commonly known as Caranx caballus. This species is probably a junior synonym of Caranx crysos.
Gymnothorax equatorialis is similar, but has three pores below the eye, a narrower tail, and the spots at the rear of the tail are elongate and much larger than the eye.
For taxonomic treatment see Gomon (2006).

There are likely cryptic species in parts of this species' distribution and taxonomic research is needed (D.R. Robertson and J. Van Tassell pers. comm. 2024). According to Miller and Steffani (2001) there are two subspecies - Bathygobius r. longipinnis from the Revillagigedos and Tres Marias Islands, and Bathygobius r. ramosus from the remainder of the range.
Taxonomic studies are needed to confirm this as a single species.
Closely related to Rypticus saponaceus (Bloch and Schneider) from the western Atlantic.

Some authors (Hensley 1995, Evseenko 1999, Robertson et al. 2017) consider this species to be a possible senior subjective synonym of M. asaedae. Other authors consider M. asaedae to be valid (Castro-Aguirre et al. 1992, Bussing and López 1994, De La Cruz Agüero et al. 1997, Evseenko 1998, Amaoka and Imamura 2000, Nelson et al. 2004, Page et al. 2013). The most recent evidence (Robertson et al. 2017), based on both morphology and molecular evidence, indicate that M. asaedae is a junior synonym of M. dubiosa. {Ask RLU to merge M. asaedae into this account}
More information should be obtained from Pietch and Grobecker (1987).
This species is also known as Mnierpes macrocephalus.
This species was previously considered to be a subspecies of the Atlantic species Fodiator acutus (Parin and Belyanina 2002).
Newly discovered species in 2005.

Merluccius hernandezi can be a distinct species from ,i>M. angustimanus (Nelson et al. 2004) However, Lloris D., J. Matallanas and P. Oliver (2003) consider both species as the same. Further taxonomic research is needed.
Also listed as Caranx otrynter.

This species is commonly misidentified as Anchoa panamensis (which occurs only in Panama Bay); thus most records of Anchoa panamensis north of Panama Bay refer to Anchoa mundeola (Palacios and Phillips 1984).
Most recently, Sciades has been used as the genus for this species (Marceniuk and Menezes 2007). Further research is needed to confirm that this represents a single species.
Although Kailola (2004) treat this species as a synonym of Sciades hymenorrhinos, it is accepted here as Sciades dowii following Betancur-R. et al. (2007).

Knudsen and Clements (2013) recently revised the family Kyphosidae. They determined that microcanthids, oplegnathids, kuhliids and terapontids are more closely related to Kyphosus than is Girella. Knudsen and Clements (2013) concluded that Girella, Scorpis, and Kyphosus should not be included within the same family and instead, be separated as individual families. Their study recognized 11 species in Kyphosidae, as well as one Neoscorpis, which is considered a distinct genus within Kyphosidae. Thus, there are 12 species total in the family Kyphosidae. 

Kyphosus lutescens and K. pacificus are now treated as synonyms of K. sectatrix. Both K. incisor and K. analogus are now considered synonyms of K. vaigiensis. K. pacificus/sandwicensis is a synonym of K. elegans. Before Knudsen and Clements (2013) it was thought that only two Kyphosids occurred in the Atlantic, but there are in fact four species, K. sectatrix, K. vaigiensis/incisor, K. bigibbus, and K. cinerascens.
There are two recognized subspecies: Dactyloscopus byersi heraldi, from Baja California; and D. byersi byersi from the remainder of the range.
This species seems to have two forms or subspecies: Harengula thrissina thrissina from the Gulf of California to Panama and Harengula thrissina peruana from Panama to Peru (Watson and Sandknop 1996).
Newly discovered species in 2005.
References to this species prior to 2001 are to Hyporhamphus unifasciatus which is a western Atlantic species (Banford and Collette 2001).

Some authors (Hensley 1995, Evseenko 1999) consider this species to be a possible junior subjective synonym of M. dubiosa; other authors consider this species to be valid using a variety of spellings for the specific epithet (Castro-Aguirre et al. 1992, Bussing and López 1994, De La Cruz Agüero et al. 1997, Evseenko 1998, Amaoka and Imamura 2000, Nelson et al. 2004, Page et al. 2013). Most recently, Robertson et al. (2017), based on both morphology and molecular evidence, also consider this nominal species to be a synonym of M. dubiosa.
Also known as Encheliophis dubius.
Synonyms: Arctus depressus (S.I. Smith, 1881); S. nearctus (Holthuis, 1960).
Synonyms: Arctus americanus (S.I. Smith, 1869), Scyllarus gundlachi (Von Martens, 1872).
This species was split by Holthuis 1960 into S. chacei and S. americanus, as previous specimens have had some confusion between these two species.
This species was thought to occur South to Brazil, but genetic research revealed that Brazilian populations belong to a different species (Rocha 2004).

This species was thought to occur along the Brazilian coast, but recent genetic research revealed that coastal Brazilian populations belong to a different species (Rocha 2004).

Several endemic species of the Brazilian province have been taxonomically revised and are now validated as Halichoeres penrosei (previously recorded as H. maculipinna) (Pinherio et al. 2009).

H. maculipinna  is closer to Thalassoma than to any other Halichoeres (Rocha et al. 2010)
For taxonomic treatment see Gomon (2006).

There is some taxonomic confusion between the species under Xyrichtys and Iniistius. The genus Iniistius has been considered a synonym of Xyrichtys by some authors but it is now recognized as a separate genus, distinct from Xyrichtys (Randall and Earle 2002, Randall et al. 2002). Seventeen species are included in Iniistius and they are: I. aneitensis, I. auropunctatus, I. baldwini, I. bimaculatus, I. cyanifrons, I. dea, I. evides, I. griffithsi, I. jacksoniensis, I. melanopus, I. pavo, I. pentadactylus, I. spilonotus, I. trivittatus, I. twistii, I. umbrilatus, and I. verrens.
For taxonomic treatment see Gomon (2006).

There is some taxonomic confusion between the species under Xyrichtys and Iniistius. The genus Iniistius has been considered a synonym of Xyrichtys by some authors but it is now recognized as a separate genus, distinct from Xyrichtys (Randall and Earle 2002, Randall et al. 2002).

Seventeen species are included in Iniistius and they are: I. aneitensis, I. auropunctatus, I. baldwini, I. bimaculatus, I. cyanifrons, I. dea, I. evides, I. griffithsi, I. jacksoniensis, I. melanopus, I. pavo, I. pentadactylus, I. spilonotus, I. trivittatus, I. twistii, I. umbrilatus and I. verrens.

Halichoeres sazimai, n. sp. is described from the Western South Atlantic. During many years it was misidentified as H. bathyphilus from the Northwestern Atlantic, but it can be distinguished from the latter by striking color differences between the two species, with H. sazimai being characterized by a white body with a midline, zigzag patterned stripe on body, black and brownish in terminal males and yellow or golden in females and juveniles (Luiz et al. 2009).

There is some taxonomic confusion between the species under Xyrichtys and Iniistius. The genus Iniistius has been considered a synonym of Xyrichtys by some authors but it is now recognized as a separate genus, distinct from Xyrichtys (Randall and Earle 2002, Randall et al. 2002). Seventeen species are included in Iniistius and they are: I. aneitensis, I. auropunctatus, I. baldwini, I. bimaculatus, I. cyanifrons, I. dea, I. evides, I. griffithsi, I. jacksoniensis, I. melanopus, I. pavo, I. pentadactylus, I. spilonotus, I. trivittatus, I. twistii, I. umbrilatus, and I. verrens.
This species was thought to occur along the Brazilian coast, but genetic research revealed that coastal Brazilian populations belong to a different species (Rocha 2004).

The ICZN (1999, opinion 1896) fixed Buccinum truncatulum Muller, 1774 as the type species of the nominal genus Galba Schrank, 1803; it also placed Galba Schrank, 1803 on the Official List of Species Names in Zoology, thereby replacing the current usage of the name Fossaria Westerlund, 1885, which now a junior objective synonym. 

In Europe, Falkner et al. (2001) use Galba based on ICZN opinion 1896, whereas in North American Fossaria was used for this genus (Turgeon et al., 1998).  The latest publication on the conservation status of the North America Gastropods (Johnson et al., 2013) used Galba for the genus in North America, thus the IUCN Red List is now following this convention and all species previously recognised as Fossaria are now in genus Galba.

The Galba bulimoides group is in flux (Burch 1989; Hubendick, 1951) with species variably recognised as forms, varieties subspecies or full species.

Dillon et al. (2006) follows Hubendick (1951) in placing this species in the genus Lymnaea, with Fossaria as a subspecies.  The analysis of the prostate surface, preputium and penis sheath lengths and the anterior and posterior width of the penis sheath allow a clear separation between Galba cubensis and Galba truncatula (Samadi et al. 2000), so G. cubensis is a distinct species, not a synonym of G. truncatula.

Genetic examination of the molecular phylogeny of global Planorboidea at the COI and 18S molecular markers indicates that all North American taxa within the subfamily Planorbinae form a well-supported clade, which is as yet unnamed but referred to as the C-Clade (Albrecht et al. 2007). This species is sometimes referred to as Biomphalaria obstructa (Morelet 1849), a likely synonym.
This species was placed in the genus Stenophysa by Taylor (2003), but subsequent molecular analyses included it within the family Physidae and genus Physa (Wethington and Lydeard 2007).

This species was placed in family Dicotylidae by Jones et al. (1992) and in Tayassuidae by Grubb (2005). The appropriate generic name has been debated. It was placed in genus Dicotyles by some authors, the genus Pecari by Grubb (1993, 2005), and the genus Tayassu by Jones et al. (1992). MtDNA data support the recognition of three genera of extant peccaries: Catagonus, Pecari, and Tayassu, with this species in the genus Pecari (Theimer and Keim 1998, Gongora and Moran 2005). DNA studies suggest that P. tajacu may consist of at least two major clades or lineages comprising specimens from North/Central and South America (Gongora et al. 2006, 2011) with structural chromosomal differences (Gongora et al. 2000, Adega et al. 2006). Additional studies are needed to clarify whether intra and/or inter-specific genetic and chromosomal variation is occurring within this species.
Recent analysis suggest that the Central American populations may be different from the South American ones (Castoe et al. 2005).

Genetic analyses in the Atlantic and Indo-Pacific indicate that nesting populations comprise separate and identifiable stocks that should be treated as separate management units (Bass et al. 1996, Bowen et al. 1996, Bowen and Karl 2007). Hawksbill aggregations on foraging grounds comprise animals from multiple nesting populations and often include animals from distant rookeries (Broderick et al. 1994, Bowen et al. 2007).
Species of the Acropomatidae family are ill-defined (FAO ECA guide in prep PC Heemstra).
Because this species was described relatively recently, it is often referenced in the literature as Ctenosaura palearis or Enyaliosaurus palearis, the sister species that it was split from.

Four subspecies are recognised:
  • T. a. acus (Lacepède, 1803) in the western Atlantic (Massachusetts, USA to Brazil) and east Atlantic (off Morocco and the western Mediterranean Sea);
  • T. a. imperialis (Rafinesque, 1810) in the Mediterranean Sea and Cape Verde Islands);
  • T. a. rafale Collette and Parin 1970 from the Gulf of Guinea; and
  • T. a melanotus (Bleeker, 1850) in the the Indo-West Pacific and oceanic islands in the eastern tropical Pacific (Revillagigedos, Clipperton, and Cocos).

Exocoetus obtusirostris is endemic to the Atlantic Ocean and showed no significant differences from different parts of this ocean. It was thought to occur circumglobally before it was split into three other closely related species (Parin and Shakhovskoy 2000).

Two subspecies are recognized by Collette (2003), T. crocodilus crocodilus (Peron and Lesueur 1821) from the Atlantic and Indo-West Pacific and T. crocodilus fodiator (Jordan and Gilbert 1882) in the eastern tropical Pacific.
Subpopulations of this species should be further investigated as they may represent separate species (Tomio pers. comm. 2012).

Cheilopogon melanurus has been reported from the eastern Atlantic, from Senegal to Angola (Parin 1999). The eastern tropical Atlantic population was studied earlier by Gibbs and Staiger (1970). They discovered significant differences in pectoral-fin pigmentation and barbel structure between juvenile specimens of this population and similar-sized western Atlantic specimens and suspected, even not finding any distinctions between adults of both populations, the presence of yet undescribed species near the shores of West Africa. Parin and Belyanina (2000) reexamined three of these smaller eastern Atlantic specimens (USNM 203903, 203905 and 218912) and re-identified them as C. milleri (Gibbs and Staiger 1970). However, the western and eastern populations are so different in predorsal-scale number (25-33, mean 28.4, by 8 specimens, vs. 31-36, mean 33.7) that recognition of another species is highly probable (Parin in prep).
This species has been previously recorded as Gigantura vorax but this is now regarded as a synonym of G. chuni.
The correct spelling for this species is Omosudis lowii (Günther, 1887), though other spellings are in use (Eschmeyer 2014). This species is also referred to as Omosudis loweii by FAO.

The name S. brasiliensis (type locality: Cape Frio, Brazil) has been generally used for this species.  However, genetic evidence indicates approximately 5-6% divergence in CO1 between eastern and western Atlantic populations, which suggests the populations on either side of the Atlantic are distinct species [Baldwin et al. in press]. Thus, the name S. parri Norman 1935 (type locality: Angola) should be applied to this species.
Hemiramphus balao is frequently misidentified as Hemiramphus brasiliensis.

Oxyporhamphus micropterus similis is replaced in the Indo-Pacific by the nominal species Oxyporhamphus micropterus micropterus.  It is considered to be Exocoetidae by some authors (Collette 2002). The recent acceptance of Oxyporhamphus similis as a species by Eschmeyer should be reviewed (B. Collette pers. comm. 2012).

There are three co-occurring species of the genus Syacium in the western Atlantic. Identification of specimens to species is difficult because the species are morphologically similar and there is a significant amount of sexual dimorphism. Often times, these fishes are not identified to the species level and it is likely that in some studies catches consist of more than one species (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2015).

Taylor (1956) reviewed Middle American Mabuya found in Costa Rica and concluded that three species could be diagnosed: M. brachypoda, M. alliacea and M. unimarginata. Subsequent authors adopted this scheme inconsistently (Hedges and Conn 2012), and most recent publications have rejected this division and placed all Mabuya in Middle America in Mabuya unimarginata following Savage (2002), who contended that intergradation between these forms indicated the presence of only a single species in Costa Rica. Hedges and Conn (2012) reexamined representatives of these proposed species, and confirmed the original diagnosis of Taylor (1956). These authors noted that the position taken by Savage (2002) was not supported by evidence and was inconsistent with the observation presented by Taylor (1956) that M. unimarginata and M. brachypoda occur within 10 km of one another with no indication of hybridisation, Hedges and Conn (2012) therefore revalidated M. brachypoda and M. alliacea, and assigned all former Mabuya in Central America to the new genus Marisora. Marisora brachypoda is the most widespread of the three mainland species, and there are indications from both morphology and molecular analysis that further taxonomic work is required to clarify the identity of additional forms within this possible species complex (Hedges and Conn 2012).
The genus of this species was recently changed from Carangoides to Caranx (B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2012, Page et al. 2012).
Dornburg et al. (2012) proposed changing the genus of this species to Flammeo, however, this has not yet been generally accepted.
The genus of this species was previously Hypoatherina, but is now Atherina.
This species can be commonly misidentified as B. maculiferus (Weigt et al. 2012).

Many specimens historically identified as A. maculatus that have been found off the coast of Brazil around St. Paul's Rocks may have been misidentifications of A. strigosus, which has been recorded there based on molecular evidence (Bowen et al. 2001).
Dornburg et al. (2012) proposed changing the genus of this species to Neoniphon, however, this has not yet been generally accepted.

This species was described based on a single specimen collected off Haiti (Jordan in Jordan and Goss 1889). Other studies dealing with the taxonomy of Atlantic species of Citharichthys (Jordan and Goss 1889, Jordan and Evermann 1900, Norman 1934, Gutherz 1967) did not report any additional specimens. It has since been reported in several books and checklists from Central America (e.g. Castro-Aguirre et al. 1999, Munroe 2003, Angulo et al. 2013), but the basis of these records and the number of additional specimens is uncertain. The taxonomic status of this nominal species requires further investigation (Munroe 2003); for example, Robertson and Van Tassell (2019) suggested that this nominal species may be conspecific with Citharichthys arenaceus.
Dornburg et al. (2012) proposed changing the genus of this species to Neoniphon, however, this has not yet been generally accepted.
Page et al. (in press) accept the present taxonomic standing of Foetorepus agassizii.
In Brazilian waters, this species has been previously misidentified as Saurida suspicio (Carvalho-Filho et al. 2010).
The West Pacific population may represent another species.
Brotula barbata may be a species complex (Nielsen et al. 1999, de Paiva et al. 2010, R. Robins pers. comm. 2013).
This species may represent a complex of more than one species and further work is required to resolve it taxonomic status of S. suspicio and its distribution in the region (A. Polanco 2006).

Species of the Ogilbichthys genus are easily confused with A. minyomma due to very similar morphologies and sympatric occurrences, therefore, extra care should be taken to determine an accurate identification (Moller et al. 2004).

Böhlke and Thomas (1961) discussed geographic variation in Opistognathus aurifrons, especially with regard to color pattern. Although they noted that specimens from the Bahamas and Florida can be consistently distinguished from each other by the presence or absence of black markings on the head, their observation that these markings are inconsistent in Virgin Island specimens led them to synonymize Gnathypops bermudezi. Subsequently, Ho et al. (2012) examined population genetics and color pattern of four Caribbean populations of O. aurifrons; although each population exhibited high levels of genetic differentiation, phenotype variation and genetics were not congruent.

Specimens from Brazil, including Trinidade Island and Fernando de Noronha, possibly represent a geminate species of O. aurifrons. They cannot be distinguished genetically and have virtually identical color patterns, but differ in vertebral counts. The taxonomic status of the Brazilian population is presently unresolved.

There is some uncertainty surrounding the taxonomic status of this species. There are two recognized species: Bathyanthias mexicanus and B. cubensis. A third, not yet described species occurs in the southern part of the Caribbean, and it is unknown if this confuses the distribution of B. cubensis. However, specimens examined from Colombia by A. Polanco pers. comm. (2018) are recognized as B. cubensis. The genus Bathyanthias requires further taxonomic study and it is not known how the ranges of B. mexicanus and B. cubensis overlap in the Gulf of Mexico (R. Robertson pers. comm. 2018).
Some workers consider the genus of this species to be valid as Serranus, not Centropristis.

There is an ongoing discussion on the validity of the hamlets as biological species (Domeier 1994). Hamlet "species" are defined primarily on differences in color patterns. They are known to interbreed and hybridize freely with very little consistent genetic differentiation amongst them.

Lonchopisthus meadi (Menezes and Figueiredo 1971) is a junior synonym of L. lemur (B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2012).
Lonchopisthus linderi Ginsburg, 1942 is a junior synonym of L. micrognathus.
The genus of this species was recently changed from Hemanthias to Baldwinella (Anderson and Heemstra 2012)

The eastern Atlantic and Brazilian subpopulations may represent variations of R. subbifrenatus or an undescribed species (Baldwin and Weigt 2012).
There are likely two well-defined sub-species that differ in coloration and meristics: a northern one and a southern one (Bullock and Smith 1991).

Etropus crossotus was originally described from specimens collected in the eastern Pacific Ocean. Populations identified as this species from the western Atlantic, though morphologically similiar, have not been examined from a genetic perspective to determine if they are conspecific with the eastern Pacific populations (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2015). For now, we continue to use E. crossotus for Atlantic populations.

There are three co-occurring species of the genus Syacium in the western Atlantic. Identification of specimens to species is difficult because the species are morphologically similar and there is a significant amount of sexual dimorphism. Often times, these fishes are not identified to the species level and it is likely that in some studies catches consist of more than one species (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2015).
In the field, this species is difficult to distinguish from Stephanolepis hispidus (R. Robertson and J. Tyler pers. comm. 2015).
This species is now considered a synonym of Prionurus laticlavius (Catalog of Fishes online database accessed May 2024).
Westneat and Alfaro (2005) recognize the Scarini as a tribe within the family Labridae. The genera Chlororus and Scarus are two distinct monophyletic lineages (Smith et al. 2008).

There is strong evidence of genetic break between Pacific and Indian ocean populations. However, there is no clear evidence of morphological differentiation (J.H. Choat pers comm. 2009).

The population in Fernando de Noronha are genetically distinct and probably represents a separate species (R. Robertson pers comm. 2008). Juveniles of this species are easily misidentified in Brazil as other species of Sparisoma and Nicholsina.

Lawrance (1933) originally recognized the howlers from Belize, north and eastern Guatemala and the Yucatán Peninsula in Mexico, as to distinct taxa, within Aloutta palliata (A. p. pigra and A. p. luctuosa). Regarding A. p. pigra she mentioned “The differences, however, are so definite that they unquestionably indicate a separate subspecies; indeed, if it were not for the form found at Mountain Cow [A. p. luctuosa] which seems to be intermediate between this and typical A. p. palliata, one might be justified in calling it a distinct species” (Lawrance 1933, p. 334). Smith (1970) analysed pelage coloration patterns, and cranial and dental features of 238 specimens from across the range of A. palliata (including those studied by Lawrence, 1933) and compared them with a population sample of two sympatric forms of howler monkeys from the state of Tabasco, Mexico. He determined that the two (partially sympatric) forms from his sample constituted two well-differentiated species, and thus recommended A. pigra to be considered full species and separated from A. palliata. He considered A. p. luctuosa Lawrence, 1933 as junior synonym of A. pigra. Most authors have considered A. pigra as the single species of Black howler in Central America (e.g., Groves 2001, 2005; Rylands et al. 2006). Napier (1976) discussed that A. pigra was in fact A. villosa (Gray 1845), and Brandon-Jones (2006) argued that Alouatta pigra Lawrence, 1933 is a junior synonym. However, due to the poor condition of the type specimen of A. villosa, the lack of compelling evidence (genetic or otherwise) to ensure that this is in fact the same taxon as A. pigra, and in pro of taxonomic stability, Cortés-Ortiz et al. (2015a) continue to call this taxon A. pigra until further studies are completed. Using mtDNA markers, Cortés-Ortiz et al. (2003) confirmed that A. palliata and A. pigra comprise reciprocally monophyletic groups, justifying their separation into distinct species. Nonetheless, as pointed out by Cortés-Ortiz et al. (2015a) “the validity of A. pigra luctuosa from the Cayo District in Belize has yet to be evaluated with genetic data.”
This species was originally described as Triathalassothia gloverensis, but was later moved into the genus Vladichthys (Greenfield et al. 2008).
The taxonomy and key characteristics of Brama species are in need of review (Haedrich in press).

The western Pacific/Indo-Pacific populations of this species were previously considered a subspecies Lagocephalus lagocephalus oceanicus, while those in the Atlantic were previously considered the subspecies Lagocephalus lagocephalus lagocephalus.
The taxonomy of this species needs review.
Howella atlantica is considered by some a subspecies of Howella brodiei Ogilby, 1899, although accepted by Eschmeyer (2015).
Previous to the description of Lepophidium cultratum many workers applied the name Lepophidium profundorum to the undescribed species (Rob Robins pers comm 2013).

Lepophidium entomelan and L. zophochir are similar, disjunctly distributed species. Further sampling in the Southern Caribbean may reveal an adjacency or overlap in distribution that will clarify relationships between the species (R. Robins pers. comm. 2012).
According to Ghedotti et al. (2015), this species should be placed in the family Lestidiidae.
Populations of this species in the Western Atlantic versus the Pacific may represent two separate species (Kotlyar 2001).
Ipomoea ramosissima (Poir.) Chiosy is a gene pool tertiary wild relative of sweet potato, Ipomoea batatas (L.) Lam. var. batatas  (Vincent et al. 2013).

Ipomoea cordatotriloba Dennst. is in the series Batatas (Khoury et al. 2015) and comprises three varieties (USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2018): var. australis (O’Donell) D.F.Austin, var. cordatotriloba and var. torreyana (A.Gray) D.F.Austin. The latter should not be recognised for this taxon (J.R.I. Wood pers. comm. 2018).

Ipomoea cordatotriloba is a tertiary genetic wild relative of Sweet Potato, I. batatas (L.) Lam. var. batatas (L.) Lam. (Vincent et al. 2013, USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2018).

Manihot aesculifolia Pohl is a gene pool secondary wild relative of Cassava, M. esculenta Crantz subsp. esculenta (Allem 2002, Vincent et al. 2013). However, according to USDA, ARS, GRIN (2017) it is a tertiary wild relative of Cassava based on the production of hybrids by polyploidization (Nassar and Ortiz 2009).
Manihot brachyloba Müll.Arg. is a gene pool secondary wild relative of cassava, M. esculenta Crantz ssp. esculenta (Vincent et al. 2013).
This species had a genus change in 2016 according to Poulsen et al., and should now be considered as Monacoa grimaldii. need to request change in SIS
The Trachipteridae family needs revision (Olney in press).

Controversy abounds over who deserves the credit for naming D. albus. Oken may have been responsible, but credit is usually given to Wied-Neuwied (1820) (Potchynok and Myers 2006). Populations in Central America may be distinct species referable to D. virgo but more study is needed (B.K. Lim pers. comm.).
This species was formerly considered a subspecies of greenhalli (e.g., Koopman 1994) but is apparently distinct, see Peters et al. (2002) and also see discussion in Simmons and Voss (1998).

Formerly it was treated as a subspecies of L. curasoae (see Simmons 2005). Arita and Humphrey (1988) determined that sanborni is a junior synonym of yerbabuenae and that yerbabuenae is a subspecies of L. curasoae. Koopman (in Wilson and Reeder 1993) used the name L. curasoae for the species occurring in the southwestern United States. Simmons (in Wilson and Reeder 2005) cited references supporting her listing of L. curasoae and L. yerbabuenae as distinct species; the latter species is the one occurring in the United States.
  
Prior to 1962 specimens of what was then known as L. sanborni were reported as L. nivalis.
This is a species complex of at least three species (Tavares pers. comm.), which was previously included in V. pusilla, and separated by Lim et al. (2003).
This species formerly was treated as a subspecies of M. bennettii (Simmons 2005).

This is part of the subgenus Artibeus. It includes palmarum and intermedius. It is not appropriate to treat intermedius as a subspecies of lituratus because it supposedly co-occurs with other populations of lituratus (referred to palmarum, which has priority) at several Central American localities. As there are no characters that unambiguously separate palmarum and intermedius, it seems most likely that intermedius simply represents individuals of palmarum that fall at the lower end of the normal range of size variation. Accordingly, intermediusis treated as a junior synonym of A. lituratus palmarum (Simmons 2005).

Larsen et al. (2007) examined the phylogenetics and phylogeography of the Jamaican fruit-eating bat (Artibeus jamaicensis). Results document that A. jamaicensis (sensu Simmons 2005) comprises 3 monophyletic assemblages. According to the mitochondrial DNA sequence variation, A. jamaicensis, A. schwartzi, and A. planirostris are appropriate species-level names for these lineages.

Subgenus Artibeus. Closely related to hirsutus but apparently distinct. See Webster and Jones (1983). This subgenus has been recognized as a distinct genus on molecular grounds (Lim et al. 2004), but there are no diagnostic morphological differences from Artibeus.
Formerly included in Artibeus
Subgenus Dermanura. This subgenus has been recognized as a separate genus on molecular grounds, but there are no diagnostic morphological differences from Artibeus (Lim et al. 2004).

This Middle American species has been associated to other names, including one from South America (like A. ravus; see Davis 1969). This could be the reason for the supposed presence of D. tolteca in Colombia (see Cuervo et al. 1986, Alberico et al. 2000), however, recent reviews don't support these claims (Solari et al. 2013).

The definition of this species has changed through the years and distinct researchers, Handley (1987) included A. ravus as a synonym, without further discussion, but previously Davis (1970) also synonymized other names under A. phaeotis. This view was kept by subsequent authors, like Simmons (2005). However, the molecular analyses by Solari et al. (2009) plus the side-by-side comparison of the type specimens (S. Solari pers. comm.) showed these two names represent distinct entities, and therefore valid species.

Artibeus aztecus - Subgenus Dermanura (Simmons 2005).
This genus has been recognized as a separate genus on molecular grounds (Lim et al. 2004), but there are no diagnostic morphological differences from Artibeus.

The previous (2008) assessment for this species was published under the genus Artibeus. This is an amended assessment, under the newly recognised genus Dermanura.

López-Wilchis et al. (2012) analyzed morphological and molecular characters to determine if two distinct species of Funnel-eared Bats (N. lanatus and N. mexicanus) occur in Mexico. They found that the proposed diagnostic morphological characters that separate the two taxa are not consistent and rarely differentiate between the two forms. Likewise, phylogenetic analyses do not support the separation of Natalus into two species in Mexico, but there is clearly geographic structure when all Mexican haplotypes are combined into N. mexicanus. The results of both morphological and molecular analyses point to the presence of a single species of Natalus in Mexico.

Karyotypic and genetic studies of a population of Rhogeessa io from western Ecuador, revealed that the form referred to as R. io velilla should be treated as a valid species (Baird et al. 2008).
