The taxonomy and systematic of Central American brocket deer has been studied by morphological data of collections and cytogenetic analysis, with locality type Mirador Veracruz México by Hershkovitz (1951). This is considered by some authors as a subspecies of Mazama americana (Hershkovitz, 1951). But currently M. temama has been raised to species status (Geist 1998). Tate (1939) classified red brocket deer in two groups (large and small brockets) and allied M. temama in with the small brockets division with a distribution in Central America. Groves and Grubb (1987) also were of the opinion that it be granted species status mainly due to the old karyotype data of Jorge and Benirschke (1977) who segregated it by its karyotype of 2n=50 from Mazama americana which has 2n=68-70. M. t. cerasina and M. t. reperticia are recognized subspecies of M. temama.

Morphological and molecular analyses by Spradling et al. (2016) resulted in resurrection of the genus Heterogeomys, to which the species cherriei is now assigned (as Heterogeomys cherriei). The former species Orthogeomys matagalpae has been synonymized under Heterogeomys cherriei, resulting in four currently recognized subspecies: H. c. carlosensis, H. c. cherriei, H. c. costaricensis, and H. c. matagalpae (Hafner 2016). The addition of matagalpae to cherriei dramatically increases the geographic distribution of Heterogeomys cherriei.
Synonymized under Heteromys: Hafner et al. (2007) confirmed paraphyly of Liomys relative to Heteromys, placing Liomys in synonymy with Heteromys.
Until recently this taxon was a subspecies of C. parva, but it was given species rank by Woodman (2002).
This taxon was until recently considered a subspecies of parva, but is included in Hutterer (2005), and hence here as a species. This species is monotypic (Carraway 2014).

The characters thought to differentiate Zenion longipinnis from Z. hololepis are erroneous. The course of the lateral line is the same for both species. The isthmus of Z. hololepis is completely scaly, but scales were missing on the holotype from abrasion in the trawl. The membrane joining the pelvic-fin spine to the rays is fragile and easily torn in trawl-caught specimens (Heemstra in press).

Ma and Craig (2018) revised the classification of groupers, concluding that there are now nine genera: Alphestes, Cephalopholis (subsuming Aethaloperca, Gracila, and Paranthias), Dermatolepis, Epinephelus (sensu stricto), Gonioplectrus, Hyporthodus (subsuming Triso dermopterus, with the addition of three species previously placed in Epinephelus), Mycteroperca (with the addition of 11 species previously placed in Epinephelus), Plectropomus (subsuming Saloptia), and Variola.

Hybrid specimens of Cephalopholis fulva and C. furcifer have been observed in the Brazilian oceanic islands of Trindade (Pinheiro et al. 2009), Atol das Rocas (Batista et al. 2012) and Fernando de Noronha (B. P. Ferreira and A.A. Bertoncini pers. comm. 2016) and in the North Atlantic from Cuba and Bermuda (Smith 1966, Bostrom et al. 2002). These were initially described by Poey in 1860 and 1875 as Menephorus dubius and M. punctiferus (Smith 1966, Bostrom et al. 2002).

The West Indian Manatee (Trichechus manatus) is currently divided into two subspecies: the Florida Manatee (T. m. latirostris) and the Antillean Manatee (T. m. manatus) (Hatt 1934, Domning and Hayek 1986).  The mtDNA data (García-Rodríguez et al. 1998) and molecular data (Vianna et al. 2006) revealed a population structure with three distinctive lineages corresponding geographically with: (1) Florida, Mexico, the Greater Antilles, Central America, and the Caribbean coast of South America; (2) Mexico, Central America, and the Caribbean coast of South America; and (3) NE South America from Guyana to Brazil. Evidence exists for viable hybridisation with T. inunguis near the mouth of the Amazon River, Guyana, French Guiana, and possibly Suriname (Lima et al. 2019).

Recent cranial and chromosomal geographic variation data from Antillean manatees in Brazil show morphological discontinuity and chromosomal divergence within T. m. manatus and the Brazilian population south of the Amazon. These data suggest that the current taxonomy of T. manatus needs to be revised (Barros et al. 2016).

As this Red List assessment was being submitted for publication, we were made aware of a paper by Mignucci-Giannoni et al. (2024) that proposes to standardise the vernacular names for Trichechus manatus and subspecies across five languages. The proposed common names in English are: American Manatee instead of West Indian Manatee for T. manatus; Florida Manatee as it currently is used for T. manatus latirostris; and Greater Caribbean Manatee instead of Antillean Manatee for T. manatus manatus. We have left the existing common names in this assessment, as they are well-established and associated with various federal and state legislation, but recognise that there may be support to change those names in the future.

A systematic revision is necessary. According to Hall (1981) there are 24 recognized subspecies: Sylvilagus floridanus alacer, S. f. ammophilus, S. f. aztecus, S. f. chapmani, S. f. chiapensis, S. f. cognatus, S. f. connectens, S. f. costaricensis, S. f. floridanus, S. f. hesperius, S. f. hitchensi, S. f. holzneri, S. f. hondurensis, S. f. llanensis, S. f. mallurus, S. f. mearnsii, S. f. orizabae, S. f. paulsoni, S. f. restrictus, S. f. robustus, S. f. russatus, S. f. similis, S. f. subcinctus, and S. f. yucatanicus.

Chapman et al. (1980) also included S. f. avius, S. f. continentis, S. f. cumanicus, S. f. margaritae, S. f. nelsoni, S. f. nigronuchalis, S. f. orinoci, S. f. purgatus, S. f. superciliaris, and S. f. valenciae.

The subspecies S. f. cognatus and S. f. robustus have been designated as independent species (Hoffmann and Smith 2005) since the publication of Hall (1981).
The genus Bassaricyon was revised by Helgen et al. (2013).

Conepatus leuconotus and C. mesoleucus formerly were regarded as distinct species (e.g. Jones et al. 1992). Dragoo et al. (2003) examined morphological and molecular characters of Conepatus skunks and determined that (1) C. mesoleucus is not a species distinct from C. leuconotus, (2) Conepatus subspecies texensis, mearnsi, mesoleucus , nelsoni, venaticus, nicaraguae, sonoriensis, and filipensis should be lumped as C. leuconotus leuconotus , (3) subspecies figginsi and fremonti should be lumped as C. l. figginsi, and (4) C. mesoleucus telmalestes should be regarded as C. leuconotus telmalestes. They suggested that further genetic research might indicate that figginsi and telmalestes are not valid taxa but that the populations they represent (if not extinct) will require different management strategies from the wide-ranging C. l. leuconotus. Wozencraft (2005) included mesoleucus in C. leuconotus.

While many authors have traditionally considered skunks a subfamily (Mephitinae) within Mustelidae, recent molecular evidence indicates that skunks do not lie within the mustelid group and should be recognised as a single family, Mephitidae (Wozencraft 2005).

While many authors have traditionally considered skunks a subfamily (Mephitinae) within Mustelidae, recent molecular evidence indicates that skunks do not lie within the mustelid family and should be recognised as a separate family, Mephitidae (Wozencraft 2005).
Includes Nasua nelsoni (see Decker and Wozencraft 1991).
Includes the Caribbean introduced populations of gloveralleni, minor, and maynardi after Helgen and Wilson (2003); includes insularis after Helgen and Wilson (2005).

Owen et al. (1996) examined the karyotypes of two each of S. putorius interrupta and S. putorius tropicalis, the results of which Wozencraft (2005) stated supported the recognition of S. angustifrons (containing tropicalis) as a species distinct from S. putorius (containing interrupta). This treatment was followed by Dragoo (2009).

California Sea Lions were once considered a subspecies of Zalophus californianus (Z. c. californianus) by many authors, but Rice (1998) argued that Z. californianus, Z. japonicus, and Z. wollebaeki are distinct species. Other studies have confirmed the separate species status of Z. japonicus and Z. californianus (Brunner 2004, Sakahira and Niimi 2007) and the separation of Z. californianus and Z. wollebaeki (Wolf et al. 2007).
Although several geographic populations have been named as species, morphological and genetic data show there is one world-wide panmictic species (Gibbs and Collette 1967, Scoles and Graves 1993).

Mitochondrial DNA restriction analysis reveals that genetic differentiation occurs between populations inhabiting the Mediterranean Sea and the tropical Atlantic Ocean, indicating that little genetic exchange occurs between the two (Kotoulas et al. 1995).

Recent study of mitochondrial DNA by Viñas et al. (2010) found further differentiation between populations in the eastern and western Mediterranean Sea.
Some authors have included Skipjack Tuna in the genus Euthynnus, but recent authors agree with its placement in the monotypic genus Katsuwonus (Collette and Graves 2019).
This species previously was included in the genus Makaira (Collette et al. 2006).

There is no genetic evidence in the mtDNA control region to indicate that the Atlantic (Istiophorus albicans) and Indo-Pacific (Istiophorus platypterus) Sailfishes are separate species (Collette et al. 2006). However, there are two distinct mtDNA clades, both evident in the Atlantic while only one is found in the Indo-Pacific (McDowell 2002). There is also no difference in pectoral fin length or in any other morphometric or meristic characters between the Atlantic and Indo-Pacific populations of sailfish (Morrow and Harbo 1969, McDowell 2002).

Prior to 1960, many authors included including Auxis rochei in Auxis thazard, in the belief that there was only a single worldwide species of Auxis. This species contains two subspecies: the widespread Auxis thazard thazard and Auxis thazard brachydorax (Collette and Aadland 1996).

Before 1960, many researchers thought that there was only one species (with a global distribution) in the genus Auxis, which was recorded as Auxis thazard (Collette and Aaland 1996). Auxis rochei contains two subspecies:  A. r. rochei (Risso, 1810), which occurs worldwide except for in the eastern tropical Pacific where it is replaced by A. r. eudorax (Collette and Aadland 1996).
Craig and Hastings (2007) changed the generic name of this species from Epinephelus to Hyporthodus. The family name was changed to Epinephelidae by Smith and Craig (2007).
Craig and Hastings (2007) changed the generic name from Epinephelus to Hyporthodus and Smith and Craig (2007) changed the family name to Epinephelidae.

There is an ongoing discussion on the validity of the hamlets as biological species (Domeier 1994). Hamlet "species" are defined primarily on differences in color patterns. They are known to interbreed and hybridize freely with very little consistent genetic differentiation amongst them.
The genus Thunnus is divisible into two subgenera, Thunnus and Neothunnus, but the Bigeye Tuna does not neatly fit in either subgenus (Collette and Graves 2019).
Craig and Hastings (2007) changed the generic name of this species to Hyporthodus, and Smith and Craig (2007) changed the family name to Epinephelidae.
This species is frequently confused with Coryphopterus personatus; C. hyalinus and C. personatus are genetically distinct (Baldwin et al. 2009).
Tetrapturus pfluegeri was confused with the eastern Atlantic T. belone, until it was described as a distinct species by Robins and de Sylva (1963).

Blue Marlin (Makaira nigricans) of the Indo-Pacific and the Atlantic are conspecific (Buonaccorsi et al. 1999, 2001; Collette et al. 2006). The Indo-Pacific Blue Marlin previously was known as Makaira mazara (Jordan & Snyder, 1901).

Previously, this species was known as Tetrapturus albidus (Collette et al. 2006). There is a question as to whether this species is distinct from the Pacific Striped Marlin, Kajikia audax (Graves 1998, Collette et al. 2006, Hanner et al. 2011).

Literature records before1978 for Scomberomorus maculatus from the Caribbean and the Atlantic coasts of Central and South America apply to Scomberomorus brasiliensis, which were previously indentified as Scomberomorus maculatus by many authors (Collette and Russo 1985, Banford et al. 1999).
This species was redescribed four times in the same publication by Cuvier in Cuvier and Valenciennes (1832).

According to Sporre et al. (2024), Emblemaria pandionis does not comprise a single taxonomic unit found throughout the Caribbean, but instead is a species complex with multiple operational taxonomic units (OTUs). According to Sporre et al. (2024), this species is deeply divergent with isolated and independently evolving lineages in the southern Caribbean, central Caribbean, Florida and Gulf of Mexico, with the populations at Flower Garden Banks representing its own endemic taxonomic unit.

This species was originally described as Syngnathus dendriticum by Thomas Barbour in 1905. The genus Amphelikturus was subsequently described by Parr (1930), with this species subsumed within it. Dawson (1984) later subsumed Amphelikturus and Idiotropiscis as subgenera of Acentronura based on morphology. However, Hamilton et al. 2017 phylogenetically recovered the species as nested within an Atlantic clade of pipefish, all sharing an Atlantic ancestor. Currently, the accepted name for the species is Amphelikturus dendritica (Fricke et al. 2024).
This species should not to be confused with Briggs’ Crested Pipefish (Histiogamphelus briggsii), which is found in southern Australia.
This species was recently resurrected from synonymy under S. foetens (Frable et al. 2013).

This species was previously considered a synonym of E. plumieri by Deckert (1973), Deckert and Geenfield (1987), and González-Acosta (2005), because the original description was based on juveniles of this species.  Eugerres awlae has been re-described and considered a valid gerreid species from the western Atlantic by González-Acosta et al. (2007). It was recently reviewed in 2014 with conclusion that this species is valid (R. Robertson pers. comm. 2015).
The wide range of C. centralis might be obscuring the presence of locally distributed forms that may constitute separate species.
There are seven subspecies of Cyclopes didactylus (Gardner 2007).
Six subspecies are recognized by Gardner (2007).
Three subspecies are recognized by Gardner (2007).

Gardner (2005) recognizes four subspecies of T. mexicana (T. m. mexicana, T. m. opistholeuca, T. m. instabilis, and T. m. punensis). It is likely that further taxonomic work is needed for this species.
This species is also reported as Lophotus lacepedei (Quignard and Tomasini 2000).

This species is commonly confused with Laemonema barbatulum, particularly when small. This introduces uncertainty in assessing the distribution and habitat utilization of L. goodebeanorum (S. Ross pers. comm. 2018).
The genus Hypleurochilus is considered to be paraphyletic, with many species within this genus being poorly known and having a history of significant taxonomic confusion (Carter et al. 2023).

Some workers consider the correct genus of this species to be Tigrigobius. The genus Tigrigobius is currently defined as not monophyletic and will at some point be divided into two or more genera (J. Van Tassell pers. comm. 2015).

Neobythites ocellatus was recently split into two species based on differences in color patterns, which resulted in the naming of a new species (Neobythites multiocellatus) and restricted the distribution of N. ocellatus to Brazil between 233-641m depth (Nielsen et al. 2009).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus kalisherae to the genus Gobioclinus.

This species was previously considered to be a subspecies of Ophioblennius atlanticus under the name O. atlanticus macclurei (Lastrucci et al. 2018). However, O. atlanticus has since been divided into five distinct species: O. atlanticus (from Azores, Madeira, the Canary Islands, and Cape Verde), O. macclurei (from the Caribbean), O. trinitatis (from Brazil), and two undescribed species (one from São Tomé and Príncipe in the Gulf of Guinea and Santa Catarina, Brazil and the other from Ascension and St. Helena in the Mid-Atlantic islands; Lastrucci et al. 2018).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus filamentosus to the genus Gobioclinus.
Individuals of this species have been regularly misidentified as Emblemariopsis bottomei (Victor 2020).
This species was previously considered a subspecies of Stathmonotus stahli (Hastings and Springer 2009).

Attention RLU: This species needs a new taxonomic concept created since Emblemariopsis arawak was synonymized under E. leptocirris by Victor 2020.

Emblemariopsis arawak is now a synonym of E. leptocirris (Victor 2020).
Previously it was believed that Belize was abundant with Emblemariopsis signifera but according to DNA surveys and collections,E. signifera is not found in the Caribbeans (Victor 2020). Rather, specimens previously cited as E. signifera in Belize instead represent the initial phase of either this species or of E. dianae (Victor 2020).
Species within the Emblemariopsis genus are poorly known and poorly represented in museum collections because of their small size, mostly transparent bodies, and preference for hole-dwelling habitats (Victor 2020). Descriptions of species within this genus are often based on adult male specimens, and due to significant sexual dimorphism, females and immature specimens are often mistaken as different species (Victor 2020).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus bucciferus to the genus Gobioclinus.
Scartella cristata is generally recognized to be a species complex. The eastern Atlantic and Brazilian populations may represent separate species (J.T. Williams pers. comm. 2009).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus gobio to the genus Gobioclinus.
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus guppyi to the genus Gobioclinus.
This species was formerly a subspecies of Dactyloscopus pectoralis (Hastings and Springer 2009).

Baldwin et al. (2011) revealed that most broadly distributed species of Starksia are comprised of a complex of species with discrete distributions. Assignment to a specific species requires barcode data for specimens outside the type locality. Since no barcode data are available for the Gulf of Mexico, all that can be concluded is that the Gulf of Mexico population is a member of the S. nanodes species complex (B. Smith-Vaniz and R. Robertson pers. comm. 2015).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus albigenys to the genus Brockius.

Labrisomus nuchipinnis is likely a species complex and there is only one species in the Gulf of Mexico (J. Williams pers. comm. 2014). The holotype of L. nuchipinnis is from Brazil, so the name will change.
Malacoctenus triangulatus is a species complex and taxonomic work is needed.
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus nigricinctus to the genus Brockius.
Many pictures identified as Acanthemblemaria maria in guidebooks and on the internet are actually A. spinosa (R. Eytan pers. comm. 2007).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus haitiensis to the genus Gobioclinus.
A large number of synonyms have been described for this widespread and introduced taxon.

Until the 1990s, only one species of Minke Whale was recognized, the Antarctic Minke Whale, Balaenoptera bonaerensis, being regarded as conspecific with the Common Minke Whale, B. acutorostrata. Most of the scientific literature prior to the late 1990s uses the name B. acutorostrata for all Minke Whales including Antarctic Minke Whales. Since 2000, the International Whaling Commission (IWC) Scientific Committee has recognized Antarctic Minke Whales as the separate species B. bonaerensis, and provisionally assigns all Northern Hemisphere Minke Whales and all Southern Hemisphere "Dwarf" Minke Whales to B. acutorostrata (IWC 2001). This practice has been followed by management and treaty bodies, such as the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES).

The Dwarf Minke Whale is the common name used for B. acutorostrata in the Southern Hemisphere. It was initially described by Best (1985) and Arnold et al. (1987) in terms of its differences from the Antarctic Minke Whale. Subsequent genetic analyses (Wada et al. 1991, Pastene et al. 1994) revealed that the Dwarf Minke Whale is conspecific with the "ordinary" Minke Whale of the Northern Hemisphere, which was given the name Common Minke Whale, while the Antarctic Minke Whale is the separate species B. bonaerensis (see separate Red List assessment).

Following Rice (1998) the Committee on Taxonomy of the Society for Marine Mammalogy provisionally recognizes three subspecies: B. a. acutorostrata (Lacépède, 1804) in the North Atlantic, B. a. scammoni (Deméré, 1986) (= B. a . davidsoni) in the North Pacific, and the Dwarf Minke Whale as an unnamed subspecies in the Southern Hemisphere (Committee on Taxonomy 2017). However, the limited sampling of Dwarf Minke Whales to date does not support the grouping together of all Southern Hemisphere Dwarf Minke Whales. For example, Pastene et al. (2010) found Dwarf Minke Whales from Brazil and Chile to be more closely related to Common Minke Whales in the North Atlantic than to Dwarf Minke Whales in the South Pacific.

Rice’s Whale (Balaenoptera ricei) is a distinct evolutionary lineage closely related to Eden’s Whale (Balaenoptera edeni edeni), Bryde’s Whale (B. e. brydei) and Sei Whale (Balaenoptera borealis) (Rosel et al. 2021). Previously considered an undescribed subspecies of Balaenoptera edeni and referred to as the Gulf of Mexico Whale or the Gulf of Mexico Bryde’s Whale, a recent morphological study of Rice’s Whale has revealed diagnostic differences in the shape and size of bones in the skull in comparison to the two subspecies of B. edeni. This morphological evidence reinforced earlier findings of significant genetic divergence and fixed DNA differences found in several mitochondrial DNA genes; together these data supported the description of the new species B. ricei . With elevation of Rice’s Whale to species status, there is still uncertainty as to whether Eden’s Whale and Bryde’s Whale, each of which is clearly distinct, represent subspecies of B. edeni or full species.
Pygmy Killer Whales (Feresa attenuata) are easily confused with Melon-Headed Whales (Peponocephala electra) in the field because of their similar external morphology (Jefferson et al. 2015).

Two forms of Short-finned Pilot Whales (Globicephala macrorhynchus) are found off northern and southern Japan, differing in external and cranial morphology (Kasuya et al. 1988, Van Cise et al. 2016). Although it has been suggested that these might represent two distinct subspecies (Oremus et al. 2009), evidence has not been marshalled to make this distinction official and no subspecies of Short-finned Pilot Whale are currently recognized (Van Cise et al. 2016, Committee on Taxonomy 2017).
The genus Grampus contains a single species, the Risso’s Dolphin (Grampus griseus). No subspecies are recognized (Committee on Taxonomy 2021).

The genus Kogia contains two species, the Pygmy Sperm Whale (Kogia breviceps) and Dwarf Sperm Whale (Kogia sima), with no subspecies recognized (Committee on Taxonomy 2021). The cryptic behavior and similar external morphology of the two species mean that records are often not displayed at the species level and are instead combined into Kogia spp. It has been suggested that K. sima may consist of two parapatric species occupying the Atlantic and Indo-Pacific Oceans, based on evidence from the mitochondrial cytochrome b gene (Chivers et al. 2005). K. breviceps and K. sima are clearly distinguished genetically, but full recognition of a putative third Kogia spp. awaits further supporting evidence (Chivers et al. 2005).

The genus Kogia contains two species, the Dwarf Sperm Whale (Kogia sima) and Pygmy Sperm Whale (Kogia breviceps), with no subspecies recognized (Committee on Taxonomy 2021). The cryptic behavior and similar external morphology of the two species mean that records are often not displayed at the species level and are instead combined into Kogia spp. It has been suggested that K. sima may consist of two parapatric species occupying the Atlantic and Indo-Pacific Oceans, based on evidence from the mitochondrial cytochrome b gene (Chivers et al. 2005). K. breviceps and K. sima are clearly distinguished genetically, but full recognition of a putative third Kogia spp. awaits further supporting evidence (Chivers et al. 2005).
Fraser’s Dolphin was described in 1956 and the external appearance of this species was not known until 1971 (Perrin et al. 1973).

The Committee on Taxonomy of the Society for Marine Mammalogy recognizes three subspecies of Humpback Whale: the nominate subspecies M. n. novaeangliae (Borowski, 1781) refers to the North Atlantic Humpback Whale; M. n. australis (Lesson, 1828) is the Southern (Hemisphere) Humpback Whale; and M. n. kuzira (Gray, 1850) is the North Pacific Humpback Whale (Committee on Taxonomy 2021). This is based on the finding that Humpback Whales in the three ocean basins, although not separate clades, appear to be on diverging genetic trajectories (Jackson et al. 2014).
Blainville’s Beaked Whales (Mesoplodon densirostris) is one of 15 species of Mesoplodon with a worldwide range in tropical and warm-temperate waters. No subspecies are currently recognized.

Mesoplodon peruvianus was first described in 1991 (Reyes et al. 1991) based on specimens from Peru. Prior to that, beginning in the late 1970s, there had been numerous sightings of a distinctively patterned, but unidentified, mesoplodont during regular cetacean surveys in the eastern tropical Pacific. These were originally referred to in the survey sighting records and earlier publications as “Mesoplodon sp. A” (Pitman et al. 1987), but after the description of M. peruvianus, it was suggested that M. sp. A was, in fact, M. peruvianus (Pitman and Lynn 2001). This contention was later confirmed by genetic analysis of a fresh-stranded Mesoplodon in western Mexico with the same diagnostic color pattern (Urbán et al. 2013).

This taxonomic unit is treated as a single species even though there is extensive and growing evidence that it is, in fact, a complex of multiple forms with morphological, genetic, ecological, and behavioural differences that merit subspecies if not also species designations. At the time of writing (June 2017), the Committee on Taxonomy of the Society for Marine Mammalogy (www.marinemammalscience.org/species-information/list-marine-mammal-species-subspecies), which is generally regarded as the authority for marine mammal taxonomy, recognized a single killer whale species, Orcinus orca (Linnaeus, 1758), and two unnamed subspecies in the eastern North Pacific, the ENP resident killer whale (O. o. un-named subsp.) and the ENP transient Killer Whale (O. o. un-named subsp.) also known as Bigg’s Killer Whale. The Committee noted, however, “Other forms of killer whales in the North Pacific, North Atlantic and Antarctic [Southern] Ocean may warrant recognition as separate subspecies or even species, but the taxonomy has not yet been fully clarified or agreed (Morin et al. 2010; Foote et al. 2009, 2013).” One population (a “distinct population segment”) of the ENP resident subspecies (the “southern resident” population) was listed as Endangered under the Canadian Species at Risk Act in 2003 and the U.S. Endangered Species Act in 2005.

No subspecies of the Melon-headed Whale (Peponocephala electra) are currently recognized (Committee on Taxonomy 2018). This species is morphologically similar to the Pygmy Killer Whale and the two species can be easily confused in the field.  Although they sometimes form resident populations around oceanic islands, Melon-headed Whales show low levels of genetic differentiation both within and between ocean basins, suggesting high levels of population connectivity (Martien et al. 2017).

The genus Stenella is paraphyletic, and it is likely that the Delphininae will be restructured in the coming years (LeDuc et al. 1999, Perrin et al. 2013). Two subspecies are recognized: S. attenuata attenuata in oceanic tropical waters worldwide, and S. a. graffmani in the coastal waters of the eastern tropical Pacific (ETP) (Jefferson et al. 2015, Perrin 2018).

The Clymene Dolphin (Stenella clymene) is likely to have evolved through a case of hybrid speciation, involving widespread hybridization of Spinner (S. longirostris) and Striped (S. coeruleoalba) Dolphins (Amaral et al., 2014). Recent genetic work suggests that the genus Stenella is paraphyletic, and it is likely that taxonomy of the Delphinidae will be restructured in coming years (LeDuc et al. 1999, Perrin et al. 2013). This species might even move to a different genus. Coloration differences between the Clymene Dolphins in the eastern and western Atlantic Ocean suggest possible population structuring, although this remains unconfirmed (Weir et al. 2014).

The Striped Dolphin (Stenella coeruleoalba) is recognized as a single species worldwide, with subspecies recognized (Committee on Taxonomy 2021). However, the genus Stenella is possibly paraphyletic, and it is likely that the Delphininae will be restructured in coming years (LeDuc et al. 1999, Perrin et al. 2013).

Recent molecular work suggests that the genus Stenella is paraphyletic, and it is likely that the Delphininae (the subfamily to which the species currently belongs) will be restructured in coming years, at which point this species may be assigned to a different genus (LeDuc et al. 1999, Perrin et al. 2013). Some evidence suggests a close relationship with the Indo-Pacific bottlenose dolphin (Tursiops aduncus) (Jefferson et al. 2015). There is a large, heavy form of Atlantic Spotted Dolphin found along the coasts on both sides of the Atlantic (formerly called Stenella plagiodon along the U.S. coast), while a smaller form that is lightly spotted or unspotted as an adult occurs in the Gulf Stream and the central North Atlantic (Perrin et al. 1987, Viallelle 1997, Herzing and Perrin 2018).

Cuvier’s Beaked Whale (Ziphius cavirostris) is the only species in the monotypic genus Ziphius (Rice 1998, Dalebout et al. 2005). During the 19th century numerous specimens of Cuvier’s Beaked Whales were described as new species but none of them have been accepted as valid and a single species is recognized to occur throughout its range.

This species was originally included in the genus Mesoplodon (Longman 1926), but based on morphological features, Moore (1968) created the monotypic genus Indopacetus. There has been debate about the validity of this genus (e.g., Mead 1989, Rice 1998), and, although Dalebout et al. (2003) were unable to validate Indopacetus based on available genetic evidence, they recommended retention of the genus based on morphological features. Prior to descriptions of its field characteristics, sightings in tropical waters of what are now known to be this species were sometimes mistakenly attributed to the genus Hyperoodon (Pitman et al. 1999, Dalebout et al. 2003).

Taxonomy is currently under review by the IUCN SSC Cat Specialist Group.  Johnson et al. (2006) and Eizirik et al. (2008) placed yagouaroundi in the genus Puma. However, Agnarsson et al. (2010) noted that the Jaguarundi is not a sister species to the Puma. More recently Segura et al. (2013) looked at cranial development within the Puma clade and found that while this is similar in Cheetah and Puma, that of the Jaguarundi is quite different. Given these phylogenetic uncertainties, and these and other morphological and behavioural differences, the IUCN SSC Cat Specialist Group retains this species in Herpailurus.

Taxonomy is currently under review by the IUCN SSC Cat Specialist Group. This species is genetically very diverse across its range and shows a high degree of population structure, with three distinct clusters: Central America and Mexico, northern South America and southern South America. The demarcation between northern and southern South America was identified as the Amazon river. In Central America, there were weaker differences between populations from the north (Mexico and Guatemala) and those from the south of this region (Eizirik et al. 1998).

This is a restricted concept of this species following the split of the broader concept into this and Bolitoglossa nympha (Campbell et al. 2010) and B. chinateca (Rovito et al. 2012). The records from Los Tuxtlas may represent another species (Rovito et al. 2012).

Brodie et al. (2012) described this species from a locality in the Guatemalan portion of Cerro Montecristo. A series of morphologically similar salamanders is available from the Honduran side of Cerro Montecristo. DNA data from one of those Honduran specimens was reported on by García-París and Wake (2000; as Oedipina sp. B). McCranie (2006) and McCranie and Castañeda (2007) had identified those salamanders as O. ignea. There is no reason to expect that the Honduran Cerro Montecristo species is not conspecific with those on the Guatemalan side of that same mountain range (although the Guatemalan locality for this species is in open pine forest [see Brodie et al. 2012, 238] and the Honduran locality assigned to O. chortiorum were found in Mesic broadleaf forest.
Mendelson et al. (2005) recently separated I. pisinnus (endemic to Mexico), I. porteri (endemic to Honduras), and I. signifer (endemic to Panama) from I. coccifer.
This species was previously within the genus Hyla but has recently been moved to the resurrected genus Dendropsophus (Faivovich et al. 2005).
This species was previously within the genus Hyla but has recently been moved to the new genus Tlalocohyla (Faivovich et al. 2005).
This species was previously within the genus Hyla but has recently been moved to the genus Tlalocohyla (Faivovich et al. 2005).

This is a restricted concept of this species following the split of the broader concept into this and Plectrohyla calvata (McCranie 2017). Some of the Honduran subpopulations may belong to other species and further taxonomic work is needed (C. Vásquez Almazán pers. comm. August 2019).

This species is possibly a species complex, and further taxonomic work needs to be carried out to verify the identity of Honduran and Guatamalan subpopulations (Duellman and Campbell 1992, J. Townsend pers. comm. March 2019).

This is a restricted concept of Smilisca baudinii following the split of the broader concept into this and Smilisca manisorum (McCranie 2017). In Costa Rica, S. baudinii occurs on the Pacific versant and S. manisorum occurs on the Atlantic versant; however, additional taxonomic research is needed on these two taxa (F. Bolaños pers. comm. September 2019).

This species was previously within the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005). This is a restricted concept of Craugastor laticeps following the split of the broader concept into this and Craugastor castanedai (McCranie 2018).
This species was previously within the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith, 2005). We follow Lynch (2000) in separating this species from C. rhodopis.
This species was previously within the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).

This species was known as Leptodactylus fragilis for many years until Heyer (1978) determined that L. labialis and L. fragilis represent the same species and that the former was the correct name based on publication priority. However, Heyer (2002) later determined that Leptodactylus fragilis is in fact the valid scientific name for the species. The concept is likely to be a species complex (C. Señaris pers. comm. February 2020).

In the Edentulus clade of Ron et al. (2006). There are two well-supported allopatric clades within Engystomops pustulosus, each occupying one of two disjunct portions of the distribution range of this species (Ron et al. 2006).
This species is a complex of several species (K.-H. Jungfer pers. comm.). It was resurrected from the synonymy of Lithobates palmipes by Hillis and de Sá (1988).
This species is probably a complex of several cryptic forms (García-París et al. 2000). The taxonomic status of this species is likely to change in the near future (S. Rovito pers. comm. 2007).
The conspecificity of the disjunct populations needs to be assessed.

Dawson (1985) recognizes three subspecies, Doryrhamphus excisus abbreviatus (from the Red Sea), D. e. excisus (pan-Indo-Pacific), and D. e. paulus (endemic to the Revillagigedo Islands off the west coast of Mexico). In contemporary literature subspecific designations are no longer followed but as Dawson (1985) recommended more research is needed to understand the systematic status of these populations. All are treated here as subspecies of D. excisus.
Attention RLU: This species is now considered a synonym of Pocillopora grandis. For reference please see WoRMS: http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=206958. C. Linardich 5Jan2022
Hyalinobatrachium cardiacalyptum has been synonymized under this species by Cisneros-Heredia and McDiarmid (2007).

Hyalinobatrachium crybetes has been made a synonym of this species, although the Honduran subpopulation previously assigned to H. crybetes needs to be confirmed using fresh material, as it either belongs to H. colymbiphyllum or H. fleischmanni (Cisneros-Heredia and McDiarmid 2007).

This species was previously included in the genus Hyla but has recently been moved to the new genus Ecnomiohyla (Faivovich et al. 2005). We follow Duellman (2001) and Savage (2002) in assigning records from Colombia and Ecuador to Ecnomiohyla phantasmagoria.

Ecnomiohyla miliaria is currently a species complex which is under revision (B. Kubicki pers. comm.).

It is not clear that records from Colombia refer to the same species as those in Central America, in part, because of the large gap in the distribution (K.-H. Jungfer pers. comm.). It is possible that this is a complex of two or three species (Federico Bolaños pers. comm.).

This is a restricted concept of this species following the split of the broader concept into this and Craugastor metriosistus [which was split from this species and C. longirostris and C. raniformis] (Ospina-Sarria et al. 2015).
It is uncertain that all populations within its range are conspecific.
Separated from Leptodactylus pentadactylus following Heyer (2005).
There is an ongoing debate on the genus placement of this species (J. Townsend pers. comm. March 2019).
Research is required to evaluate the relationship between this species and Incilius leucomyos to determine whether they are distinct (J. Townsend pers. comm. March 2019).

This species was previously included in the genus Hyla but has recently been moved to the resurrected genus Exerodonta (Faivovich et al. 2005). Faivovich et al. (2018) discussed the tentative nature of the assignment of this species to Exerodonta, and the generic assignment is currently under revision (J. Townsend pers. comm. March 2019).
This species was previously included in the genus Hyla but has recently been moved to the new genus Isthmohyla (Faivovich et al. 2005).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
This species was previously within the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
