This species was previously within the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
This is a restricted concept of this species following the split of the broader concept into this and Craugastor gutschei (McCranie 2018).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
The taxonomy of this species is currently under revision, and it is likely that the distribution of this species will be restricted in the future (Townsend et al. in review March 2019).
This is a restricted concept of this species following the split of the broader concept into this, Nototriton nelsoni and N. oreadorum (Townsend 2016).

The taxonomy of this species is confused (Wake pers. comm.). The Brodie et al. (2012) descriptions of Oedipina chortiorum and O. tzutujilorum from Guatemala calls into question the identity of the Honduran salamanders previously identified as O. ignea. There appear to be discrete differences between the salamanders from mesic broadleaf forest in Ocotepeque and those from open pine forests in Intibucá and La Paz (McCranie pers. obs.). Further morphological and genetic study of the Guatemalan topotypic O. chortiorum and those of the Honduran Intibucá and La Paz subpopulations (ca. O. ignea) would likely reveal that either the Ocotepeque subpopulations or those from Intibucá and La Paz need a new name. Another nominal form to consider in this problem is the Brodie et al. (2012) description of O. tzutujilorum from a mesic broadleaf forest on the Pacific versant of Guatemala (McCranie 2015).
This species has been separated from Incilius coccifer by Mendelson et al. (2005), although McCranie and Wilson (2002) dispute this.
This species was previously within the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).

Costus lima was described by K. Schumann in 1902 Pflanzenreich.  The species has long-appendaged reddish bracts, usually pendent, and pink to yellow tubular flowers. There are two formally described varieties.  Var. lima is distinguished by having the upper side of leaves and the bract appendages scabrid to the touch, with thickened, appressed hairs.  Its neotype was collected in Costa Rica west of Puerto Limon.  Var. scabremarginatus was described by Paul Maas in his 1972 monograph.  It is distinguished by the leaves being only somewhat scabrid towards the margins.  Its type is from Venezuela.  Dr. Maas mentioned several other collections with glabrous leaves, but are not formally described as varieties.

Costus villosissimus was described in 1809 from a collection by Surian on the island of St. Vincent in the Lessor Antilles.  C. villosissimus is easily recognized by its villose vegetative parts, bracts with leafy green appendages, and broad yellow flowers.  There are no taxonomic issues concerning this species.
This species has two varieties: Cordia sebestena L. var. sebestena and Cordia sebestena L. var. caymanensis (Urb.) Proctor.

Proctor (2012) states that the Central American plants have a different coloured fruit and may be considered another species. According to Proctor (2012), the plants identified as C. laevigata from the Lesser Antilles differ in corolla shape and may possibly be a different species. A detailed taxonomic investigation is needed.
This species has two subspecies, Varronia bullata L. subsp. bullata and Varronia bullata L. subsp. humilis (Jacq.) Feuillet.
Echinochloa polystachya  (Kunth) Hitche is a gene pool tertiary wild relative of White millet/ Siberian millet (Echinochloa frumenlacca Link) (Vincent et al. 2013)
Pristis pristis was formerly known as P. perotteti in the Atlantic and sometimes in the Eastern Pacific, and P. microdon in the Indo-West Pacific. These are both now synonyms of P. pristis.

The placement of this species in the Macrouridae is not supported by current morphological and genetic analyses; rather, it belongs in the family Bathygadidae (Howes and Crimmen 1990, Roa-Varón and Ortí 2009, Nelson et al. 2016).
Until recently, Melanolagus bericoides was assigned to the genus Bathylagus, and it is often confused with Bathylagus euryops (Møller et al. 2010).

The taxonomy of the genus Nansenia needs revision, as there may be one or two hidden synonymies among the currently recognized species (O. Gon pers. comm. 2014). Further, the importance of vertebral counts to the correct identification of Nansenia species can be overlooked, resulting in misidentification of specimens in museum collections. These misidentifications have been perpetuated through checklists, and thus the true distribution of these species is often uncertain (O. Gon pers. comm. 2014).
The genus Dicrolene is in need of taxonomic revision.
Nielsen (2009) revised the genus Luciobrotula, finding three species in the Atlantic Ocean: L. brasiliensis, L. corethromycter, and L. nolfi.
Pistacia mexicana H.B.K. belongs to the secondary Gene Pool of P. vera L. (USDA, ARS, National Genetic Resources Program 2013).
Dalbergia cubilquitezensis is an accepted name following Linares and Souza 2007 and Cervantes et al. 2019 and Tropicos 2020 (the most up to date regional lists).

For this assessment, Pterocarpus rohrii is assessed under its broadest, currently accepted concept (Pterocarpus rohrii sensu lato). The species is under taxonomic review and may be split in the future.

There remains some uncertainty as to the taxonomic status of Gnatholepis thompsoni. It has previously been considered a synonym of Gnatholepis cauerensis.

The taxonomic concept of Gnatholepis cauerensis is undergoing revision. Gnatholepis has often been misidentified and confused for many years. Previously, there were four proposed subspecies (G. c. cauerensis, G. c. australis, G. c. hawaiiensis and G. c. pascuensis), and G. thompsoni was considered a synonym (Randall and Greenfield 2001). Thacker (2004) shows G. thompsoni to be a separate species and also concludes that G. cauerensis should be synonymised with G. anjerensis. Variation in mitochondrial DNA suggested that G. thompsoni is a valid species that is widespread in the Atlantic Ocean and separate from G. cauerensis (Rocha et al. 2005). However, Randall and Greenfield (2007) consider G. thompsoni a synonym of G. cauerensis. Randall (2009) elevated three subspecies to the species level (resulting in four species: G. cauerensis, G. australis, G. hawaiiensis and G. pascuensis). During a recent revision of Gnatholepis, the classification presented by Rocha et al. was discussed and validated with meristic and other morphological characters by Larson and Buckle (2012). Larson and Buckle (2012) concluded that G. cauerensis includes subspecies G. c. cauerensis, G. c. australis and G. c. hawaiiensis and G. inconsequens is considered a synonym. They elevated G. thompsoni and G. pascuensis to valid species. Gnatholepis thompsoni, as valid in Larson and Buckle (2012), is restricted to the Atlantic Ocean. Rocha et al. (2005) examined genetic differences between the Atlantic G. thompsoni and the Indo-Pacific G. cauerensis, concluding that G. thompsoni is the result of a relatively recent (~ 145,000 years ago) invasion of the Atlantic by G. cauerensis. However, Smith-Vaniz and Collette (2013) recorded G. cauerensis, not G. thompsoni, in Bermuda, as "the meristic and other morphological characters purported to separate these two 'species' have broadly over-lapping values". Despite the issues with the characters used by Larson and Buckle (2012), G. thompsoni likely forms its own monophyletic group in an isolated ocean basin, and with threats and evolutionary trajectory separate from that of G. cauerensis. Therefore, G. thompsoni is retained as a valid species.
Quercus copeyensis is treated as a distinct species by Hardÿ and Lamant (2006), here it is being treated as a synonym to Quercus bumelioides following Morales (2010).

J. effusus hybridises with J. inflexus L. (Juncus × diffusus Hoppe) but the hybrid is not abundant and is unlikely to influence interpretation of the distribution of the species. Two varieties are widely recognised but there is little information on differences in their distribution or ecology, for example the apparent differences shown by Tela Botanica show that recording to varietal level is inconsistent, while Preston et al. (2002) do not map the different subspecies even though they are widely recorded in the UK.

Brooks and Clemants (2000) in Flora of North America vol. 22 say "The Juncus effusus complex has been variously recognized as containing several species or a single species with numerous infraspecific taxa. Unfortunately, North American treatments have dealt primarily with taxa in either the eastern or western portions of the continent. In considering the continent as a whole, little sense can be made of these treatments. The North American J. effusus complex is one that is in obvious need of modern systematic scrutiny."
The Order for this Family has changed  from Syngnathiformes to Gasterosteiformes (Nelson 2006).

Potamogeton nodosus is one of the most polymorphic Potamogeton species, showing several distinct morphotypes as well as an extreme phenotypic plasticity throughout its range. It seems likely that there has been some confusion about the distinction between this species and others such as P. linguatus, P. ferrugineus, P. tepperi and P. sulcatus (Wiegleb and Kaplan 1998), to the extent that this evaluation could include information on some of all of those taxa.

Potamogeton nodosus has been shown to hybridise with P. natans (P. ×schreberi G. Fisch.), the hybrid is not common and is unlikely to affect the survival of the species or this evaluation.
The genus Sphoeroides may be paraphyletic, and is in need of revision (Amaral et al. 2013).
This species can be taxonomically confused with Swietenia macrophylla in Costa Rica.

The H. rondeletii superspecies complex of the subgenus Danichthys is now recognized as containing four allopatric species: H. volador (western Atlantic), H. rondeletii (Mediterranean), H. gilberti (northern Pacific), and H. rufipinnis (Southern Hemisphere). The other two species, Hirundichthys marginatus (eastern tropical Pacific) and H. albimaculatus (west & central Pacific) are both distinct species in the subgenus, but are not part of the rondeletii superspecies complex (Parin and Belyanina 2002).
Ongoing genetic studies indicate that populations from Brazil and the Caribbean represent two different species (Smith-Vaniz and Jelks 2014, Rocha et al. in prep).
This species' eastern Pacific distribution is now known as R. samoensis.
This may be a junior synonym of Bothus leopardinus (Hensley 1995, Grove and Lavenberg 1997); further research is needed to clarify its status.

Gossypium barbadense L. is a primary wild relative of cotton, G. hirsutum L. and Sea Island cotton, G. barbadense L., and a tertiary wild relative of short-staple cotton, G. herbaceum L and tree cotton, G. arboreum L. (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).
Ipomoea splendor-sylvae is a tertiary wild relative of sweet-potato, I. batatas (L.) Lam. var. batatas (USDA, ARS, National Genetic Resources Program 2015).

Phaseolus lunatus var. silvester is included in this assessment, because it is the wild form. P. lunatus var.lunatus is the cultivated form and therefore is excluded.

In its wild form, Phaseolus lunatus L. is a primary wild relative of Lima Bean, the cultivated form of the species.

Phaseolus viridis, including P. longiplacentifer, is here considered a synonym of Phaseolus lunatus var. silvester.

Phaseolus parvifolius Freytag is a secondary wild relative of tepary bean, P. acutifolius A. Gray var. acutifolius, and a tertiary wild relative of common bean, P. vulgaris L. var. vulgaris and year bean, P. dumosus Macfad. (USDA, ARS, National Genetic Resources Program 2015).
Solanum bulbocastanum Dunal is a tertiary wild relative of potato, S. tuberosum L. ssp. tuberosum (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).

A subspecies has been described, Ctenosaura similis multipunctata (Barbour and Shreve 1934, Occasional Papers of the Boston Society of Natural History 8: 197) from Isla de Providencia, Colombia (Henderson and Powell 2009), however, given that the nominotypical subspecies occurs on nearby San Andrés Island (90 km distant), the validity of this subspecies should be re-evaluated.
Was previously listed on The IUCN Red List under the genus Typhlops but is now treated under Amerotyphlops (Hedges et al. 2014).

Although the most genetically distinct of the four species of spearfishes (Collette et al. 2006, Hanner et al. 2011), Tetrapturus georgii was only recently confirmed as a valid species (Shivji et al. 2006).

Further taxonomic studies are needed to establish if Zea nicaraguensis and Zea vespertilio are subspecies of Z. luxurians  (J.J. Sánchez pers. comm.2017), until then they are recognised as good species.

Zea luxurians (Durieu & Asch.) R.M. Bird is a secondary wild relative of maize, Zea mays L. ssp. mays (USDA, ARS, National Genetic Resources Program 2015).
Morphological and molecular evidence indicate that Bairdiella ronchus represents a species complex (Marceniuk et al. 2019).

Species within the genus Mustelus are very similar in both appearance and size, making accurate identification challenging. In addition to M. henlei, another four species of Mustelus are known to occur around Baja California; M. albipinnis, M. californicus, M. dorsalis and M. lunulatus. M. henlei can be distinguished from the four species based on fin positions and margin colours, labial furrows, and dentition (Castro-Aguirre et al. 2005, Pérez-Jiménez et al. 2005, Ebert et al. 2021)

This species may have been misidentified for other Mustelus spp. in the Gulf of California, including M. californicus. Records of this species from South America refer to another undescribed lunulatus-type Mustelus species. This lunulatus-type Mustelus occurs in the Eastern Pacific to Ecuador and the Galapagos Islands and has likely been recorded as M. lunulatus in South America in the past (see Compagno in prep. for discussion).

Urobatis concentricus, U. halleri, and U. maculatus have sometimes been considered colour variants of a single species, but molecular studies have shown that these are distinct species (Last et al. 2016).

The genus Hypanus formerly was a junior synonym of Dasyatis (Kottelat 2013); it was resurrected by Last et al. (2016) in their revision of the family Dasyatidae.

The nomenclature of this species is often confused, occasionally resulting in the listing of brevis and dipterurus as separate species. Both Jordan and Gilbert and Garman published descriptions of this species in the same year, 1880. However, Jordan and Gilbert published their account of specimens from San Diego in May 1880, while Garman published his description in October of that year. Garman (1913) subsequently overlooked these facts and inappropriately synonymized dipterurus with brevis. However, Jordan and Gilbert's description has precedence.
This complex has recently been separated into three species: B. lacertus, B. antilliensis, and B. soporator (Tornabene et al. 2010).

Recent genetic evidence suggests three distinct lineages in the eastern Atlantic that may represent distinct species (Galvan-Quesada et al. 2016, Guiamaes-Costa et al. 2017). Recognition of these lineages at the species level would considerably reduce the range extent of this species, and would likely warrant reassessment.
Eleotris perniger has generally been reported as E. pisonis, but the latter is a continental South American species ranging only from southern Brazil to eastern Venezuela (Pezold and Cage 2002).

Heemstra and Heemstra (2004) describes the taxonomy of the Mugilidae family as confused and the genera as obscurely defined. 

Misidentification with Mugil gaimardianus, now an invalid species, has caused much confusion in the past.  

Currently, the most frequent misidentication is with Mugil rubrioculus (Harrison et al. 2007). Mugil curema and M. rubrioculus are very similar morphologically. They are clearly separated genetically both by karyotype and molecular analysis (Nirchio et al. 2005, Fraga et al. 2007, Gonzalez-Castro et al. 2009). 

Fraga et al. (2007) identified two species occurring along the Brazilian coast, Mugil curema type I (Mugil rubrioculus) and Mugil curema type II and showed that their distribution overlaps in most of their distribution. Therefore, species identification in landings and ecological studies may confuse the two species in Brazil.
This species was previously thought to be confused with C. mexicanus off Sao Paulo State (Brazil), however, it is now known these two species do not co-occur in this area.
This species is easily confused with Centropomus parallelus (Orrell FAO report).

There is no type specimen for Mugil trichodon Poey 1875. Its description is based on Plate 8. Figure 4-8. from Cuba. Thompson (1997) considered it a "nomen nudum" (an invalid name).

This species is genetically most similar to M. rubrioculus and M. brevirostris, but is considered to be valid (Menezes et al. 2015).

Throughout much of its range, Juncus bufonius represents a complex of taxa. TROPICOS lists 80 sub-specific combinations for this name, but Flora Europaea volume 5 lists the following as falling within the J. bufonius group: J. bufonius L., J. foliosus Desf., J. hybridus Brot., J. minutulus (Albert & Jahand.) Prain, J. ranarius Nees and J. sorrentini Parl. Some of these are recognized in some countries or by some authors but use is not consistent, thus, for example in the UK, J. minutulus is considered a synonym of J. bufonius, while J. ranarius is treated as a synonym of J. ambiguus Guss., equally TROPICOS treats J. hybridus as a nomenclatural synonym of J. bufonius L. but IPNI does not.

Work is needed to achieve a degree of consistency in recording of taxa within the J. bufonius group. Kirschner (2002) treats "Juncus hybridus" (= ambiguus), and "J. ranarius" as distinct species and does not include them in "J. bufonius".

Previously a circumtropical species, Trachinocephalus myops was recently separated into three species: T. myops, restricted to the Atlantic Ocean; T. trachinus, known from throughout the Indo-West Pacific; and T. gauguini restricted to the Marquesas Islands (Polanco et al. 2016). The geographic range of T. myops has therefore been reduced considerably.
This species can be misidentified with Pomadasys corvinaeformis.

Recently, Caranx hippos from the eastern Atlantic and Mediterranean was split into two species. A new species, Caranx fischeri, was described by Smith-Vaniz and Carpenter (2007). Caranx hippos and C. fischeri are largely sympatric, however it is C. fischeri which is found in the Mediterranean. There have been no confirmed records of C. hippos in the Mediterranean.

According to Catalog of Fishes and Kong and Valdes (1990), Micropogonias manni, which is known to occur only in Chile, may be a junior synonym of M. furnieri. This is not correct, as M. manni is valid, but with nomen dubium (uncertain name). Micropogonias furnieri does not occur in Chile. Specimens collected from Lago Budi, southern Chile (N.L. Chao, 15 March 2011, deposited at the Museo Nacional de Historia Natural, Santiago, Chile) are distinct from M. manni. Taxonomic work on the East Pacific Micropogonias species is needed (N.L. Chao pers. comm. 2020).

Variations in body depth, eye size, etc., of individuals collected throughout this range suggest that more systematic work is needed on this taxon (Munroe 2002). It may be a synonym of Harengula clupeola (B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2012).

In a revision of the genus Cyclopsetta, Khidir et al. (2004) noted variation in several characters between specimens of C. fimbriata from the Gulf of Mexico and those from the Caribbean Sea. However, they indicated that more specimens were needed to address the question of whether or not more than one species is represented by these specimens. To date, no further studies have addressed this question and it is the position herein that only one species is represented by all the material examined by Khidir et al. (2004).
This species has been previously confused with Strongylura marina (Collette 1968).

Previously this was assessed as the subspecies S. brasiliensis gabbi. It has now been raised to species level.

Sylvilagus gabbi, along with its putatively subordinate taxon truei, were among the many subspecies synonymized under S. brasiliensis. The former two were recently removed from synonomy with brasiliensis, with truei becoming a subspecies of S. gabbi (Ruedas and Salazar-Bravo 2007). Currently, Gabb’s Cottontail is hypothesized to be constituted by six subspecies: S. gabbi gabbi, S. g. truei, S. g. consobrinus, S. g. messorius, S. g. tumacus, S. g. incitatus, however, the validity of some of these taxa remains in question; the taxonomy of S. gabbi is therefore unstable at the present time, until such a time as the identity of these taxa is resolved (Ruedas 2018).
It was previously treated as a subspecies of E. bonariensis (see Simmons 2005, Eger 2008).

In previous Red List assessments, this species was included within Eumops glaucinus. McDonough et al. (2008) and Baker et al. (2009) provided support for the elevation to species of 2 taxa within E. glaucinus, E. ferox and E. wilsoni, using mitochondrial gene sequence, karyotypic, morphological, and amplified fragment length polymorphism data. Their analysis supported 3 distinctive clades within the E. glaucinus complex: E. glaucinus from Paraguay and Venezuela; E. ferox and E. floridanus from Cuba, Jamaica, Mexico, and the United States; and a new species from Ecuador, E. wilsoni (Baker et al. 2009).
Previously Pteronotus mesoamericanus this was assessed as the subspecies Pteronotus parnellii ssp. mesoamericanus. It has now been raised to species level.
Previously Pteronotus rubiginosus this was included as a subspecies Pteronotus parnellii. It has now been raised to species level.
Molossus bondae previuously treated as synonym of M. currentium is now considered as a valid species (Eger 2008).

Based on the morphological distinction observed between A. g. peruana and A. g. geoffroyi, as well as the ecological differentiation of the areas inhabited by these two taxa, Mantilla-Meluk and Baker (2010) elevated A. peruana to specific level.

The species previously included populations with distinctive morphologies and karyotypes, that required description of a new species, C. benkeithi, to better recognize that evolutionary diversity (Solari and Baker 2006).
Vampyroides major was previously included within V. caraccioli. It is now considered a distinct species.
Previously recognized as subspecies of S. lilium, it has now been elevated to species rank.
Previously recognized as synonym of S. ludovici, it has now been recognized as distinct species (Velazco et al. 2010).

Molecular, morphological, and morphometric analyses (Velazco et al. 2010) of specimens formerly identified as Platyrrhinus helleri support recognition of Platyrrhinus incarum as a separate species and reveal the presence of two species from northern South America (Platyrrhinus angustirostris sp. nov. from eastern Colombia and Ecuador, north-eastern Peru, and Venezuela and Platyrrhinus fusciventris sp. nov. from Guyana, Suriname, French Guiana, Trinidad and Tobago, northern Brazil, eastern Ecuador, and southern Venezuela).
Gardnerycteris crenulatum could be a species complex and a systematic review is needed (Patterson and Tavares pers. comm). This species does not include koepckeae.

Synonym of Quercus lancifolia in WCSP and in The Oak Checklist but accepted as a good species by Oaks of the World, Valencia 2006, Chenes (personal confirmation from T. Lamant), A. Gonzalez-Rodriguez (personal confirmation).

Previously placed in family Accipitridae but moved to current family based on the phylogeny of Starikov and Wink (2020). Traditionally thought to form a species-group with E. caeruleus and E. axillaris; all three sometimes considered conspecific, but differ variously in plumage, morphology and behaviour. Two subspecies recognized.

Myiodynastes maculatus and M. solitarius (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as M. maculatus (see AOU [1998 & supplements]; SACC [2005 & updates]; Sibley & Monroe [1990, 1993]; Stotz et al. [1996]).
Ceratopipra mentalis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously listed as Pipra mentalis.

Myrmotherula axillaris (AOU [1998 & supplements]; SACC [2005 & updates]; Sibley & Monroe [1990, 1993]; Stotz et al. [1996]) and M. fluminensis (SACC [2005 & updates]; Sibley & Monroe [1990, 1993]; Stotz et al. [1996]) have been lumped and subsequently split into M. axillaris and M. luctuosa following del Hoyo and Collar (2016).

Cistothorus platensis and C. stellaris (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as C. platensis (see AOU [1998 & supplements]; SACC [2005 & updates]; Sibley & Monroe [1990, 1993]; Stotz et al. [1996]).

Henicorhina leucophrys and H. anachoreta (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as H. leucophrys following AOU (1998 & supplements), SACC (2005 & updates), Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993) and Stotz et al. (1996).

Icterus spurius and I. fuertesi (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as I. spurius following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).
Patagioenas fasciata and P. albilinea (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as P. fasciata following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Colaptes auratus, C. cafer and C. mexicanoides (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as C. auratus following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Hylatomus lineatus and H. fuscipennis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously placed in the genus Dryocopus and lumped as D. lineatus following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Circus cyaneus and C. hudsonius (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as C. cyaneus following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Psittacara rubritorquis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Aratinga.
Stelgidopteryx serripennis and S. ridgwayi (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as S. serripennis following AOU (1998 & supplements) and Stotz et al. (1996).
Eupsittula nana and E. astec (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously placed in the genus Aratinga and lumped as A. nana following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Megascops guatemalae and M. vermiculatus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as M. guatemalae following AOU (2003). Prior to that, M. guatemalae, plus M. atricapilla and M. hoyi (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), had been placed in the genus Otus and were treated as two species; O. atricapillus (including guatemalae and hoyi) and O. vermiculatus, following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Gallinula chloropus and G. galeata (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as G. chloropus following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Fulica americana (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously split as F. americana and F. caribaea following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

The status of this species in El Salvador is unclear. Smith et al. (2001) stated that Sceloporus acanthinus ranges into El Salvador, while Köhler et al. (2006) and Köhler (2008), following advice from E. N. Smith, included El Salvador populations in S. malachiticus. These accounts follow the latter authors in attributing Salvadorian records to S. malachitus.

The taxonomy of the genus Zannichellia is complex, with one species recognised throughout much of the World but with many taxa recognised at or below species level in different regions. The distinguishing characters for some taxa appear to be useful, but others appear to have been described based on very few samples and relatively minor morphological differences. Most taxa described to-date are treated as Z. palustris by Kew (The Board of Trustees of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew 2010).

Multivariate analysis of morphometric data based on Czech material did not support existence of any morphologically distinguishable taxa (Kaplan 2010).
New species in Cryptotis goldmani group (Woodman 2015).
This is a new species in Cryptotis goldmani group (Woodman 2015).
New species in Cryptotis goldmani group (Woodman 2015).
Agave angustifolia seems to be a species complex (A. García-Mendoza pers. comm. 2018).

Ipomoea triloba L. is a tertiary genetic relative of Sweet Potato (I. batatas (L.) Lam.) (Jarret and Austin 1994, Huang et al. 2002, Rajapakse et al. 2004). Crossings involving I. triloba with the crop have resulted in relatively viable progeny (Nimmakayala et al. 2011).
This species is called abrasus in Hall and Kelson (1959), but see Husson (1962) and Hall (1981). Also see Best et al. (2002). The Jamaican form was reviewed by Timm and Genoways (2003).
Status of the subspecies needs to be assessed. This may be species complex (V. Tavares pers. comm.).

Taxonomy is currently under review by the IUCN SSC Cat Specialist Group. This species is genetically very diverse across its range and shows a high degree of population structure, with four distinct clusters: Central America and Mexico, north-northwest South America, north-northeast South America and southern South America. The demarcation between northern and southern South America was identified as the Amazon river (Eizirik et al. 1998).

The taxonomy is currently under review by the IUCN SSC Cat Specialist Group. While 32 subspecies have been classically described, on the basis of genetic analysis Culver et al. (2000) suggest six subspecies as follows:

P. c. cougar: North America
P. c. costaricensis: Central America
P. c. capricornensis: eastern South America
P. c. concolor: northern South America
P. c. cabrerae: central South America
P. c. puma: southern South America.
Diodon hystrix has a very wide distribution and a genetic analysis is warranted.
Given its extremely wide distribution, genetic studies should be conducted on this species to determine its taxonomic status (Leis, Matsuura and Carpenter pers. comm. 2011).

Mola mola differ slightly genetically and morphologically between the Pacific and Atlantic Ocean basins, but the two clades are currently treated as one species pending further taxonomic research (Yoshita et al. 2009, Nyegaard et al. 2018a, Sawai et al. 2018, 2020, Caldera et al. 2020, Baptista et al. 2021). The taxonomic history of M. mola is extensive and complicated (Nyegaard et al. 2018b; Sawai et al. 2018, 2020; Fricke et al. 2021), and M. mola literature written before the redescription of Mola alexandrini and description of Mola tecta (both in 2017) may have misidentified these two other species as M. mola.

Ranzania laevis has a circumglobal distribution and is currently considered a single cosmopolitan species (Caldera et al. 2020, Sawai et al. 2020, Fricke et al. 2022), although no phylogenetic study across its range has been undertaken. Genetic differences have been documented between specimens collected in the Sargasso Sea and those from Hawai’i (Caldera et al. 2020), and additional research is needed to confirm whether this represents a species complex. Preliminary genetic comparisons show little variation across the mitochondrial locus CO1 (among 12 individuals sampled across a wide range, including North Atlantic, South Africa, and Hawai’i.; Nyegaard et al. 2018), although a 5% sequence divergence (in the mitochondrial D-loop locus) between two specimens has been noted (Yoshita et al. 2009, Yamanoue et al. 2004). Fraser-Brunner (1951) suggested morphological differences in R. laevis between the Atlantic and North Pacific Ocean, with intermediate forms in the Indian Ocean. Research combining morphological and genetic analysis is required to clarify this species' taxonomy.
A recent publication suggests changing the family name to Epinephelidae (Smith and Craig 2007).
Digitaria horizontalis Willd. is a gene pool tertiary wild relative of Fonio millet/White fonio (Digitaria exilis (Kippist) Stapf) (Vincent et al. 2013).
Digitaria insularis (L.) Mez ex Ekman is a gene pool tertiary wild relative of Fonio millet/White fonio (Digitaria exilis (Kippist) Stapf) (Vincent et al. 2013).
Smith and Craig (2007) changed the family name to Epinephelidae; however, some workers retain its classification under Serranidae.

Epinephelus quinquefasciatus was previously considered E. itajara, but is now considered a separate species, with E. itajara only in the Atlantic and E. qinquefasciatus in the Pacific (Craig et al. 2009).
A recent publication changed the generic name of this species to Hyporthodus (Craig and Hastings 2007) and a change of family name to Epinephelidae (Smith and Craig 2007).

This species can be easily confused with Hyporthodus niveatus. Craig and Hastings (2007) changed the generic name of this species to Hyporthodus and Smith and Craig (2007) changed the family name to Epinephelidae.

This species has been misidentified as Hyporthodus niveatus by some workers. The generic name was changed from Epinephelus to Hyporthodus by Craig and Hastings (2007), and the family name was changed to Epinephelidae by Smith and Craig (2007).

Ma and Craig (2018) revised the classification of groupers, concluding that there are now nine genera: Alphestes, Cephalopholis (subsuming Aethaloperca, Gracila, and Paranthias), Dermatolepis, Epinephelus (sensu stricto), Gonioplectrus, Hyporthodus (subsuming Triso dermopterus, with the addition of three species previously placed in Epinephelus), Mycteroperca (with the addition of 11 species previously placed in Epinephelus), Plectropomus (subsuming Saloptia), and Variola.

Tripsacum andersonii  (Guatemalan grass) J.R. Gray is a gene pool tertiary wild relative of maize (Zea mays L. ssp. mays) (Vincent et al, 2013) (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017). The species is thought to be an intergeneric hybrid between Tripsacum and Zea (de Wet et al. 1983, Talbert et al. 1990, Taba 1995, Li et al. 1999, Lamb and Birchler 2006).
Digitaria curvinervis (Hack.)Fernald is a gene pool tertiary wild relative of Fonio millet/White fonio (Digitaria exilis (Kippist) Stapf) (Vincent et al. 2013).
Actinopyga agassizi is sometimes incorrectly referred to as Muelleria agassizi.
Astichopus multifidus may also be known as Stichopus multifidus.
This species can hybridize with H. floridana in the Florida Keys. The hybrids are viable (Engstrom 1980).
Isostichopus macroparentheses, Stichopus badionotus, Stichopus macroparentheses and Stichopus moebii may be synonyms for this species.
Originally spelled as fürthii and subsequently emended to fuerthii (Eschmeyer et al. 2017).

The validity of this species has been questioned in the literature as it is only apparently distinct from the other regional species of Opisthopterus based on subtle morphological differences (e.g., a more anteriorly placed dorsal fin and a slight variation in the number of gill rakers: Whitehead 1985). Whitehead (1985) suggested that more species should be examined; however there has been no recent work on this species in the available literature since the 1980s. Despite the lack of available research on this species, it is currently listed as a valid species in Eschmeyer’s Catalog of Fishes (Fricke et al. 2020). Therefore, for the purposes of this Red List assessment, Opisthopterus macrops will be treated as a valid species distributed in the eastern tropical Pacific. Future taxonomic work on this species is needed.

Physalis campechiana L. is a wild relative of Cape gooseberry, P. peruviana L., low ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. and tomatillo, P. philadelphica Lam. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).

Physalis melanocystis (B.L.Rob.) Bitter is a wild relative of Cape Gooseberry, P. peruviana L., Low Ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. and Tomatillo, P. philadelphica Lam. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).

Contopus cinereus , C. punensis and C. bogotensis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as C. cinereus following AOU (1998 & supplements), SACC (2005 & updates), Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993) and Stotz et al. (1996).

The genus Hypanus formerly was a junior synonym of Dasyatis and it was resurrected by Last et al. (2016) in their revision of the family Dasyatidae. Petean et al. (2020) revised Hypanus americanus, separating the newly described species, H. berthalutzae, whose distribution includes the Brazilian coastline from the mouth of the Amazon River to São Paulo State.
The genus Hypanus formerly was a junior synonym of Dasyatis and it was resurrected by Last et al. (2016) in their revision of the family Dasyatidae.

Physalis ignota Britton is a wild relative of Cape gooseberry, P. peruviana L., low ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. and tomatillo, P. philadelphica Lam. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).
Physalis lagascae Roem. & Schult. is a tertiary wild relative of low ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).

Physalis microcarpa Urb. & Ekman is a wild relative of Cape gooseberry, P. peruviana L., low ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. and tomatillo, P. philadelphica Lam. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).
Physalis angulata L. is a tertiary wild relative of Low Ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).

According to USDA, ARS, GRIN (2017) Leptospron adenthum (G.Mey.) A.Delgado is the accepted name for this taxon. Vigna adenantha (G.Mey.) Maréchal, Mascherpa & Stainier and Phaseolus adenanthus G.Mey. are listed as synonyms of Leptospron adenthum (G.Mey.) A.Delgado.

Vigna adenantha (G.Mey.) Maréchal, Mascherpa & Stainier is a wild relative (in Taxon Group 4) of Bambara Groundnut, V. subterranea (L.) Verdc., and of Cowpea, V. unguiculata (L). Walp. (Maxted et al. 2004).
This is a split from the broader concept of Rhinella marina (Acevedo-Rincón et al. 2016).

Physalis minuta Griggs is a wild relative of Cape Gooseberry, P. peruviana L., Low Ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. and Tomatillo, P. philadelphica Lam. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).

Physalis nicandroides Schltdl. is a wild relative of Cape Gooseberry, P. peruviana L., Low Ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. and Tomatillo, P. philadelphica Lam. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).
In its wild form, Physalis philadelphica Lam. is a primary wild relative of Tomatillo, the cultivated form of the species.

Physalis porrecta Waterf. is a wild relative of Cape Gooseberry, P. peruviana L., Low Ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. and Tomatillo, P. philadelphica Lam. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).
Physalis pruinosa L. is a tertiary wild relative of Low Ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).

This species belongs to the group leptostachyus (Delgado-Salinas et al. 2006).

Following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006), Phaseolus leptostachyus Benth. is a wild relative (in Taxon Group 4) of common bean, P. vulgaris L. var. vulgaris, Lima bean, P. lunatus L., scarlet runner bean, P. coccineus L., tepary bean, P. acutifolius A. Gray var. acutifolius and year bean, P. dumosus Macfad.

USDA, ARS, GRIN (2017) recognizes four subtaxa: P. leptostachyus var. intonsus (Piper) Freytag, P. leptostachyus var. leptostachyus, P. leptostachyus var. lobatifolius Freytag, and P. leptostachyus var. nanus Freytag.

Following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006), Phaseolus oligospermus Piper is a wild relative (in Taxon Group 4) of common bean, P. vulgaris L. var. vulgaris, Lima bean, P. lunatus L., scarlet runner bean, P. coccineus L., tepary bean, P. acutifolius A. Gray var. acutifolius and year bean, P. dumosus Macfad.

Historically, the name Haemulon steindachneri included both Pacific and Atlantic populations. Recently, the species was revised; Haemulon steindachneri is now restricted to the Pacific Ocean and H. atlanticus (removed from H. steindachneri) occurs in the Atlantic Ocean (Carvalho et al. 2020).

There are currently 20 subspecies known for this species: the nominate subspecies polydamas; subspecies lucayus (Rothschild & Jordan, 1906); subspecies cubensis (Dufrane, 1946); subspecies jamaicensis (Rothschild & Jordan, 1906); subspecies polycrates (Hopffer, 1865); subspecies thyamus (Rothschild & Jordan, 1906); subspecies antiquus (Rothschild & Jordan, 1906); subspecies christopheranus (A. Hall, 1936); subspecies neodamas (Lucas, 1852); subspecies dominicus (Rothschild & Jordan, 1906); subspecies cebriones (Dalman, 1823); subspecies lucianus (Rothschild & Jordan, 1906); subspecies vincentius (Rothschild & Jordan, 1906); subspecies grenadensis (A. Hall, 1930); subspecies streckerianus (Honrath, 1884); subspecies peruanus (Fuchs, 1954); subspecies atahualpa T. Racheli & Pischedda, 1987; subspecies weyrauchi Lamas, 1998; subspecies renani Lamas, 1998; and subspecies psittacus (J. Molina, 1782).

There are several recognised subspecies: P. p. polyxenes Fabricius, 1775; P. p. asterius Stoll 1782; P. p. coloro Wright 1905; P. p. stabilis Rothschild & Jordan 1906; P. p. americus Kollar 1850; P. p. gerardi Bollino and Vitale 2002; P. p. costarum Orellana, 2009; and P. p. sadalus Lucas 1852.

There are currently four subspecies reported for this species, following the treatment by  Racheli (2006): the nominate subspecies sesostris; subspecies tarquinius (Boisduval, 1836); susbpecies zestos (Gray, [1853]); and subspecies trinitensis Brown, 1994. Another taxon, zischkai, has been considered a fifth subspecies of this species (Warren et al. 2013), but is considered a synonym of the nominate subspecies by Racheli (2006).
Troglodytes aedon and T. beani (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as T. aedon following Woods (1993).

Corapipo leucorrhoa (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously split into C. leucorrhoa (SACC [2005 and updates]; Sibley and Monroe [1990, 1993]; Stotz et al. [1996]) and C. altera (AOU [1998 and supplements]; SACC [2005 and updates]; Sibley and Monroe [1990, 1993]).

authority: Solis, Espinal, Valle, O'Reilly, Itgen & Townsend, 2016
taxonomicNotes: This is a split from the broader concept of Oedipina stuarti (Solis et al. 2016).
This is a split from the broader concept of Nototriton barbouri (Townsend 2016).
This is a split from the broader concept of Nototriton barbouri (Townsend 2016).
Oryza alta Swallen is a secondary genetic relative of rice (O. sativa L.) and African rice (O. glaberrima Steud.) (Ge et al., 1999).
The family Bathyclupeidae requires revision (Paxton and Carpenter 2002).

In a phylogenetic analysis of Eumeces based on morphology, Griffith et al. (2000) proposed splitting Eumeces into multiple genera, based on the apparent paraphyly of Eumeces. Smith (2005) and Brandley et al. (2005) formally proposed that all North American species (north of Mexico) be placed in the genus Plestiodon. This was accepted by Crother (2008) and Collins and Taggart (2009). The genus name is thus also used for species further to the south.
Will be transferred to family Cricetidae.
Subgenus Dasypterus. Includes floridanus.
This species apparently includes a species complex.
This taxon may encompass three sibling species (Edwards and Bradley 2001).
Will be transferred to family Cricetidae.
The species is in need of revision; it is likely a species complex (M. Weksler pers. comm.).

Pending revisionary work, Oryzomys alfaroi has been provisionally reassigned to the new genus Handleyomys (Weksler et al. 2006). A taxonomic review by M. Carleton and G. Musser is in progress (M. Weksler pers. comm.).
Will be transferred to family Cricetidae.
Pending revisionary work, Oryzomys rostratus has been provisionally reassigned to the new genus Handleyomys (Weksler et al. 2006).
Will be transferred to family Cricetidae.

Might include more than one species (Davalos 2006). The species is under taxonomic review and will be split into two species at Panama, the southern population is P. personatus (L. Davalos pers. comm.). Often placed in the subgenus Chilonycteris (e.g., Smith 1972, Simmons and Conway 2001), but recent molecular studies suggest that it represents an unnamed subgenus (Lewis-Oritt et al. 2001, Van Den Bussche and Weyandt 2003).

Patterns of genetic variation suggest that this species as currently defined may be represented by more than one species; further study is warranted (see Musser and Carleton 2005). For a phylogenetic analysis of Reithrodontomys species based on mitochondrial DNA, see Bell et al. (2001).
Will be transferred to family Cricetidae.

A species composite requiring detailed revision, as underscored by the large genetic distances disclosed among Middle American populations and the polyphyly of nominal “mexicanus” in the resultant cladogram (Arellano et al. 2003).
Will be transferred to family Cricetidae.
Also known as Orzomys alfari.
Genus was recently split from Tonatia.

Formerly considered part of Sigmodon hispidus (see Voss 1992). S. hirsutus was reinstated based on genetic separation by Peppers and Bradley (2000); following Carroll et al. (2005), S. hirsutus includes all cotton rats occurring in southern Chiapas (Mexico), through Central America, and into northern Colombia and Venezuela.

Carroll et al. (2005) recommend all former subspecies of S. hispidus in this region be reassigned as subspecies of S. hirsutus (this includes boracae, chiriquensis, griseus, hirsutus, and zanjonensis). They also state that it is uncertain whether specimens from southern Chiapas should be assigned to S. hirsutus zanjonensis or whether they represent a new subspecies. They refer these samples as S. hirsutus ssp. Until the issue can be resolved. Note, however, that Musser and Carleton (2005) assign zanjonensis specific status (S. zanjonensis).

Seven geographic subspecies were recognized by Collette and Parin (1970):

Platybelone argalus argalus from the western Atlantic;
P. a. lovii from the Cape Verde Islands;
P. a. annobonensis from Annobón and Fernando Po islands in the Gulf of Guinea;
P. a. trachura from Ascension and St. Helena;
P. a. platyura in most of the Indo-West Pacific;
P. a. platura in the Red Sea and Persian Gulf; and
P. a. pterura from the eastern Pacific.
The Azores population is of taxonomic interest (B. Collette pers. comm. 2012).
This species has also recently been listed under the genera Sciadeops and Sciades. Original orthography with 'ii' ending.
The taxonomic status of populations of this species in different oceans needs to be investigated (R. Robertson pers. comm. 2015).
Mulloidichthys dentatus is closely related to M. martinicus of the western Atlantic and M. vanicolensis, an Indo-Pacific species that also occurs in the region.

Although considered a worldwide species by previous authors, T. lepturus is now known with certainty only from the western Atlantic and Indo-west Pacific. The eastern Atlantic population reported as this species is probably an undescribed species. There are multiple lines of evidence showing geographically-correlated divergence and supporting the treatment of at least 3 species in the T. lepturus complex (Chakrabarty and Iwatsuki 2006, Hsu et al. 2009). 

Trichiurus japonicus, which was originally described from Japan as Trichiurus lepturus japonicus, was synonymized with Trichiurus lepturus. Another nominal species synonymized with Trichiurus lepturus is Trichiurus nitens from the eastern Pacific Ocean (California to Peru).

Gibbs and Staiger (1970) found some minor difference between the western and eastern Atlantic populations of C. cyanopterus (considered at that time as disjunct) in two meristic characters, visible number of vertebrae and number of predorsal scales. Atlantic and Indo-West Pacific populations of C. cyanopterus have been never compared.This species has been historically known as Cypselurus cyanopterus.
This species was previously placed under the family Inermiidae (Sanciangco et al. 2011).
Taxonomic note: This species is difficult to distinguish from the closely related Echeneis neucratoides which occurs only in the western central Atlantic (O’Toole 2002)

Recent work indicates significant genetic divergence between specimens from deep waters off Central America and in the Gulf of Mexico, indicating the possibility that the name poeyi may represent two species (Baldwin et al. in press).
The northern populations of this species show genetic differences in comparison to the southern populations, and may be different species (L. Rocha pers. comm. 2014)

According to a redescription of this species by Frable et al. (2013), the taxonomic authority was changed from (Spix and Agassiz, 1829) to (Agassiz, 1829). Additionally, S. intermedius was split into a new species named S. macrostigmus.

The taxonomy of the genus Masturus is in need of further study. Earlier authors (e.g., Fraser-Brunner 1951) suggested that Masturus comprises two species: M. lanceolataus and M. oxyuropterus based on the degree of claval extension. Preliminary genetic data suggest M. lanceolatus is a single, global population with no structuring among ocean basins, but no global studies have examined the taxonomy or population structure of M. lanceolatus, and a global genetic analysis is warranted (see Caldera et al. 2020).

Tyler (1980) tentatively recognized four species in this complex that have different distributions, based on his material examined and text: Chilomycterus atringa (western Atlantic); C. reticulatus (eastern Atlantic and Indo-Pacific); C. tigrinus (western Indian Ocean); and C. affinis (Eastern Pacific). However, Tyler (1980) said that C. tigrinus may be the young of C. reticulatus.
This species has a very wide distribution and a genetic analysis is warranted. Leis (1978) noted some differences in spine morphology between Pacific and north Atlantic specimens.
This species was previously known as Pomadasys corvinaeformis and all Haemulopsis species, like Pomadasys, are associated with softbottom habitats (Tavera et al. 2012).

Disjunct populations of S. aurita in the western and eastern Atlantic are in need of further study to determine their taxonomic status (Whitehead 1985). Sardinella brasiliensis is a species which has been described from the southeast Brazilian Bight and is a valid species according to Eschmeyer (Figueiredo et al. 2010). There are reports of sympatric occurrence with S. aurita in the Gulf of Mexico; however, these may be based on misidentifications (Kinsey et al. 1994). We accept the conclusions presented in Tringali and Wilson (1993) that S. brasiliensis is a junior subjective synonym of S. aurita.
This species is commonly misidentified as Seriola rivoliana and S. carpenteri, making market data unreliable (W. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2013).

The validity of the generic name Masticophis has been the subject of controversy "for many years" (Wilson et al. 2010), with some authors treating it as a synonym of Coluber. Limited taxon sampling has confounded efforts to resolve this question, with Nagy et al. (2004) finding no evidence for synonymy while a three-taxon study by Utiger et al. (2005) found M. flagellum to be nested within C. constrictor, although support for this conclusion was low (Wilson et al. 2010). More recent work involving broader taxon sampling within Masticophis and additional populations of C. constrictor found Masticophis to be monophyletic and sister to, rather than nested within, Coluber (Burbrink et al. 2008). Additional work to resolve the relationships between these and related genera is needed to resolve this issue, and is in preparation (R.A. Pyron pers. comm. October 2011). Research is also needed to resolve the position of the Central American M. mentovarius, which has not been included in these phylogenetic studies (Wilson et al. 2010). In the meantime this account follows Collins and Taggart (2008) and Wilson et al. (2010) in retaining Masticophis as a valid genus.

The name Synodus synodus (Linnaeus 1758) (type locality: "America") has been widely used for this species. Genetic evidence indicates approximately 5-6% divergence in COI between eastern and western Atlantic populations indicating deep population structure or potential cryptic species within its lineage (Frable et al. 2013). This suggests that populations on either side of the Atlantic may represent distinct species. The nominal Synodus atlanticus (Johnson 1863) is currently available for this species.  However, further work is needed to stabilize the nomenclature.

There is molecular and morphological evidence available that Atlantic specimens identified as Antennarius striatus represent a separate species (Antennarius scaber) (Arnold and Pietsch 2012). Work is underway to resurrect the species (R. Arnold pers. comm. 2013).

The higher taxonomy of this species is currently uncertain, though it is currently included in the family Caproidae (Perciformes). However, there is currently no evidence to suggest that the genera Antigonia and Capros belong in the same family (Heemstra in press). Some authors suggest that it should be placed in the Beryciformes due to otolith shape (Zehren 1987).
A geminate species, Chloroscombrus orqueta Jordan and Gilbert, occurs in the eastern Pacific Ocean (Smith-Vaniz FAO ECA Guide in prep).

The validity of this species is in question. Molecular evidence may identify it as Echeneis neucratoides as Echeneis naucrates (Gray et al. 2009). Occasional studies consider Echeneis neucratoides and Echeneis naucrates one species (O'Toole 1999).

Taxonomic study needs to be conducted for this species complex. Adults of Uraspis helvola and U. secunda are virtually impossible to distinguish although juvenile characters involving allometric growth patterns suggest that they may be distinct species. If subsequent studies indicate that these two nominal species are conspecific, the oldest available name is Uraspis helvola. A complete description is given only for U. secunda because that name has been widely used for Atlantic Uraspis (Carpenter in prep.).

This species was previously known as Inermia vittata and formerly in the family Inermiidae. Genetic analyses published in Rocha et al. (2008) place it within the genus Haemulon, within the family Haemulidae. The new combination, Haemulon vittatum, is recognized by Eschmeyer and other recent publications.
This species was previously known as Priacanthus cruentatas and Cookeolus boops.
Fistularia petimba has often wrongly been cited as the more common Fistularia commersonii (Randall et al. 1990).
In the field, this species is difficult to distinguish from Stephanolepis setifer (R. Robertson and J. Tyler pers. comm. 2015).
This species has frequently been misidentified in the literature as Decapterus macarellus (W. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2015).
Sphyraena picudilla, considered by some authors to be a different species, is here regarded as a junior synonym of S. borealis (for discussion see Smith-Vaniz et al. 1999).
This species was recently revalidated based on genetic and morphological data (Bernal and Rocha 2011). Acanthurus bahianus is now considered to be endemic to Brazil.

Pseudophallus brasiliensis Dawson 1974 is a junior synonym of P. mindii. Dawson (1974) originally described P. brasiliensis based on low meristic counts in Brazil compared to the previously described P. mindii. Later research revealed similar or lower counts in other parts of the range of P. mindii, indicating that the two are one and the same (Dawson 1982). From Dawson (1982): "Specimens with low counts from the Amazon drainage were described as P. brasiliensis, but samples with similar or lower counts have subsequently been examined from the Orinoco River and Lake Izabal, Guatemala. In the apparent absence of consistent differences in coloration or other morphological features, these specimens are considered to represent local populations of P. mindii wherein low meristic values result from unknown environmental influences."

A recent molecular phylogenetic study of 39 sea snake species in 15 genera recovered Hydrophis as broadly paraphyletic with respect to several other genera (Sanders et al. 2013). Instead of erecting multiple new genera, the authors recommended dismantling the mostly monotypic genera Pelamis, Enhydrina, Astrotia, Thalassophina, Acalyptophis, Kerilia, Lapemis and Disteira, and recognizing a single genus, Hydrophis, for these taxa (Sanders et al. 2013). This classification system avoids confusion and better reflects the history of recent and very rapid diversification of these snakes and are followed by most recent authors (e.g., Leviton et al. 2014, Lillywhite et al. 2014, Rasmussen et al. 2014, Ukuwela et al. 2014, D'Anastasi et al. 2016, Rezaie-Atagholipour et al. 2016, Udyawer et al. 2015, Mirtschin et al. 2017).

A distinctive new subspecies of sea snake from inner-basin waters of Golfo Dulce, Costa Rica has been described (Bessesen and Galbreath 2017). The Yellow sea snake, Hydrophis platurus ssp. xanthos Bessesen & Galbreath, 2017 is diagnosed by a notably smaller body size and nearly uniform yellow colouration, which contrasts with the black and yellow striae and tail spots or bands typical of the species (Bessesen and Galbreath 2017).

This species is sometimes treated as a conspecific of Leucaena shannonii. For the IUCN Red List it is treated as a distinct species following Hughes 1998, however, some records used for the assessment may not have distinguished between the two species.
Digitaria sacchariflora (Raddi) Henrard is a gene pool tertiary wild relative of Fonio millet/White fonio (Digitaria exilis (Kippist) Stapf) (Vincent et al. 2013).
Some authors consider this species as two different entities, one on the Pacific coast and a second one on the Atlantic coast. Molecular studies are needed to address this issue.

Cacicus uropygialis, C. pacificus and C. microrhynchus (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as C. uropygialis, following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).

Cyanoloxia cyanoides and C. rothschildii (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped and placed in the genus Cyanocompsa as Cyanocompsa cyanoides following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).
Molothrus aeneus and M. armenti (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as M. aeneus following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).

Argia plana Calvert, 1902 is considered a junior synonym of Argia funebris (Hagen, 1861), so the A. funebris before considered a tropical species now reaches Oklahoma and northern Texas in the middle of the USA (Rosser W. Garrison pers. comn.).

P. pusillus is a taxonomically difficult species. Difficulties of identification (particularly in the field) mean that distribution data are likely to include records that refer to the concept of P. berchtoldii employed here, as well as records of P. pusillus.

Wiegleb and Kaplan (1998) included P. berchtoldii within their concept of P. pusillus, although they have since accepted the separation of these two taxa. They state that "P. pusillus is regarded [..] as a highly polymorphic species with numerous regional forms and ecomorphoses. More detailed classification seems to be impossible because of the highly reticular variation. No correlated set of characters which would make discrimination of taxa possible have been confirmed". They also state that "Some of the plants called P. groenlandicus show certain characters deviant from the present concept of P. pusillus. They are characterized especially by the leaves with up 8 additional sclerenchymatous strands. These plants are known only from a geographically limited area in Western Greenland. Further research, such as experimental cultivation, is necessary in order to clarify its status."

The Flora of North America recognises three subspecies (Haynes and Barre-Hellquist 2000), while the World Checklist of Selected Plant Families (The Board of Trustees of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew 2010) recognises only one at a global level.

Two hybrid combinations have been reported involving P. pusillus; P. perfoliatus × P. pusillus (P. × mysticus Morong) and P. pusillus × P. trichoides (P. × grovesii Dandy et G. Taylor), both are extremely rare and unlikely to affect either the survival of the species or this evaluation.
According to Ghedotti et al. (2015), this species should be placed in the family Lestidiidae.
Four subspecies are recognized, the nominate form, subsp. columbiense (F.A.C.Weber) Bauer, subsp. guatamalense (Britton & Rose) Bauer, and subsp. pittieri (F.A.C.Weber) Bauer.
Two subspecies are recognized, the typical form and subsp. hondurensis (Kimnach) Doweld.
Four subspecies are recognized, the nominate and subsp. aurantiacus (Kimnach) Bauer, subsp. blomianus (Kimnach) Bauer and cinnabarinus (Eichlam ex Weing.) Bauer.
Two subspecies are recognized, the nominate form and subsp. costaricense (F.A.C.Weber) Bauer.
Two subspecies are recognized, the nominate form and subsp. kimnachii (Bravo ex Kimnach) U.Guzmán.

Taxonomic work is required to see if this is in fact one species or a species complex which needs splitting. The subpopulations are very disjunct from each other. Four subspecies are currently recognized, the nominate form, subsp. dawsonii (Bravo) N.P.Taylor, subsp. caesius (H.L.Wendl.) N.P.Taylor and subsp. koolwijkianus (Suringar) G.Thomson.

Hunt et al. (2006) recognize seven subspecies of Rhipsalis baccifera:
  • the nominate subspecies;
  • subsp. cleistogama M.Kessler, Ibisch & Barthlott;
  • subsp. erythrocarpa (K.Schum.) Barthlott;
  • subsp. hileiabaiana N.P.Taylor & Barthlott (this subspecies was previously assessed for the 2002 IUCN Red List as Vulnerable but it has not been reassessed here);
  • subsp. horrida (Baker) Barthlott;
  • subsp. mauritiana (DC.) Barthlott; and
  • subsp. shaferi (Britton & Rose) Bartlott & N.P.Taylor.

Subspecies schaferi, should be treated as a good species (N.P. Taylor and W. Barthlott pers. comms. 2010). This is further confirmed by the work of Korotkova (2011). For the purposes of this assessment, R. shaferi is included under R. baccifera.

Additional subspecies have been described in Africa and Madagascar but these are not recognized by Hunt et al. (2006).
Two subspecies are recognized, the nominate form and subsp. jamaicensis (Britton & Harris) Doweld.
Confusion between this species and O. puberula exists.
Four subspecies are recognized, the nominate form, subsp. donkelaarii (Salm-Dyck) Ralf Bauer, subsp. hondurensis (K. Schum. ex Weing) Ralf Bauer and subsp. lautneri Ralf Bauer.
Synonym of Selenicereus testudo (Hunt et al. 2006).

Mammillaria columbiana yucatanesis (Britton & Rose) D.R.Hunt is found in Yucatán and Chiapas and is not assessed separately.  Part or all of the population occurring in Jamaica were described as M. jamaicensis but are treated as M. columbiana in Hunt et al. 2006 (G. Gann pers. comm. 2011).
Digitaria andicola Gir.-Cañas is a gene pool tertiary wild relative of Fonio millet/White fonio (Digitaria exilis (Kippist) Stapf) (Vincent et al. 2013).
Theobroma bicolor Humb. & Bonpl. is a gene pool tertiary relative of Cacao, Theobroma cacao L. (Vincent et al. 2013).
There are four distinct subspecies: B. l. laodamas (Rothschild and Jordan 1906), B. l. copanae (Reakirt 1863), B. l. iopas (Godman and Salvin 1897) and B. l. rhipidus (Rothschild and Jordan 1906).

This species was recently proposed, following the discovery that southwestern and eastern populations of Heraclides cresphontes differed both genetically and in wing patterning (Shiraiwa et al. 2014). Described as part of the genus Heraclides, but now part of the genus Papilio, of which Heraclides is a subgenus (see below).

Some taxonomic sources have elevated the subgenus Heraclides to species level (e.g. Hancock 1983, Warren et al. 2016); however, molecular studies on Papilio phylogeny (e.g. Aubert et al. 1999, Caterino and Sperling 1999) showed that there was little support for this. Additional ongoing work has come to the same conclusion that there is no evidence for splitting Papilio into several subgenera (F. Sperling and F. Condamine pers. comm. March 2020).
The holotype of this species was originally designated as a paratype of Lestidiops pacificus described by Parr (1931).

Harry (1953) reported that the two known types were not conspecific and recognized the holotype as a valid species and the paratype was described as a new species, Lestidium neles (now Lestidiops neles). Some records from the western Pacific Ocean were confused with Lestidiops jayakari (H. Ho pers. comm. 2019).
This species may belong in the genus Lestidiops. The taxonomy of Lestidiops is quite confused and a complete revision is needed (H. Ho pers. comm. 2019).
According to Ghedotti et al. (2015), this species should be placed in the family Lestidiidae.

According to Moore (2002), this species is only known from juvenile specimens and some specimens identified as Anoplogaster cornuta may be adult forms of A. brachycera. The validity of this species is in question due to recent genetic analyses (J. Moore pers. comm. 2018).
Savinykh and Baitalyuk (2011) suggested Trachipterus altivelis is a junior synonym of T. trachypterus, but this requires further study.

The status of the subspecies is unclear. Although eight subspecies have been recognized (Seymour 1989), morphological and genetic analyses do not support the existence of discrete subspecies (Larson 1997, Eizirik et al. 2001, Ruiz-Garcia et al. 2006). While not elevating the regional differences to the subspecies level, Eizirk et al. (2001) found evidence for four incompletely isolated phylogeographic groups: Mexico and Guatemala, southern Central America, northern South America, and South America south of the Amazon River. Similarly, Ruiz-Garcia et al. (2006) found that the Andes Mountains incompletely isolates Jaguar populations in Colombia.
Cryptotis goodwini and Cryptotis griseoventris are sister species. Cryptotis goodwini are larger in size; however, cranial measurements of the species broadly overlap (Woodman 2010).
This species is a heterotypic synonym of Platymiscium pleiostachyum (Klitgaard 2005). It is included on CITES appendix II as this synonym.

Last et al. (2016a) revised the genus Rhinobatos, transferring glaucostigma, horkelii, lentiginosus, leucorhynchus, percellens, planiceps, prahli, and productus to the new genus Pseudobatos.

In Chile, a second rhinobatid species is known from just a dried head: Tarsistes philippi Jordan, 1918. The taxonomic situation of this species is not clear.
The genus Hypanus formerly was a junior synonym of Dasyatis (Kottelat, 2013); it was resurrected by Last et al. (2016) in their revision of the family Dasyatidae.
Last et al. (2016a) revised the genus Rhinobatos, transferring glaucostigma, horkelii, lentiginosus, leucorhynchus, percellens, planiceps, prahli, and productus to the new genus Pseudobatos.
Last et al. (2016) revised the genus Rhinobatos, transferring glaucostigma, horkelii, lentiginosus, leucorhynchus, percellens, planiceps, prahli, and productus to the new genus Pseudobatos.

There has been a great deal of historic uncertainty regarding the taxonomic status of Eastern Pacific gymnurids, with some authors considering Gymnura crebripunctata to be a junior synonym of G. marmorata. However, Smith et al. (2009) confirmed the validity of G. crebripunctata as a distinct species using both morphometric and molecular techniques.

Cestrum guatemalense Francey is an accepted name for the species.There has been a taxonomic confusion between Cestrum guatemalense, C. mexicanum and C. pacayense, species distributed in southern Mexico, Guatemala, Honduras and El Salvador. This is due to the plasticity of some of their morphological characters, so they have even been proposed as synonyms (Castillo-Batista et al. 2017).However, a recent morphometric study carried out by Castillo-Batista et al. (2017) indicates that they are different species.
This species was previously accepted as Symplocos matudae Lundell; it is now accepted as Symplocos pycnantha Hemsl. (Kelly et al. 2016).
This species is easily confused with Neoscopelus macrolepidotus (Roberts 2015).
The two populations of this species may correspond to distinct species.
Originally considered a subspecies of soricina.
There is possibly confusion between identifications of Diaphus aliciae and D. impostor, and taxonomic work is ongoing (A. Williams and J. Paxton pers. comm. 2018).
According to Evseenko (2008), Triphoturus mexicanus has two genetically different forms; one in California and one in Peru.
Closely related to Elops saurus of the western Atlantic.

Historically, it has been proposed that American Eels (Anguilla rostrata) and European Eels (A. anguilla) may be conspecific (vertebral count differences were believed to be entirely ecophenotypic); this has now been shown to be incorrect by several studies. Separate species status has been confirmed by demonstrations that American and European Eels comprise two largely separate gene pools (see Avise et al. 1990, Bastrop et al. 2000, Avise 2003, Bernatchez et al. 2011). Eels in Iceland include, in low frequency, the products of hybridisation between American and European Eels (Avise et al. 1990, Avise 2003, Albert et al. 2006, Pujolar et al. 2014). Phylogenies of the genus Anguilla based on mitochondrial DNA have shown the two species to be distinct, although more closely related than most species of the genus (Aoyama et al. 2001, Minegishi et al. 2005).
Persea caerulea (Ruiz & Pav.) Mez is a wild relative of avocado, P. americana Mill. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).
This species was previously considered a possible synonym of Pseudoscopelus scriptus by Prokofiev and Kukuev (2007), but further investigation by Prokofiev (2011, 2014) concluded it is valid.
Ciccaba nigrolineata (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Strix.

Although three subspecies, costaricensis (S Honduras to W Panama), salmoni (C Colombia) and viduata (NW Ecuador), have been described, their diagnosability and geographical ranges are uncertain; further study required. Monotypic.
This species is part of the Diaphus fulgens complex in the eastern Pacific (Wisner 1976).

The Sei Whale, Balaenoptera borealis is a recognized species but catch and sightings records of Sei Whales prior to 1972 tended to include Bryde's Whales (B. edeni or B. brydei) in areas where both species occur. The Society for Marine Mammalogy’s Committee on Taxonomy (Committee on Taxonomy 2017) recognizes two subspecies, B. b. borealis in the Northern Hemisphere and B. b. schlegelii in the Southern Hemisphere, as proposed by Tomilin (1957). The Sei Whales found in the North Pacific and North Atlantic have not been formally compared and so are still placed in the same nominate subspecies by default, although Huijser et al. (2018) found a high degree of genetic divergence between North Atlantic and North Pacific Sei Whales.
A possible nomenclature problem with species name needs to be clarified between L. Chao and L. Findley.
This species is easily misidentified as congeneric species.
This species is easily misidentified as congeneric species.
This species is easily misidentified as congeneric species.
Original orthography is petersii.
This species is often misidentified with cogenerics.
This species is often misidentified with cogenerics.
