This species is often misidentified with cogenerics.
Amazona autumnalis, A. diadema and A. lilacina (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as A. autumnalis following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Bubo virginianus and B. magellanicus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as B. virginianusfollowing Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Amaurospiza moesta and A. relicta (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped within A. moesta, which was previously split into A. moesta, A. concolor and A. carrizalensis following following SACC (2005 and updates); Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).
Pheugopedius atrogularis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously listed as Thryothorus atrogularis.
Spinus psaltria (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Carduelis following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Oxyura jamaicensis and O. ferruginea (incorporating andina) (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as O. jamaicensis following SACC (2005), and before then were split as O. jamaicensis (incorporating andina) and O. ferruginea following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Psittacara holochlorus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was formerly placed in the genus Aratinga and previously split into A. holochlora and A. brevipes, following Stotz et al. (1996).
Thryothorus ludovicianus and T. albinucha (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as T. ludovicianus (see AOU [1998 & supplements]; Sibley & Monroe [1990, 1993]; Stotz et al. [1996]).

The BirdLife Taxonomic Working Group is aware that phylogenetic analyses have been published which have proposed generic rearrangements which may affect this species, but prefers to wait until work by other taxonomists reveals how these changes affect the entire groups involved.
Thalasseus maximus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Sterna as S. maxima.
Sternula antillarum (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Sterna.
Ardenna creatopus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Puffinus.
Hydrobates microsoma (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genera Oceanodroma and Halocyptena.
Sula dactylatra (AOU 1998 + updates) and Sula tasmani (Christidis and Boles 1994) have been lumped as S. dactylatra following Christidis and Boles (2008).

Following Kennedy and Spencer (2014) the genus Phalacrocorax has been divided into seven genera, with P. auritum, P. brasilianum and P. harrisi moved into Nannopterum (HBW and BirdLife International 2018). Long referred to as P. olivaceus, but brasilianus has priority (Browning 1989); P. olivaceus thus a junior synonym. Proposed subspecies chancho (Sonora, in NW Mexico) is synonymised with mexicanum, and hornensis (S Chile) with nominate. Two subspecies usually recognised.

The placement of this species in the Macrouridae is not supported by current morphological and genetic analyses; instead, it belongs in the family Steindachneriidae (Howes 1993, Roa-Varón and Ortí 2009).
This species is commonly confused with Malacocephalus occidentalis and Ventrifossa mucocephalus (Cohen et al. 1990).
This species is commonly confused with Ventrifossa macropogon.

The systematics of the genus Chiasmodon is still poorly understood and the exact number of species is unknown. There are two main theories: Prokofiev and Kukuev (2009) consider the existence of only two species in the genus (C. niger and C. lavenbergi), while Melo (2009) defends the existence of seven species in the genus (including C. pluriradiatus). For the purpose of this assessment, we are treating C. pluriradiatus as a valid species. Further taxonomic research on this genus is needed.

Two species descriptions were occurring simultaneously, Kali caribbaea Prokofiev 2008 and K. colubrina Melo 2008. These descriptions were accepted and published within a very short time, leading to disagreement as to which species name had priority (Melo 2010, Prokofiev 2011). Based on the ICZN rules and interpretations, K. colubrina was given priority (e.g., Melo 2010, Eschmeyer et al. 2018).

Bathophilus longipes has been treated as a junior synonym of B. digitatus by some authors, but is considered a valid species according to the Catalog of Fishes. Given this taxonomic uncertainty, its distribution is not clearly understood (T. Harold pers. comm. 2018).
This species was once considered a subspecies of Eustomias bigelowi (Parin and Pokhil’skaya 1974). It is considered a valid species by Clarke (2000, 2001) and Harold (2002).

Guatteria tomentosa is very well recognizable by the long-persistent indument of erect stiff hairs pointed flower buds and long sepals of 5-13 mm long. The leaf base of this species is extremely variable. It goes from obtuse cordate to even stem-clasping and is often oblique. It could be confused with G. hirsuta but from that species it differs by its erect instead of erect and appressed indument on most parts of the plant and by often revolute basal leaf margins (Maas et al. 2015).

Typical Guatteria amplifolia is encountered throughout Panama into Costa Rica, Nicaragua and all other western Central American. It has substantial morphological variation. We consider all of the variation to be encompassed within a single species (Maas et al. 2015).
According to Tropicos (2019) and The Plant List (2019), Brachistus nelsonii (Fernald) D´Arcy, J.L.Gentry & Averett is an accepted name for this species.

Cestrum laxum is the accepted name for this species. Many of the collections of this species made in Mexico have been identified as Cestrum anagyris, but it has been suggested that this species is a synonym of Cestrum laxum.

Cestrum pacayense Francey is an accepted name for the species.There has been a taxonomic confusion between Cestrum guatemalense, C. mexicanum and C. pacayense, species distributed in southern Mexico, Guatemala, Honduras and El Salvador. This is due to the plasticity of some of their morphological characters, so they have even been proposed as synonyms (Castillo-Batista et al. 2017).However, a recent morphometric study carried out by Castillo-Batista et al. (2017) indicates that they are different species.

According to Tropicos (2019), Lycianthes armentalis J. L. Gentry is an accepted name for this species. This species has been confused with Lycianthes sideroxyloides Schlecht. in herbaria. It differs from that species by its longer calyx appendages, unequal stamens, and fewer flowers in the inflorescences (Gentry and Standley 1974).

According to Tropicos (2019), Lycianthes arrazolensis (J. M. Coult. & Donn. Sm.) Bitter is an accepted name for this species. Lycianthes arrazolensis is a species very similar morphologically with Lycianthes tricolor and its relation has been a little conflictive since it is difficult to distinguish them if you do not have ripe fruit and in some cases hybridization is suspected, so more studies are needed in this regard than resolve the relationships between these species (Reyes 2015). There is a wide range of morphological variation within Lycianthes arrazolensis, especially in leaf size, leaf shape, and density of pubescence. This is particularly true of populations in the state of Oaxaca and Guerrero where small-leaved forms with very dense pubescence as well as large-leaved forms with sparse pubescence are found. The populations with larger leaves and sparser pubescence are usually found below 1,500 m, while those with denser pubescence are usually found above 2,000 m (Dean et al. 2017).

Witheringia meiantha (Donn. Sm.) Hunz. is an accepted name for this species. Witheringia meiantha is a species very similar to Witheringia solanacea, however they present some characteristics that differentiate them (Nee 1986).
This species is treated as distinct from Leucaena salvadorensis following Hughes 1998.

According to Tropicos (2019) and The Plant List (2019), Solanum nigricans M. Martens & Galeotti is an accepted name for this species. Solanum nigricans is superficially similar to and probably the sister species of Solanum maturecalvans of the Andes, sharing with that species patchy arachnoid pubescence and difoliate, geminate sympodial units (Knapp 2002).
This species has frequently been erroneously identified in Central American locations as Fuchsia arborescens Sims, which only occurs in Mexico from Jalisco to Oaxaca.

This taxon, endemic to central Mexico, has been frequently misidentified and confused with other species; for this reason, this nomenclatural combination became for a long time a home for many taxa, which caused a lot of confusion.
The taxonomy of the genus Clusia is very complex; some specimens of C. flava may be hybrids with C. guatemalensis which has smaller leaves, flowers and fruit, and which grows at higher elevations.
Specimens from El Salvador, Colombia, Peru and Bolivia are uncertain and need more comprehensive taxonomic studies.
Melozone biarcuata and M. cabanisi (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as M. biarcuata following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).
Sporophila funerea (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Oryzoborus and listed as O. funereus following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Stotz et al. (1996).

Cardellina pusilla (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Wilsonia following AERC TAC (2003); AOU (1998 & supplements); Cramp et al. (1977-1994); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Cardellina canadensis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Wilsonia following AERC TAC (2003); AOU (1998 & supplements); Cramp et al. (1977-1994); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Basileuterus lachrymosus (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Euthlypis and listed as E. lachrymosa following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Myiothlypis fulvicauda (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Phaeothlypis following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).
Setophaga townsendi (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Dendroica following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Setophaga petechia (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Dendroica following AERC TAC (2003); AOU (1998 & supplements); Cramp et al. (1977-1994); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Setophaga fusca (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Dendroica following AERC TAC (2003); AOU (1998 & supplements); Cramp et al. (1977-1994); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Setophaga magnolia (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Dendroica following AERC TAC (2003); AOU (1998 & supplements); Cramp et al. (1977-1994); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Setophaga tigrina (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Dendroica following AERC TAC (2003); AOU (1998 & supplements); Cramp et al. (1977-1994); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Setophaga citrina (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Wilsonia following AERC TAC (2003); AOU (1998 & supplements); Cramp et al. (1977-1994); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Geothlypis formosa (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Oporornis and listed as O. formosus following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Geothlypis philadelphia (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Oporornis following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Leiothlypis peregrina (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Vermivora following AERC TAC (2003); AOU (1998 & supplements); Cramp et al. (1977-1994); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).
Oreothlypis superciliosa (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Parula following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Vireo olivaceus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) has been split into Red-eyed Vireo V. olivaceus and Chivi Vireo V. chivi, as previously adopted by Stotz et al. (1996). Battey and Klicka (2017) strengthen this case on the basis of complete genetic separation and entirely antithetical patterns of movement but make no attempt to consider morphological characters. Boesman (2016) provides further support via finding that there is an extreme likelihood that there are consistent differences between the songs, (allowing a score of 4), plus chivi has a dark brown versus ruby-red iris (3) and the different migratory habits (maximum permitted score 1). Consequently, Chivi Vireo V. chivi is accorded species status.

(1996). Paraphyletic with respect to C. tacarcunae, C. inornatus and C. semifuscus (Weir et al. 2008). Constituent taxa, which may or may not break down into a number of species, exhibit a high degree of mosaic variation involving pale or dark irides, presence or absence of a white postocular patch, colour of crown, throat and breast, morphometrics, voice (Boesman 2016) and genetics; despite important insights in a succession of studies (Bonaccorso et al. 2008, Maldonado-Sánchez et al. 2016, Sánchez-González et al. 2007, Sosa-López et al. 2013, Weir et al. 2008) no unequivocal new rearrangement has yet emerged for adoption (Avendano et al. 2013, Dickinson and Christidis 2014), and a comprehensive integrative analysis of the complex is still badly needed (including the evaluation of poorly defined taxa). Subspecies punctulatus has sometimes been treated as a full species, as have cinereocephalus and the “flavopectus group” (also including trudis, nigriceps, exitelus, macarenae and phaeocephalus). Proposed subspecies novicius represents intergrades between regionalis and punctulatus (Olson 1993). Proposed subspecies persimilis (described from R Guajolote, SW of San Miguel Suchixtepec, in Oaxaca, Mexico) regarded as synonymous with albifrons (Binford 1989), although genetic data offer support for its recognition (Weir et al. 2008). Species name long given as ophthalmicus, but flavopectus has priority (SACC 2012). Twenty-six subspecies currently recognized.

Two species are recognized in the genus Sotalia: S. guianensis, the Guiana Dolphin, and S. fluviatilis, the Tucuxi. They are very similar in appearance and the genus was long considered monotypic. Two issues concerning the taxonomy of the dolphins in particular parts of the range of the genus deserve mention.

First, there is some uncertainty about the taxonomic status and range of Guiana Dolphins in the Orinoco River. There are frequent records of Sotalia at Ciudad Bolívar, some 300 km upstream from the river mouth. Such records are suspected to correspond to S. guianensis (da Silva and Best 1996, Meade and Koehnken 1991, Flores and da Silva 2009, da Silva et al. 2010). It is generally assumed that Sotalia dolphins cannot traverse the rapids at the Casiquiare Channel, which connects the Orinoco and Amazon basins (da Silva and Best 1996). This barrier has existed since the uplift of the Mérida Cordillera (10 million years ago; Lundberg et al. 1998), which predates the divergence of the two species of Sotalia (Cunha et al. 2005, Caballero et al. 2007, 2008). Thus, Sotalia in the Middle Orinoco are likely to be an isolated population of Guiana Dolphins (da Silva et al. 2010, Cunha et al. 2010). Seven animals from the Orinoco all possessed the same mitochondrial DNA sequences and had an estimated divergence from S. guianensis of 640,000 years ago (Caballero et al. 2017). Caballero et al. (2017) suggested that the Orinoco River animals belong to an independent population unit isolated from other coastal populations and worthy of separate conservation and management efforts.

The second issue relates to the taxonomic status of Sotalia dolphins from the southern freshwater portion of Maracaibo Lake. Those individuals are morphologically different from the marine Sotalia that inhabit the northern portion of the lake, adjacent to the Gulf of Venezuela. Dolphins from southern Maracaibo are smaller than marine Sotalia and about the same size as S. fluviatilis (Casinos et al. 1981, da Silva and Best 1996, León 2005). However, there is no connection between Maracaibo Lake and the known present-day range of riverine Sotalia, and the lake has been isolated from the Amazon basin for the last 8-10 million years (Hoorn et al. 1995, Días de Gamero 1996 cited in Cunha et al. 2010). The morphological distinctiveness of the southern Maracaibo Lake Sotalia population could be a result of phenotypic plasticity, unlike the difference between S. guianensis and S. fluviatilis. However, it may also indicate a lack of gene flow with the marine Sotalia from the mouth of the lake and the Gulf of Venezuela. Indeed, Caballero et al. (2006) observed some exclusive haplotypes in samples from the lake, but they did not consider this to signify a species-level difference. All haplotypes in Maracaibo Lake were S. guianensis (Caballero et al. 2017) with one of those being most closely related to the single haplotype found in the Orinoco River. Both of the populations here—in Maracaibo Lake and the Orinoco River—would meet the IUCN definition of a subpopulation.

No subspecies of False Killer Whale (Pseudorca crassidens) are currently recognized. However, there is evidence of geographic variability in skull morphology and life history (Kitchener et al. 1990, Ferreira et al. 2014). Based on genetics there is substantial population structure, both between and within-ocean basins, and even within a single archipelago (Martien et al. 2014). This species has been intensively studied only in Hawaii (Baird 2016) and more recently in New Zealand (Zaeschmar 2014). In Hawaii, three subpopulations have been identified based on a combination of genetic studies (Martien et al. 2014), satellite tagging (Baird et al. 2010, 2012, 2014, Bradford et al. 2014a), and analyses of photo-identification data (Baird et al. 2008, Baird 2016). These include two partially overlapping insular populations, one around the main Hawaiian Islands, and one in the northwestern Hawaiian Islands, as well as a partially overlapping pelagic population that ranges throughout and beyond the U.S. Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) around the Hawaiian Archipelago. In New Zealand, based on high resighting rates of photo-identified individuals and a relatively small number of individuals documented, it is likely that this represents a distinct subpopulation (Zaeschmar 2014). While the number of subpopulations world-wide is unknown, this is due primarily to incomplete sampling in most of the range. Based on the evidence from Hawaii, subpopulation structure likely exists throughout their range.
In Costa Rica, this species is very closely related to Aiouea pittieri and A. tonduzii (González and Hammel 2007).
The taxonomic relationship of this species to Cryptotriton monzoni needs to be investigated (D. Wake and G. Parra-Olea pers. comm. 2007).

Almeda en Flora de Nicaragua (2001) establece que “Se necesitan colectas adicionales de esta especie, de Mesoamérica, para determinar si es coespecífica con Henriettea patrisiana DC. del norte de Sudamérica” y menciona una serie de características que se traslapan entre ambas especies, pero al momento de esta evaluación con la evidencia disponible la estamos tratando como una especie válida y distinta.

En Honduras ha sido considerado siempre bajo el nombre de Ardisia austin-smithii Lundell (Nelson Sutherland, 2008) pero todos los autores que trabajan en las floras de la región lo consideran ahora como un sinónimo (Davidse et al., 2009; Morales, 2007) recientes lo consideran como un sinónimo de Gentlea austin-smithii (Lundell) Lundell.

El nombre correcto de esta especie es Gentlea lancifolia Lundell. Ardisia intibucana Lundell, fue propuesto por Lundell (1986) como un nombre nuevo en caso que se pasara al género Ardisia (una nueva circunscripción del género), pero este nombre es inválido con base en el Artículo 34.1 del CINB, por lo que el nombre que le corresponde a esta especie es Gentlea lancifolia Lundell el cual es aceptado por la mayoría de autores de la región (Stevens et al., 2001; Davidse et al., 2009).
Esta especie tiene dos variedades (ambas presentes en Honduras según Nelson (2001 [2002], Nelson Sutherland 2008),  en esta evaluación se considera la especie en su totalidad

Esta especie fue transferida al género Myrcia recientemente (Lourenço et al., 2018). Anteriormente estaba en el género Calyptanthes y mucha de la información concerniente al taxón aún se encuentra bajo ese género.
Thalasseus sandvicensis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Sterna.
Onychoprion anaethetus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Sterna.

Himantopus himantopus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously split as H. himantopus, H. leucocephalus and H. mexicanus and following AOU (1998) and SACC (2006). Prior to that, H. melanurus had been split from H. mexicanus following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Ardea alba (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Casmerodius as C. albus. Casmerodius albus (Sibley and Monroe 1990, 1993) was previously retained as a cross-regional species contra Christidis and Boles (2008) who moved C. albus into the genus Ardea and split it into two cross-regional species A. alba and A. modesta (note gender agreement of specific name for alba).
Hydroprogne caspia (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Sterna.

Passer domesticus and P. italiae (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as P. domesticus following AERC TAC (2003); AOU (1998 and supplements); Christidis and Boles (2008); Cramp et al. (1977-1994); Dowsett and Forbes-Watson (1993); SACC (2005 and updates); Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996); Turbott (1990).

Riparia riparia and R. diluta (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as R. riparia following AERC TAC (2003), AOU (1998 and supplements), Cramp and Simmons (1977–1994), Dowsett and Forbes-Watson (1993), SACC (2005 and updates), Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993), and Stotz et al. (1996).
Larus argentatus and L. smithsonianus (the latter including vegae and mongolicus) (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as L. argentatus following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Flathead Mullet taxonomy remains unresolved, and there is a wealth of evidence suggesting that it comprises a complex of closely-related species rather than a single cosmopolitan taxon (Whitfield et al. 2012, Durand and Borsa 2015). It is thus likely to be revised in the future.
It is easily confused with Syacium ovale (Murakami and Amaoka 1992).
This species is very similar to the congener Syacium ovale (Murakami and Amaoka 1992).

The Committee on Taxonomy of the Society for Marine Mammalogy (Committee on Taxonomy 2016) provisionally lists the following subspecies: Balaenoptera musculus musculus (Linnaeus, 1758) - Northern Blue Whale (found in the North Atlantic and the North Pacific); B. m. intermedia (Burmeister, 1871) - Antarctic Blue Whale; B. m. indica (Blyth 1859) - Northern Indian Ocean Blue Whale; B. m. brevicauda (Ichihara, 1966) - Pygmy Blue Whale; and B. m. un-named subspecies - Chilean Blue Whale.

The nominate subspecies B. m. musculus refers at least to the North Atlantic Blue Whale which was the basis for the first description of the species by Linnaeus. Animals in the North Pacific are similar in size and morphology to North Atlantic Blue Whales and are also regarded as B. m. musculus, pending a genetic comparison of these populations. The Antarctic form B. m. intermedia is distinguished by its large body size and Antarctic distribution in summer. The Pygmy Blue Whale B. m. brevicauda has a number of morphological characteristics that distinguish it from B. m. intermedia and B. m. musculus. It occurs in the Indian Ocean, excluding the Antarctic, from Africa and Madagascar across to Indonesia and Australia, and in the southwestern Pacific, including Tasmania and New Zealand. Blue Whales in the northern Indian Ocean have been tentatively assigned the name B. m. indica, but a clear distinction between B. m. indica and B. m. brevicauda has not yet been established.

Blue Whales in the southeastern Pacific are intermediate in size between B. m. intermedia and B. m. brevicauda (Branch et al. 2007a) and are genetically differentiated from both groups (LeDuc et al. 2017). They are provisionally designated as an unnamed subspecies with the common name Chilean Blue Whales. Chilean Blue Whales are genetically most similar to Blue Whales in the northeast Pacific (LeDuc et al. 2017); investigations into the genetic and morphological distinction between these two groups are ongoing. The respective winter ranges of Blue Whales from the eastern South Pacific (Chilean Blue whales) and from the eastern North Pacific may overlap in the eastern equatorial Pacific but their breeding seasons are probably six months out of phase (LeDuc et al. 2017).

Recent genetic work indicates that the genus Stenella is paraphyletic and it is likely that the Delphininae will be restructured in the coming years (LeDuc et al. 1999, Perrin et al. 2013).

Four subspecies of Spinner Dolphins are currently recognized: S. l. longirostris (Gray’s Spinner Dolphin), S. l. orientalis (Eastern Spinner Dolphin), S. l. centroamericana (Central American Spinner Dolphin) and S. l. roseiventris (Dwarf Spinner Dolphin) (Perrin 1990, Perrin et al. 1999). There is a zone of hydridisation between Gray’s Spinner and the Eastern Spinner where an intermediate form called the White-bellied Spinner occurs (Andrews et al. 2013). Smaller individuals in Arabian waters (Red Sea and Arabian Gulf) (Van Waerebeek et al. 1999) and morphologically different animals in West Africa may represent as yet undescribed subspecies (Cadenat 1959, Jefferson et al. 1997). Several studies have demonstrated significant meta-population genetic structure, especially where relatively insular dolphin communities are strongly associated with island resting habitat such as in the Hawaiian Archipelago (Andrews et al. 2013) and in the South Pacific (Oremus et al. 2007).

Of the two species presently recognized within the genus Tursiops (the Common Bottlenose Dolphin T. truncatus, and the Indo-Pacific Bottlenose Dolphin T. aduncus) only the former is known to occur in the Paneuropean area. The subspecies Tursiops truncatus ponticus is recognized to occur in the Black Sea.
This species is frequently misidentified as Symphurus elongatus (Mahadeva and Munroe 1990).
This species is frequently misidentified as Symphurus chabanaudi (Mahadeva and Munroe 1990).

Symphurus leei Jordan and Bollman 1890 was named after Professor L.A. Lee and Mr. Thomas Lee. According to Fricke et al. (2021), the appropriate spelling of the specific epithet should be leeorum because this is the correct form when the species was named after two people (ICZN Article 31.1.2).
Munroe (1990) placed Symphurus seychellensis Chabanaud 1955 and S. sechurae Hildebrand 1946 into the synonymy of S. melanurus Clark 1936.

Although Physeter catodon is still occasionally used in the literature, P. macrocephalus is recommended (Rice 1989). Both names are listed on the same page of the original description by Linnaeus (1758), and priority is unclear. However, P. macrocephalus is preferable because it is used much more frequently, and this will support nomenclatural stability.
This species was described in 2001.

Aegiphila panamensis is closely related to Aegiphila mollis and they are difficult to separate. There are older names that can be apply for this species (A. panamensis), including:  A. mollis Kunth, A. filipes Mart. & Schauer and A. peruviana Turcz.; a taxonomic research is needed in order to clarify this complex. (Rueda and Hammel 2015).
This species is close related to Aiouea pittieri, because some collections seem to integrate and might represent hybrids due to they share some morphological characters (González and  Hammel 2007).

This species is similar to Acalypha apodanthes, there are some collections that exhibit characters in common, representing or suggesting variability or hybridization between those species (González 2010).
Morales (2007), treated Parathesis aeruginosa as a synonym of P. fusca, because morpholical differences between those species overlap.
The Costarican material belongs to Robinsonella lindeniana subsp. divergens (Rose & Baker f.) Fryxell (Fryxell 2007).
This species was previously included in the genus Hyla but has recently been moved to the new genus Ecnomiohyla (Faivovich et al. 2005).
Zentrygon albifacies (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Geotrygon.
Antrostomus badius (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Caprimulgus.
Hydropsalis maculicaudus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Caprimulgus.

Puffinus lherminieri (incorporating baroli), P. bannermani, P. persicus, P. subalaris and P. bailloni (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as P. lherminieri and baroli was subsumed under P. assimilis, following Brooke (2004), before which P. bannermani and P. persicus where split following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Momotus momota, M. coeruliceps, M. lessonii, M. subrufescens, M. bahamensis and M. aequatorialis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as M. momota following SACC (2005). Prior to that, M. aequatorialis had been split following Stotz et al. (1996), and before that all forms were lumped with M. momota following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Butorides striata (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously split as B. striata and B. virescens following AOU (2003), and before then B. striata was split as B. striatus and B. sundevalli following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993). Gender agreement of B. striata follows David and Gosselin (2002).
Anous tenuirostris and A. minutus (Sibley and Monroe 1990, 1993), cross-regional species, are retained as separate species contra Turbott (1990) who includes minutus as a subspecies of tenuirostris.

Possibly closest to T. curucui, T. elegans (with T. ambiguus), T. mexicanus, T. collaris and T. personatus; DNA studies suggest that T. elegans (with T. ambiguus), T. collaris and T. personatus may be nearest relatives. Dickens et al. (2021) proposed several species-level splits within T. rufus but more evidence required; their proposed species T. muriciensis from the Atlantic Forest of north-eastern Brazil and known only from the type locality treated here as a subspecies of T. rufus. Seven subspecies recognized.
Trogon collaris (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously split as T. collaris and T. aurantiiventris following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
This species is one of four species within the Poecilia sphenops species complex (Bagley et al. 2015).

A number of molecular studies have suggested that this species may be synonymous with the widely distributed P. mexicana (Bagley et al. 2015, Ho et al. 2016, Palacios et al. 2016, Sanchez et al. 2019). Current taxonomic understanding treats this species as distinct from P. mexicana, although additional research is needed to confirm the validity of this species (Fricke et al. 2020).

Solitary polyps of Mussa angulosa have been sometimes identified as Scolymia lacera (Veron 2000; see also Fenner 1993). According to the World Register of Marine Species (WoRMS), this species is valid (database accessed September 2021).
This species is a complex (Gijsbers et al. 2023).

Orbicella franksi was identified as Montastraea annularis until 1994, when ecological, morphological, and molecular studies provided evidence that it was part of a species complex composed of three species: M. annularis, M. faveolata and M. franksi (Weil and Knowlton 1994). Consequently, most studies prior to 1994 do not distinguish between the three species, and information on population is difficult to disaggregate for the three taxa. Later, Budd et al. (2012) separated modern species of the genus Montastraea into three genera: Montastraea de Blainville, 1830 (Atlantic Montastraea cavernosa), Orbicella Dana, 1846 (Atlantic Orbicella annularis complex), and Phymastrea Milne Edwards and Haime, 1848 (Indo-Pacific).

According to the WoRMS database (accessed August 2021), Dichotaenia stellaris is a junior synonym of D. stokesii. Colonies from lower reef slopes or shaded habitats have markedly smaller corallites than those from more exposed environments, and are usually identified as D. stellaris (Veron 2000).

Montastraea annularis (Weil and Knowlton 1994) has been split into three species, including M. faveolata and M. franksi. Consequently, most studies prior to 1994 do not distinguish between the three species, and information on population is difficult to disaggregate for the three taxa. Later, Budd et al. (2012) separated modern species of the genus Montastraea into three genera: Montastraea de Blainville, 1830 (Atlantic Montastraea cavernosa), Orbicella Dana, 1846 (Atlantic Orbicella annularis complex), and Phymastrea Milne Edwards and Haime, 1848 (Indo-Pacific).

This taxon is now classified under the family Pocilloporidae, along with all Madracis species (Benzoni et al. 2018). Moreover, recent genetic and morphological evidence suggests it is highly probable that the Caribbean zooxanthellate species Madracis pharensis f. luciphila is actually a completely separate species to the cave-dwelling M. pharensis found in the eastern Atlantic (Azores and Mediterranean; Benzoni et al. 2018). As M. pharensis was originally described from the Adriatic Sea by Heller (1868), it is likely that the populations of M. pharensis f. luciphila described by Wells (1973) will have to adopt a new species name.

The consequences of these new findings are a restricted geographic range in what we now know as M. pharensis f. luciphila, compared to the 2008 IUCN Red List assessment. A recent work on the evolution of symbiosis and coloniality of Scleractinia has shown that the Madracis genus may not be monophyletic with two lineages diverging early in the tree, one of M. decactis, M. senaria, M. kirbyi and M. pharensis clustering with Dendrophylliidae in the Robusta clade, while M. asanoi, M. myriaster, M. formosa and M. carmabi together with Pocilloporidae in the Complex clade (Navarro-Campoy et al. 2020). These results must be taken with caution before taxonomic decisions are made as the phylogenetic analyses of Navarro-Campoy et al. (2020) are based on incomplete sampling of molecular markers across the analysed Madracis species, and mainly based on nuclear marker 28s, which is a multicopy gene with intragenomic variation.

Recent genetic revisions have confirmed a long-standing suspicion that M. pharensis in the Caribbean (a zooxanthellate form, often referred to as M. pharensis f. luciphila) is in fact not the same species as the M. pharensis found in the Mediterranean (a cave-loving species often found without zooxanthellae, sometimes referred to as M. pharensis f. pharensis to distinguish it from Luciphila in the Caribbean; Benzoni et al. 2018). Clear genetic and morphological differences suggest these are two different species and reduces the known range of this species compared to the 2008 IUCN Red List assessment, when it was thought to be pan-Atlantic and found in the Azores and Mediterranean (Benzoni et al. 2018). Madracis pharensis f. luciphila has smaller corallites more closely packed together (Benzoni et al. 2018).

Other studies of M. pharensis f. luciphila show strong genetic divergence between deep (>25 m) and shallow (< 25 m) Caribbean populations, whereby both hosts and zooxanthellae are genetically different between depth zones (Frade et al. 2008). Madracis pharensis was previously thought to have a very broad depth distribution, but these findings suggest the existence of deep and shallow taxa. The genetic divergence observed between deep and shallow M. pharensis is similar to that measured for well-established interspecific comparisons (e.g. M. mirabilis and M. formosa), making it likely that these two groups represent subspecies or even cryptic species (Frade et al. 2010). These findings further suggest that the range of M. pharensis is more restricted both geographically and depth-wise. Smaller than presumed effective population sizes and more limited genetic exchange may leave these populations more vulnerable than previously assumed.

Controversy around the taxonomy of M. pharensis and assignation of new names for potentially new species within this species complex will remain until a complete sampling of this taxon is undertaken, including the different populations of the species reported not only in the Caribbean and Atlantic (Benzoni et al. 2018), but also in the Pacific (Cairns and Zibrowius 1997, see discussion in Cairns 2000). In this updated Red List assessment, we include data collected from both forms and referred to them accordingly.

In 2012, the genus Diploria was split into two separate genera: Diploria, which consists only of the species Diploria labyrinthiformis; and a new genus, Pseudodiploria, which consists of the species Pseudodiploria strigosa and Pseudodiploria clivosa (Budd et al. 2012).
Pocillopora danae is now a synonym of this species (WoRMS accessed January 2022).
Porites baueri and Porites excavata are now synonyms of this species (WoRMS accessed January 2022).

This species is commonly confused with Meandrina braziliensis. Smith (1971) recognized two species in the Caribbean, the sub-massive and platy form, M. meandrites, and a free-living form, M. danae, and a third species in Brazil, M. braziliensis. Most reports in the last 20 years refer to the free-living form in the Caribbean as M. braziliensis. Review of the genus in the Caribbean has confirmed the identity of M. danae as the free-living form distinct from M. braziliensis, the identity of M. meandrites as a sub-massive platy form and a new crustos species yet to be described (Pinzón and Weil 2011).

This species is comprised of a group of closely related yet clearly distinct genetic lineages representing at least eight newly defined species. The improved taxonomic scheme has helped to explain controversies over differences in life history strategies assumed for the species, such as reproductive mode or timing, however, evidence suggests that additional cryptic species remain to be identified (Schmidt-Roach et al. 2014).
This species was previously classified in the family Faviidae but is now under Montastraeidae (Huang et al. 2014).

Madracis formosa has been moved into Pocilloporidae, along with all Madracis species, as genetics has recently confirmed it is more closely related to Pocillopora than Stephanocoenia (Benzoni et al. 2018).

Orbicella faveolata was identified as Montastraea annularis until 1994, when ecological, morphological, and molecular studies provided evidence that it was part of a species complex composed of three species: M. annularis, M. faveolata and M. franksi (Weil and Knowlton 1994). Consequently, most studies prior to 1994 do not distinguish between the three species, and information on population is difficult to disaggregate for the three taxa. Later, Budd et al. (2012) separated modern species of the genus Montastraea into three genera: Montastraea de Blainville, 1830 (Atlantic Montastraea cavernosa), Orbicella Dana, 1846 (Atlantic Orbicella annularis complex), and Phymastrea Milne Edwards and Haime, 1848 (Indo-Pacific).

In 2012, the genus Diploria was split into two separate genera: Diploria, which consists only of the species Diploria labyrinthiformis; and a new genus, Pseudodiploria, which consists of the species Pseudodiploria strigosa and Pseudodiploria clivosa (Budd et al. 2012).
Siderastrea glynni is a subjective junior synonym of this species (Glynn et al. 2016).
This species is likely multiple species (Lewis pers comm. 2023).

This represents a species complex which is likely to be divisible into several cryptic species. The species irregularis has been used with three related genera, Porites, Napopora and Synaraea. Porites irregularis Verrill (1864) is not recognisable from the original description. The Porites irregularis of Vaughan (1907), Nemenzo (1955) and Maragos (1977) is this species. Napopora irregularis Quelch (1884) (illustrated by Bosserelle, Berteaux-Lecellier, Chancerelle et al. 2014) is currently under review but is likely to be accepted as a valid species.

There is discussion about species distinctions among Porties porites - Porites furcata - Porites divaricata, whether these species represent morphological variants of one diverse species or distinct species. It is suggested that genetic variation among these putative species occur along geographic gradients rather than taxonomy (Prada et al. 2014).

Features that distinguish this species from other Madracis species are the combination of (1) a branching morphology and (2) decameral septal organization. Vermeij et al. (2003) proposed that hybridization between Madracis decactis and Madracis formosa was the process leading to this new taxon. Madracis carmabi has been moved back into Pocilloporidae, along with all Madracis species, as genetics has recently confirmed it is more closely related to Pocillopora than Stephanocoenia (Benzoni et al. 2018). Madracis carmabi shares characteristics with two other Madracis species, i.e., colony morphology and septal arrangement correspond to that of M. formosa and M. decactis, respectively. Close relationships and exchange of genetic information have been found among Madracis species (Diekmann et al. 2001).
Veron (2000) synonymized Isophyllastrea with Isophyllia.
Psammocora superficialis is now a synonym of this species (WoRMS online database accessed March 2023).

There is discussion about species distinctions among Porites porites - Porites furcata - Porites divaricata, whether these species represent morphological variants of one diverse species or distinct species. It is suggested that genetic variation among these putative species occur along geographic gradients rather than taxonomy (Prada et al. 2014).

Madracis senaria has been moved into Pocilloporidae along with all Madracis species, as genetics has recently confirmed it is more closely related to Pocillopora than Stephanocoenia (Benzoni et al. 2018).

Madracis mirabilis (sensu Wells 1973)—a pale yellow shallow branching stony coral with cylindrical branches known as Yellow Pencil Coral—is a well studied species and the name ‘Madracis mirabilis’ is deeply entrenched within the literature to describe it. Locke et al. (2007) found this coral had never formally been described, and moreover, M. mirabilis (Duchassaing and Michelotti 1860) technically referred to a deep-water azooxanthellate species now synonymous with Madracis myriaster (Milne-Edwards and Haime 1849). Locke et al. (2007) described the Yellow Pencil Coral commonly known as M. mirabilis, as M. auretenra. However, many studies continue to use the name M. mirabilis to designate populations of this species (e.g. Frade et al. 2010, Veron et al. 2020) and there is some debate around whether replacing this well-established name with M. auretenra is adequately supported. The taxonomic debate about the validity of the new name M. auretenra in respect to M. mirabilis is based on the fact that the type specimen of M. mirabilis designated by Duchassaing and Michelotti (1860) was not revised by Locke et al. (2007) for the description of M. auretenra.

Claravis, as previously defined, was shown to be paraphyletic, with two of the three species grouping separately to C. pretiosi. These two need generic reallocation, moving to the new genus Paraclaravis (Sangster et al. 2018): hence P. geoffroyi and P. mondetoura.

Aramides cajaneus has been split into Grey-cowled Wood-rail A. cajaneus (with one subspecies A. c. avicenniae: latens and morrisoni are synonymised with cajaneus) and Russet-naped Wood-rail A. albiventris (with mexicanus, vanrossemi, pacificus, and plumbeicollis synonymised with albiventris) following an assessment of the evidence provided by Marcondes and Silveira (2015).

Phaethornis longirostris, P. mexicanus and P. baroni (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as P. longirostris following SACC (2005), and before then were also lumped with P. superciliosus as P. superciliosus following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Taxonomy somewhat confused, and precise distributions of subspecies not well known. Probably a sister-species of L. clemenciae (García-Moreno et al. 2006). Ornelas et al. (2016) argued for the treatment of margaritae as a ‘separate evolutionary unit’, which they proceeded to call Lampornis margaritae, but they fell short of calling it a separate species. This form has already been highlit in HBW as a possible split, but there (and in the Checklist [del Hoyo and Collar 2014], which gives the issue a fair airing) it is suggested that the forms salvini and nobilis would form part of the new split. This is difficult to follow, since these latter taxa have deep pinkish throats like the nominate and circumventus. In some male specimens of margaritae it appears that differences also involve greener vs bronzier dorsal feathering, a weaker white postocular line and a shorter bill, but these characters do not seem to be constant; and one specimen even seems to have a throat that is midway between pinkish and purplish. At present, therefore, it seems better to retain margaritae as a distinctive form of L. amethystinus. Proposed subspecies brevirostris doubtfully distinct from margaritae. Name of subspecies circumventus sometimes misspelt as circumventris. Five subspecies recognised.

Previously listed as Chlorostilbon canivetii (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), but moved to current genus following a recent overhaul of all genera by NACC, based on McGuire et al. (2014), Stiles et al. (2017a, b) and others. Formerly treated as one of many subspecies of C. mellisugus (which see); an alternative was, on basis of bill colour, to treat the five N subspecies (present species with auriceps, forficatus, osberti and salvini) as a separate species. A more radical evaluation of the complex (Stiles 1996) is largely followed here but, owing to both the sheer number of taxa in the original complex and the diaspora of specimen material, comparisons between taxa and decisions on their taxonomic status are limited mainly to geographical neighbours. Thus, present form, including subspecies osberti and salvini, is specifically distinct from C. auriceps, C. forficatus and C. assimilis on account of the diagnoses given under those species. Three subspecies currently recognized.

Previously listed as Campylopterus cuvierii (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), and before that in Phaeochroa, now moved back to latter genus following a recent overhaul of all genera by NACC, based on McGuire et al. (2014), Stiles et al. (2017a, b) and others. However, the thickened, flattened shaft of outer primary of adult male similar to that of other Campylopterus, and coloration, behaviour and vocalizations of some of the dull-coloured, sexually monochromatic Campylopterus species also resemble those of present species. Subspecies roberti sometimes given species status on basis of differences in bill and rectrix colour, but hardly distinctive. Six subspecies normally recognized.

Previously listed as Campylopterus curvipennis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), but moved to current genus following a recent overhaul of all genera by NACC, based on McGuire et al. (2014), Stiles et al. (2017a, b) and others. Campylopterus curvipennis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously split into C. curvipennis and C. excellens following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993), but differences not striking, involving slightly larger size, paler underparts and longer tail; molecular, morphological and vocal analysis (González et al. 2011) supports monophyly of the three subspecies, although this evidence plus the findings of larger skull size (Lowery and Dalquest 1951) may lend support to acceptance of excellens as a full species (Dickinson and Remsen 2013); none of the differences, however, appears particularly strong or compelling (e.g. much vocal overlap and variability), so all three taxa retained here as conspecific, but research required in zone of hypothetical contact between excellens and nominate. Subpopulation of Yucatán Peninsula sometimes regarded as subspecies yucatanensis, but doubtfully distinct. Three subspecies currently recognized.

Geographically isolated subspecies intermedia was included in the previous concept of Chalybura urochrysia (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) but is now included with C. buffonii, based largely on its greater similarity to the plumage of C. buffonii, especially in blue tail colour. Race melanorrhoa long considered a separate species, presumably on basis of its sooty-black vent (no other notable character), but intergrades with isaurae along border of Costa Rica with Panama. Proposed subspecies incognita (E Panama) probably best treated as a synonym of isaurae. Three subspecies recognized.

Thalurania colombica (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously split as T. colombica and T. fannyi following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993), and subsequently T. ridgwayi was recognised following AOU (1998).

Previously listed as Amazilia candida (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), but moved to current genus following a recent overhaul of all genera by NACC, based on McGuire et al. (2014), Stiles et al. (2017a, b) and others. Has been placed in genus Agyrtria. Subspecies genini has been questioned on the basis of some intergradation with nominate in E Mexico. Three subspecies recognized.

Previously listed as Amazilia cyanocephala (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), but moved to current genus following a recent overhaul of all genera by NACC, based on McGuire et al. (2014), Stiles et al. (2017a, b) and others. Sometimes placed in genus Agyrtria. Subspecies chlorostephana has been suggested as possibly approaching species status, but nominate (in E of range) shows clinal variation in crown colour (blue to green) towards chlorostephana; nevertheless, the smaller size and different habitat use (pine savanna) of chlorostephana suggest a significantly divergent taxon worthy of further taxonomic research. Birds from Belize S to N Nicaragua formerly separated as subspecies guatemalensis, but specimens from C and E Guatemala, including type locality of guatemalensis (Dueñas), show strong intergradation with nominate birds from Chiapas (S Mexico). In recent study, however, it was found that populations were separated genetically (mtDNA) by Isthmus of Tehuantepec, and this, together with associated morphological and environmental-niche differences observed, and results of coalescent-based test, indicated that selection had been sufficiently strong to counter effects of gene flow (Rodríguez-Gómez et al. 2013); further study needed. Proposed species Amazilia microrhyncha (Honduras and Nicaragua), known from two specimens and separated in part on basis of unusually short bill, does not merit even subspecific recognition because characters appear to be based on individual variation of present species or are those of juvenile, probably of nominate. Two subspecies recognized.

Previously listed as Amazilia beryllina (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), but moved to current genus following a recent overhaul of all genera by NACC, based on McGuire et al. (2014), Stiles et al. (2017a, b) and others. Closely related to S. cyanura; reports of hybridization in a small zone of sympatry in Guatemala and El Salvador seem to be unproven, and may be erroneously based on variable tail coloration of present species. Form sumichrasti, long ignored, has proved to represent a well-marked subspecies. Individuals of extreme W subpopulation of nominate subspecies exhibit intergradation towards viola in belly coloration. Proposed subspecies motaguae (from E Guatemala) is invalid, as main distinguishing characters can be ascribed to juvenile or female plumage. Subspecies devillei considered “as distinct as many recognized hummingbird species” (Howell and Webb 1995), but violet-purple vs bronzier-brown tail (score 2) and all glittering-green underparts vs glittering-green breast with greyish-cinnamon belly (2) appear to be only significant points of difference; further research desirable. Five subspecies recognized.

Previously listed as Amazilia cyanura (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), but moved to current genus following a recent overhaul of all genera by NACC, based on McGuire et al. (2014), Stiles et al. (2017a, b) and others. Closely related to S. beryllina; reports of hybridization in a small zone of sympatry in Guatemala and El Salvador seem to be unproven, and may be erroneously based on variable tail coloration of that species. In recent literature only two subspecies have been recognized, with impatiens (from Costa Rica) ignored, perhaps because only two specimens exist; morphological characters, however, indicate that it should be considered valid. Subspecies guatemalae considered “as distinct as many recognized hummingbird species” (Howell and Webb 1995), with a more purplish, less coppery back and rump and less extensive rufous in wings (these characters seem correlated) (2); specimens in NHMUK have a far more metallic green crown, but this requires confirmation; situation merits further study. Subspecies show highly disjunct distribution. Three subspecies recognized.

Taxonomic note from HBW and BirdLife International Illustrated Checklist (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), updated where necessary to reflect later taxonomic changes: Subspecies handleyi has been treated as a distinct species on basis of being “considerably larger and heavier” and “slightly darker bronze-green above” (HBW), but considered disqualified by zone of morphometric intergradation with nominate in Bocas del Toro Archipelago; genetic evidence also unfavourable to species status (Miller et al. 2011), and material in USNM shows no colour difference in plumage; however, difference in size exceptional (effect size for wing length 11.1, score 4), while narrow zone of intergradation scores 2, so species status almost achieved. Validity of subspecies fuscicaudata has been questioned, but supported by morphometric characters. Form A. bangsi is a hybrid of present species and A. rutila. Five subspecies recognized.

Taxonomic note from HBW and BirdLife International Illustrated Checklist (del Hoyo and Collar 2014), updated where necessary to reflect later taxonomic changes: Closely related to A. yucatanensis, but not, as claimed, to A. tzacatl and Amazilis amazilia alticola. Formerly listed as A. cinnamomea, but this name was unavailable. Subspecies graysoni sometimes considered a separate species, being considerably larger than other subspecies (estimated 3) and slightly darker and duskier (1). Validity of subspecies diluta has been doubted because of intergradation towards nominate. Name saturata is a synonym of corallirostris. Described form A. bangsi, known from a single Costa Rican specimen, is a hybrid of present species and A. tzacatl. Populations from Yucatán, Honduras, Nicaragua and Costa Rica, formerly attributed to nominate, are more appropriately placed in corallirostris on basis of morphology. Four subspecies recognized.
Basilinna leucotis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Hylocharis.
Tangara episcopus (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Thraupis following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Spodiornis rusticus (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Haplospiza and listed as H. rustica following  AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Islerothraupis luctuosa (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Tachyphonus and listed as T. luctuosus following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Chrysocorypha delatrii (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Tachyphonus following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

The form lambi was reassigned to Megascops asio from M. cooperi in del Hoyo and Collar (2014), however the claimed sympatry of lambi and M. cooperi (König et al. 2008) is not clear (T.S. Schulenberg in litt. 2019) and lambi is reassigned back to M. cooperi.
Ciccaba virgata (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Strix.
Asio clamator (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Pseudoscops.

Aulacorhynchus prasinus, A. wagleri, A. caeruleogularis, A. albivitta, A. cyanolaemus and A. atrogularis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as A. prasinus following  Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Pteroglossus torquatus, P. sanguineus and P. erythropygius (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as P. torquatus following SACC (2006) and a review by the BirdLife Taxonomic Working Group, and before then were split as P. torquatus, P. sanguineus and P. erythropygius following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Distinctive within the so-called “croaking group” (see R. toco). Subspecies weakly defined, intergrading where they meet. Two subspecies recognized.

Previously placed in family Accipitridae but moved to current family based on the phylogeny of Starikov and Wink (2020). Disjunct N population (El Salvador to Nicaragua) reportedly indistinguishable from South American populations, but individual variation rather marked. Three subspecies recognized.
Rupornis magnirostris (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Buteo.
Pseudastur albicollis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Leucopternis.
Sporophila torqueola and S. morelleti (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as S. torqueola following SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).
Antrostomus ridgwayi (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Caprimulgus.

Setophaga pitiayumi and S. graysoni (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously placed in the genus Parula and lumped as P. pitiayumi following AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).
Trogon elegans and T. ambiguus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as T. elegans following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).
Onychoprion fuscatus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Sterna as S. fuscata.
Hydrobates melania (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Oceanodroma.
Geranoaetus albicaudatus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Buteo.

Buteo nitidus and B. plagiatus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as B. nitidus following AOU (2006), the gender agreement of which follows David and Gosselin (2002a), and before then were placed in the genus Asturina following AOU (1998), and before then were split as A. nitida and A. plagiata following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Previously, this species was included in the genus Tetrapturus (Collette et al. 2006). It is genetically similar to the White Marlin (Kajikia albida), but represents a distinct evolutionary unit (Collette and Graves 2019).

Sometimes, erroneously, this species has been considered a synonym of the western Atlantic Scomberomorus maculatus but  it is a valid species closely related to that species, and to the other Gulf Spanish mackerel, S. concolor, (Collette and Russo 1985, Banford et al. 1999, Bayona-Vásquez et al. 2015).

A single subadult specimen (FMNH 64646) from the northeastern slopes of the Cordillera de Montecillos, Depto. Comayagua, was tentatively assigned to Bolitoglossa celaque sensu lato by McCranie and Wilson (2002), and, based on the presumed provenance of the specimen (ca 25 km NNE of the nearest locality for B. copinhorum), this specimen is tentatively referred to as B. copinhorum (Itgen et al. 2019).
Additional research is needed to determine the range extent of this species and its' systematic status (McMahan pers. comm. 2020).
Core (1936) treated Scleria tenella as a synonym of the related species Scleria verticillata Muhl. ex Willd.
P. schiedeana Nees is a tertiary wild relative of avocado, P. americana Mill. (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).

In its wild form, Capsicum frutescens L. is a primary wild relative of Tabasco pepper, the cultivated form of the species. The species is also a secondary wild relative of aji, C. baccatum L. var. pendulum (Willd.) Eshbaug, bell/chili pepper, C. annuum L. var. annuum, and habanero pepper, C. chinense Jacq., as well as a tertiary wild relative of rocoto, C. pubescens Ruiz & Pav. (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).

This species is conformed by two varieties, Capsicum annuum var. annuum which is the cultivated form and C. annuum var. glabriusculum which is the wild form. We are here assessing the later variety.

Capsicum annuum L. var. glabriusculum (Dunal) Heiser & Pickersgill is a primary wild relative of bell/chili pepper, C. annuum var. annuum (of which it is the progenitor), and Tabasco pepper, C. frutescens L., a secondary wild relative of aji, C. baccatum L. var. pendulum (Willd.) Eshbaug, and a tertiary wild relative of rocoto, C. pubescens Ruiz & Pav. Habanero pepper (Capsicum chinense) (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).

There is no taxonomic uncertainty with Zerene cesonia. It co-occurs with the California Dogface (Zerene eurydice) in certain parts of its range, but there are is no evidence of hybridization (Opler and Wright 1999).

Physalis cordata Houst. ex Mill. is a wild relative of Cape gooseberry, P. peruviana L., low ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. and tomatillo, P. philadelphica Lam. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).

Physalis gracilis Miers is a wild relative of Cape gooseberry, P. peruviana L., low ground-cherry, P. pubescens L. and tomatillo, P. philadelphica Lam. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).

Physalis pubescens L. is a secondary wild relative of Cape gooseberry, P. peruviana L., and in its wild form is a primary wild relative of low ground-cherry, the cultivated form of the species (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).

Following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006), Capsicum lanceolatum (Greenm.) C.V. Morton & Standl. is a wild relative (Taxon Group 4) of a number of pepper crops: Bell/chili pepper, C. annuum L. var. annuum, Habanero pepper, C. chinense Jacq., Tabasco pepper, C. frutescens L., Aji, C. baccatum L. var. pendulum (Willd.) Eshbaug  and Rocoto, C. pubescens Ruiz & Pav.

Following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006), Capsicum rhomboideum (Dunal) Kuntze is a wild relative (Taxon Group 4) of a number of pepper crops: Bell/chili pepper, C. annuum L. var. annuum, Habanero pepper, C. chinense Jacq., Tabasco pepper, C. frutescens L., Aji, C. baccatum L. var. pendulum (Willd.) Eshbaug, Rocoto, C. pubescens Ruiz & Pav.
Persea albida Kosterm. is a wild relative of avocado, P. americana Mill. The species is classified in Taxon Group 4, following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).
Tripsacum intermedium de Wet & J. R. Harlan is a tertiary wild relative of maize (Z. mays L. ssp. mays) (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).
Tripsacum latifolium Hitchc. is a tertiary wild relative of maize (Zea mays L. ssp. mays) (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).

Setophaga cerulea (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Dendroica following AERC TAC (2003); AOU (1998 & supplements); SACC (2005 & updates); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).

Ipomoea trifida (H.B.K.) G.Don. is a secondary wild relative of Sweet potato, Ipomoea batatas (L.) Poir (Vincent et al, 2013). It is probably one of the progenitors of Sweet Potato, Ipomoea batatas (L.) Lam. var. batatas (Nishiyama 1971, 1982). However, given the ploidy incompatibility with the cultivated Sweet Potato it is considered its secondary wild relative (Jarret et al. 1992, Jarret and Austin 1994, Rajapakse et al. 2004, Vincent et al. 2013).
En algunos listados florísticos antiguos como la Flora de Guatemala se ha considerado como sinónimo o como una forma de Aegiphila martinicensis pero es claramente una especie distinta y válida.
Esta especie está muy relacionada con Ruprechtia costaricensis.
There may be some taxonomic overlap of Centropomus armatus, C. robalito, and C. unionensis. Further taxonomic study is needed.

This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005). This is some doubt as to the taxonomic assignment of the subpopulations from Yoro and Olancho Departments, based on differences in habitat and biogeographic patterns (J. Townsend and J.M. Solís pers. comm. March 2019).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
In the Craugastor alfredi group. Craugastor cyanochthebius differs from all other species in the group by a combination of morphological characters (McCranie and Smith 2006).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
The sister taxon of, and previously confused with, Oedipina gephrya according to the original publication (Frost 2013).

Previously, this species included two subspecies: P. o. occidentalis and P. o. sonoriensis. These subspecies are now recognised as separate species: P. occidentalis and P. sonoriensis. The previous entry for P. occidentalis on the IUCN Red List (LR/nt, 1996) does not refer to the current concept of P. occidentalis as that assessment included data for both subspecies, while the current assessment refers only to the population that was previously referred to as P. o. occidentalis.
This species has been placed in the genus Sibon in the past, but was returned to Tropidodipsas by Wallach (1995).

No subspecies of the Rough-toothed Dolphin (Steno bredanensis) are currently recognized (Committee on Taxonomy 2017, 2021). However, based on genetics there is evidence of population structuring, both within and between ocean basins, and even within specific archipelagos (Oremus et al. 2012, Da Silva et al. 2015, Albertson et al. 2016). Analyses of photo-identification and satellite tag data indicate population structuring within the Hawaiian archipelago (Baird et al. 2008, Baird 2016), and similar population structuring has been identified in the Society Islands, French Polynesia, based on photo-identification data (Oremus et al. 2012). It is likely that subpopulation structure exists throughout the species’ range.

Many current publications erroneously attribute the name Steno (Delphinus) bredanensis to G. Cuvier in Lesson (1828), rather than to Lesson (1828) (Smeenk 2018), and this latter attribution is now followed by the Committee on Taxonomy (2020).
Thalasseus elegans (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Sterna.
Buteogallus solitarius (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Harpyhaliaetus.
Amazona farinosa and A. guatemalae (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as A. farinosa following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Millepora striata was synonymized under M. squarrosa by Boschma (1948), but subsequent work based on morphometric analysis of dactylopore size and density shows that M. striata is distinguishable from the other Caribbean milleporids based on morphology (de Weerdt 1984). Genetic data also supports M. striata as being distinct from M. squarrosa and the M. alcicornis–M. complanata complex (Ruiz-Ramos et al. 2014).

Sturnella magna (Sibley and Monroe 1990, 1993) and S. lilianae (Sibley and Monroe 1990, 1993) have been lumped as S. magna following AOU (1998), who note the two groups differ in plumage, morphology, and habitat preferences (Lanyon 1962; Rohwer 1972, 1976), but are quite similar in vocalizations (Lanyon 1962).
Setophaga chrysoparia (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was previously placed in the genus Dendroica following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993); Stotz et al. (1996).
Charadrius alexandrinus, C. dealbatus and C. nivosus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as C. alexandrinus following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

McGuire et al. (2019) review in detail the status of the all-white taxon occidentalis, which although formerly given species status (‘Great White Heron’ [GWH]) has long been considered a subspecies of Great Blue Heron [GBH] Ardea herodias, in great part because the two taxa interbreed with regularity. However, given that the evidence points to assortative mating where possible, they conclude that occidentalis is indeed better treated as a species.

It is separated by diagnostic plumage (white vs. blue), behavior (mate choice and timing of mating) and habitat (saltwater-island vs. fresh/brackish water mainland).

There are, in fact, a few additional morphological considerations, with GWH having a shorter occipital plume but longer bill, tarsus and middle toe than GBH (supplementary material online with measurements not accessed). Applying the Tobias criteria to the situation, the taxonomic status of GWH involves a consideration of its

·       all-white vs grey/blue plumage (an exceptional difference: score 4);
·       shorter occipital plume (seemingly fairly distinctive from the authors’ Figure 3: allow 1);
·       longer tarsus (apparently the most distinctive of the longer characters measured, but perhaps insufficient to be allowed a score: ns);
·       timing of mating or habitat choice (only one of these permitted as a score: 1);
·       narrow hybrid zone (not more than 50 km as measured on Google Earth: 2).

On this basis BirdLife accepts Ardea occidentalis (Handbook of the Birds of the World and BirdLife International 2020) as a separate species.

Chaetura vauxi (del Hoyo et al. 2014) has been split into Vaux's Swift C. vauxi, including form aphanes from NE Venezuela, and Andre's Swift C. andrei (Handbook of the Birds of the World and BirdLife International 2020) following a review of the relationships within Chaetura and investigation of the morphological characters within the group (Chesser et al. 2018).
Eupsittula canicularis (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Aratinga.
Gallinago gallinago and G. delicata (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as G. gallinago following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

Pyrocephalus rubinus, P. nanus and P. dubius (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as P. rubinus following AOU (1998 & supplements), SACC (2005 & updates), Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993) and Stotz et al. (1996).

Liogier (1996) and Acevedo-Rodriguez and Strong (2012) consider Trema domingensis Urban as endemic to Hispaniola. Zanoni and Mejia (1989) and Garcia et al. (2001) considered the species to be endemic to the Sierra de Bahoruco based on what they considered the only known specimen (Fuertes 312) collected in the Barahona Peninsula. They overlooked Ekman’s collections (Ekman 12293, Ekman 15720) collected in the Cordillera Septentrional and Cordillera Central, respectively. Peguero and Jimenez (2011) considered the species Critically Endangered and possibly extinct, though curiously the species was not published in the Dominican Republic national Red List (Ministerio de Medio Ambiente y Recursos Naturales de la Republica Dominicana, 2011).


The Dominican publications were prior to taxonomic studies by Garwood et al. (2018) that clarified the taxonomic and nomenclatural confusion regarding the species. The other entire-leaved species of the genus (T. integerrima, T. laxiflora) were placed in synonymy, thus extending the species’ distribution throughout the Neotropics, from Central America, the Caribbean and South America.

Following the review of the genus Oedipina by Brodie et al. (2012), where the presence of Oedipina salvadorensis was confirmed for El Salvador, E. Morán and V. Henríquez reviewed nine specimens of Oedipina from the departments of San Salvador and Ahuachapán, El Salvador [deposited in the El Salvador Museum of Natural History (MUNHES)].

The taxonomic characteristics of the specimens from San Salvador corresponded to those of Oedipina salvadorensis, while the specimens from the department of Ahuachapán corresponded to Oedipina taylori (V. Henríquez pers. comm. June 2019).

The taxonomy of the howlers of Mesoamerica, the Pacific coasts of Colombia and Ecuador and the Tumbes region of Northern Peru is based on Lawrence (1933), and recently revised by Cortés-Ortiz et al. (2015a). Through a comprehensive study of Mesoamerican howlers based on cranial features and pelage colouration patterns, Lawrence (1933) considered all Mesoamerican howlers to be subspecies of A. palliata, including: A. p. mexicana, A. p. palliata, A. p. aequatorialis, A. p. pigra, A. p. luctuosa, A. p. coibensis, and A. p. trabeata. Smith (1970) analysed pelage colouration patterns, and cranial and dental features of 238 specimens from across the range of A. palliata (including those studied by Lawrence, 1933) and compared them with a population sample of two sympatric forms of howler monkeys from the state of Tabasco, Mexico. He determined that the two (partially sympatric) forms from his sample constituted two well-differentiated species, and thus recommended A. pigra to be considered full species and separated from A. palliata. He considered A. p. luctuosa Lawrence, 1933 as junior synonym of A. pigra.

Froehlich and Froehlich (1986, 1987), analysed the dermal ridge patterns of howler monkeys from Nicaragua, Costa Rica, and Panama and suggested that the forms coibensis and trabeata be treated as subspecies of a distinct species, A. coibensis. Groves (2001, 2005) followed Froehlich and Froehlich and recognized A. palliata (Gray, 1849) and A. coibensis Thomas, 1902 as distinct species, but did not distinguish any subspecies.

Using mtDNA markers, Cortés-Ortiz et al. (2003) found that the Mantled Howler Monkeys from Mexico to Panama comprise a monophyletic group that is distinct from the clade of black howler monkeys (A. pigra). However, individuals from Coiba Island were found to share mitochondrial haplotypes with mantled howler monkeys from Costa Rica and Mexico, and howler monkeys from Azuero peninsula in Panama shared haplotypes with those from central and eastern Panama. In general, the divergence among mitochondrial lineages of individuals from Mexico, Costa Rica, Coiba Island, Azuero Peninsula and the rest of Panama was minimal and did not justify separating them into distinct species.

The current taxonomy of Ateles geoffroyi is based on Kellogg and Goldman (1944), Rylands et al. 2006, and Morales-Jiménez et al. (2015). Originally, detail analyses of cranial morphology and pelage colouration by Kellogg and Goldman (1944) recognized nine distinct subspecies. Hill (1962), Hall (1981), and Konstant et al. (1985) retained all these subspecies, but morphological and genetic analyses over the past two decades challenged the validity of these taxa. For example, Silva-López et al. (1996) exemplified the enormous variation in pelage colouration of Ateles in Mexico, Guatemala and Belize and concluded that A. g. pan Schlegel, 1876 and A. g. yucatanensis Kellogg and Goldman, 1944 was within the variation of A. g. vellerosus. Napier (1976) also showed that the type specimen A. g. panamensis Kellogg and Goldman, 1944 falls within the variation of A. g. ornatus, Gray, 1870 and recommended considering the former a synonym of the latter. Based on phylogenetic analyses of small fragments of mitochondrial DNA genes, Collins and Dubach (2000) recognized a northern and a southern group of spider monkeys in Central America, but due to their fragmentary sampling could not properly evaluate subspecies distinctiveness. Using ~800 bp of the mtDNA control region, Morales-Jiménez et al. (2015) analysed the phylogenetic relationships of 49 spider monkeys sampled across Central America, and concluded that individuals from Mexico, Guatemala and Belize should be considered as part of A. g. vellerosus, while individuals from El Salvador should not be included in this taxon. They also found that individuals from southwestern Nicaragua and northwestern Costa Rica should be considered as A. g. frontatus and individuals from Azuero peninsula formed a monophyletic clade, supporting their recognition as distinct subspecies. However, despite recent efforts to improve our understanding of the phylogenetic relationships of the different subspecies of A. geoffroyi, conclusive results regarding the taxonomic validity of its subspecies still require analyses that include samples of individuals from southern Guatemala, Honduras, northern and eastern Nicaragua, central and western Panama, and eastern Costa Rica. Here, we tentatively recognized six subspecies: Ateles geoffroyi geoffroyi, Ateles geoffroyi azuerensis, Ateles geoffroyi frontatus, Ateles geoffroyi grisescens, Ateles geoffroyi ornatus, Ateles geoffroyi vellerosus.

The taxonomy and distributions of Ateles geoffroyi and Ateles fusciceps was reviewed by Rylands et al. (2006). Recent molecular data has suggested that the Mesoamerican spider monkeys (Ateles geoffroyi) and spider monkeys in north-western South America (Ateles fusciceps) shared a common ancestor nearly 2.2 Mya, and that both disjunct subspecies A. f. fusciceps and A. f. rufiventris shared a common ancestor nearly 1.3 Mya (Morales-Jimenez et al. 2015b). Mitochondrial DNA sequencing strongly supports Ateles geoffroyi and Ateles fusciceps being reciprocally monophyletic taxa (Morales-Jimenez et al. 2015b).

Until recently, Central American capuchins were considered to be subspecies of Cebus capucinus; however, recent genetic analyses (Boubli et al. 2012) suggest a phylogenetic division between C. capuchinus from South America and Eastern Panama and the Central American populations with no evidence of division within the latter group.

Popularmente conhecida como Assacú, Assacú-vermelho no Acre, Assacu-preto no Amazonas, Inupupu no Pará, Assacu na região Norte, Acre, Amazonas e Pará, açacu, areeiro, uassacu, açacu-branco, açacuzeiro, árvore-do-diabo, catauá, pinho-do-norte, uaçacu, uçacu e aracu (Flora do Brasil 2020, 2020, Sabrina Queiroz de Farias, comunicação pessoal, 2020).

authority: Townsend, Herrera-B., Hofmann, Luque-Montes, Ross, Dudek, Krygeris, Duchamp & Wilson, 2020
taxonomicNotes: This is a split from the broader concept of Atlantihyla spinipollex (Townsend et al. 2020).

The use of this name has been clarified by McCranie and Wilson (1993). This species was moved from Ptychohyla to Atlantihyla (Faivovich et al. 2018). This is a restricted concept of Atlantihyla spinipollex following the split of the broader concept into this and A. melissa (Townsend et al. 2020).
Neomorphus geoffroyi (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously split as N. geoffroyi and N. squamiger following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993).

authority: Firneno, Itgen, Jacobs, Mcdaniels, Luque-Montes, Wilson & Townsend, 2021
